<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NotDeadYet     11-11 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Not Dead Yet,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmer Told At Polls That He's Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTMINSTER, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Melvin Leroy Blizzard Sr. arrived at the
polls on Election Day to find election officials thought he had
departed _ permanently.
   The records at Blizzard's polling place at the Deer Park United
Methodist Church listed the 58-year-old farmer as dead.
   ``I'm deceased,'' he said. ``They buried me back in July. Can you
beat that?''
   Blizzard said he always votes and was particularly anxious to do
so Tuesday to vote against a ballot question to retain Maryland's
new law banning the manufacture and sale of some handguns. The
referendum passed.
   So he told poll workers at the church to wait while he went to
the Carroll County Board of Election Supervisors in Westminster, the
county seat.
   ``I was mad,'' Blizzard said. ``I went in there and said, `What
in the world is going on?' I preached them a sermon up one way and
down the other.''
   Chief Clerk Pauline Kram said Blizzard's name was mistakenly
removed from the rolls when another Melvin Leroy Blizzard died last
summer. She issued him a temporary voting card.
   The living Blizzard, in fact, knew the deceased Blizzard.
   He said about 25 people called him after the other Blizzard's
obituary appeared, and he still occasionally meets acquaintances who
are surprised to find him alive.
</TEXT>
