<DOCNO> AP881111-0004 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0008EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-APArts:LiteracyDictionary     11-11 0969</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Literacy Dictionary,0993</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Books And Authors: Just What Does Every American Need To Know?
^Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   E.D. Hirsch, the University of Virginia English
professor who was about as famous as any other UVA English professor
until rocketing onto best-seller lists with his book, ``Cultural
Literacy: What Every American Needs to Know,'' is anxious these days
to avoid the charge of arrogance.
   That may be a bit harder now with the publication of his
similarly titled sequel, ``The Dictionary of Cultural Literacy: What
Every American Needs to Know'' (Houghton Mifflin, $19.95),
co-written by University of Virginia history professor Joseph F.
Kett, and James Trefil, a physics professor at George Mason
University.
   The book contains 23 chapters detailing what these scholars
believe literate Americans should know about such subjects as the
Bible, world and U.S. history, geography, the arts, science,
economics, proverbs and idioms.
   Hirsch's dictionary, however, more aptly resembles a patent drug
whose manufacturer forgot to include the warning labels.
   The subtitle, ``What Every American Needs to Know,'' might
logically lead one to suppose that this dictionary contains what one
ought to know. But Hirsch bridles at the suggestion that he would
ever be so arrogant, or as he puts it, ``prescriptive.''
   He makes a different claim for his dictionary _ more modest in
his view. The dictionary lays out, he says, the nation's common
parlance, what all of us need to know to communicate with each other
despite our ethnic or regional differences.
   ``I'm interested in what brings us together as strangers,'' he
said in a recent conversation.
   In arriving at which entries were ``common'' to Americans and
thus belonged in his dictionary, Hirsch said he and his academic
colleagues first consulted the front pages of such leading news
publications as The New York Times and The Washington Post for terms
and concepts in common usage. From there, they canvassed and quizzed
lawyers, teachers and others generally considered literate to see
which items ought to be included in the dictionary.
   The results of this winnowing process sometimes range from the
merely idiosyncratic to a sad commentary on what we Americans
consider our cultural domain.
   It includes, for example, the term ``meliorism,'' meaning a
belief that things are getting better. Knowing that may make you a
hit at a political science convention, but even the most literate of
us will probably cruise happily through life without ever uttering
that word.
   The dictionary also manages to present two sections on world
history nearly free of any suggestion that anything notable ever
occurred south of the Equator. Hirsch insisted that including such
information in this book so prescriptively titled ``What Americans
Need to Know'' would have been too ``prescriptive.''
   That half of the world does, however, get mentioned in the world
geography section.
   So what are we to make of this dictionary? It's necessary to
refer to the book's brief introduction and, more importantly, to the
earlier work that started it all.
   In April 1987, Hirsch flew to San Francisco to introduce his
original book, ``Cultural Literacy: What Every American Needs to
Know,'' to a gathering of education writers. The work featured an
audacious, 4,500-item list consisting of what he believed all
Americans should know to be considered ``culturally literate'': from
Star Wars to the Stamp Act, nouveau riche to Neanderthal man, Old
King Cole to Omar Khayyam.
   His message was clear, and it struck a chord with the book-buying
public: U.S. schools, he argued, are stressing mere mechanical
skills over content, leaving millions of Americans ignorant of the
common knowledge that make up our culture.
   To everyone's surprise, this ``where's the beef''-type challenge
to the education establishment turned this scholarly book into a
publishing sensation.
   His first book and, no doubt, his new dictionary, will continue
to be a rallying point for those who believe schools have strayed
from their central mission of teaching youngsters what the American
heritage is all about.
   We ought to be able to agree, Hirsch insists, on a body of shared
knowledge that all Americans should know. More to the point, we must
insist that schools teach it.
   ``Schools ought to decide on goals,'' he said in the interview.
``Those goals should be content goals, and not just skills goals.
They should know what kids should know at the end of first grade, or
second grade. That's completely foreign now.''
   Hirsch still receives numerous letters from teachers and others
who applaud his message. But he's also taken his share of criticism.
   The left has condemned him for omitting references to minority
groups and non-western cultures. Conservatives have said his
literacy list lets youngsters off too easily by reducing American
culture to slogans, buzzwords and maxims.
   Hirsch strongly defends the idea of listing such items: ``You
can't have a concrete proposal without a list. Not to make a list is
to be evasive.''
   But in light of all this, Hirsch's claim that his dictionary
merely describes what Americans know, rather than what they ought
to, sounds disingenuous.
   How does one account, for example, for the nearly complete
omission of the pervasive influence of television on American
culture? It might perhaps be better if young and old minds weren't
awash with ``I Love Lucy'' and J.R. Ewing, but leaving them out of
this dictionary won't make it so.
   More fundamentally, it's not at all clear that Hirsch is correct
in his central contention that there exists a ``consensus culture''
awaiting scholarly discovery, a common American cultural language
that can be distilled free of transient regional or ethnic
impurities.
   Even less clear is that any good would result from finding it,
had he succeeded in doing so.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Lee Mitgang has covered education for the AP
since 1981.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
