<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-CrankCalls     11-11 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Crank Calls,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Angry Ex-Wife Called Husband's Office 100,000 Times</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who allegedly made up to 100,000 crank calls
to her former husband since 1986 has been arrested near Tokyo, local
police said today.
   Toyoko Terahashi, 26, allegedly called her former husband at his
office, alternately yelling into the phone or saying nothing before
hanging up, according to Kawasaki Police Department spokesman
Hiroshi Katsutani.
   Katsutani said the calls began three months after the couple were
divorced in January 1986 and numbered up to 200 a day. The couple
married in May 1985.
   According to police, Ms. Terahashi's husband left her and filed
for divorce after being subjected to domestic violence. Ms.
Terahashi then began telephoning the man's office and homes of over
20 of his coworkers in an effort to find out where he was living.
   The president of the company where the man is employed filed a
complaint with the police, who found that during their
investigation, from Sept. 3 to Oct. 19, the woman called the company
753 times.
   The woman allegedly told police she initially made the calls
because she wanted to see her former husband and thought the company
was hiding him from her. Later, however, the calls were ``simply out
of spite,'' Katsutani said.
   He said that when investigators arrived at her home Thursday to
arrest her, she was yelling ``You idiot!'' into the phone.
   Ms. Terahashi confessed her monthly phone bill was over 40,000
yen ($320), and at times reached half her monthly salary, according
to the spokesman.
   Ms. Terahashi was arrested for harrassing the company and could
face up to 3 years in jail or a fine of up to 200,000 yen ($1,500).
</TEXT>
