<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0030EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Maldives-Image     11-11 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Maldives-Image,0707</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paradise Lost: Lush Islands Reel From Violent Coup Attempt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MALE, Maldives (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An abrupt burst of violence has left deep
scars in this otherwise peaceful paradise, a land where only two
murders have been reported this century.
   The Maldives, a group of about 2,000 coral islands in the Indian
Ocean, is better known for its picture-postcard beaches and secluded
resorts than for foreign mercenaries battling soldiers in the
streets.
   But the islands' image underwent a brutal overhaul on Nov. 3,
when hired gunmen from Sri Lanka tried unsuccessfully to overthrow
President Maumoon Abdul Gayoom.
   ``Maldives has been catapulted into the 20th century,'' said A.K.
Banerjee, India's top diplomat on the islands.
   The attempt to oust Gayoom was thwarted by the arrival of Indian
paratroopers, but at least a dozen people were killed in Male, the
capital, and at least six more died on a ship hijacked by escaping
mercenaries.
   The Indian paratroopers have begun withdrawing from the country
after their quick success but some remain as a token force,
controlling the jetty on Male and the international airport on
nearby Hulule island.
   A week after the fighting, soldiers of the Maldivian National
Security Service, the country's 1,200-man militia, continue to
patrol the narrow, unpaved streets of Male island.
   The militia's coast guard speedboats constantly monitor movements
off anchored ships.
   Gayoom lives under heavy guard at the Security Service
headquarters, and civilians are barred from moving in front of the
three-story white building.
   Before the coup attempt, Gayoom's chauffeur-driven car moved
freely along the streets of the capital without bodyguards, said a
resident who spoke on condition of anonymity. Now he is accompanied
by bodyguards, and the streets are cleared in advance.
   The militia headquarters bore the brunt of the mercenaries'
attacks. The building's front is chipped by bullets, windows are
shattered and a huge hole was knocked into its 30-foot boundary wall
by a rocket-propelled grenade.
   ``The effect of the coup will last,'' said Sajida Mohammed, a
19-year-old girl who said she'd never seen a dead person until the
fighting. She lives down the street from the presidental palace and
said fighting raged outside her one-story brick house for more than
10 hours.
   The people of Male, most government employees or fishermen,
gathered to stare at the Indian paratroopers in red berets,
camouflage uniforms and black army boots.
   ``They are not hostile, but you can sense their disapproval,''
said an Indian major. ``I think they don't like violence.''
   Ismail Mohammad, a law student, said he could find records of
only two murders in the islands in this century. ``One was by a West
German tourist who killed his girlfriend on a resort,'' he said. ``I
don't remember the other but know that a fisherman was killed.''
   The German was convicted a few years ago and banished to a remote
island where he married a Maldivian woman.
   Banishment has been the customary punishment for crimes, but the
mercenaries could face the death sentence, Gayoom told a news
conference this week.
   Tourism brings in about $10.5 million a year in the
Maldives.About 120,000 tourists, mostly from Western Europe and
Japan, visit the islands annually.
   Gayoom was unconcerned about the long-term effects of the coup.
Asked if the trouble could affect tourism, the islands' largest
industry after fishing, he said: ``It could get better after the
exposure we have received in the international press.''
   Sources in the Maldivian government, however, said the security
of the islands would now be a priority.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Gayoom
would discuss the situation with foreign delegations visiting Male
on Friday for the ceremony installing him as president for a third
five-year term.
   Delegations from the United States, India and Sri Lanka are to
attend, they said.
   Gayoom was re-elected Sept. 23. As is customary in the Maldives,
a former hereditary sultanate that became independent from Britain
in 1965, he was the only candidate and the ballot was a yes-or-no
vote. Ninety-five percent of the ballots said ``yes.''
</TEXT>
