<DOCNO> AP881111-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0036EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Teitelbaum     11-11 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teitelbaum,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Who Ordered Lawyer to Use Husband's Name Steps Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge who aroused controversy last
summer by ordering a female attorney to use her husband's last name
in his courtroom says he is stepping down as an active trial judge.
   ``I'm 73 years old and I think it's about time I ease up my trial
schedule,'' said U.S. District Judge Hubert Teitelbaum, who's been a
federal judge since 1971.
   Teitelbaum said Thursday his decision had nothing to do with his
order last July forbidding attorney Barbara Wolvovitz to use her
maiden name during a civil trial in his courtroom.
   ``I conferred with the court and did this on my own volition and
not because of anything connected with Ms. Wolvovitz,'' he said.
   The judge had threatened to jail Ms. Wolvovitz for refusing his
order. He later apologized and rescinded his order after outraged
women's groups sought his resignation.
   The controversy also helped prompt an investigation by the local
bar association into sexism in the courtroom.
   Teitelbaum said he notified Chief U.S. District Judge Maurice
Cohill three weeks ago that he was stepping down as an active trial
judge and transferring most of his cases to other judges.
   Teitelbaum said he would retain his courtroom and hear social
security cases and routine constitutional appeals in criminal cases.
</TEXT>
