<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0039EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugAgentSlain     11-11 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Agent Slain,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexican Policeman Convicted In Camarena Murder Gets 15 More Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Mexican policeman sentenced to 240
years in prison for a drug agent's murder has been given another 15
years for conspiring to kill a fictitious customs agent.
   U.S. District Judge Pamela Ann Rymer pronounced sentence on Raul
Lopez Alvarez, 29, and two co-defendants Thursday, but not without
criticizing the prosecution for a case that ``pushes the conspiracy
theory to its ultimate.''
   She imposed sentences far lower than what prosecutors had
recommended.
   Lopez, once a member of the Guadalajara police homicide squad,
was convicted last month along with two Mexican drug traffickers in
the 1985 murder of U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration Agent
Enrique Camarena.
   Before that trial began, Lopez was convicted in the conspiracy
case that stemmed from a government sting operation tied to the
Camarena investigation.
   An undercover agent posing as a drug dealer lured Lopez to the
United States, ostensibly to obtain information for the Camarena
probe, then conducted lengthy videotaped conversations with him.
   The tapes were the key government evidence in both trials. During
the talks, Lopez discussed details of Camarena's torture murder and
agreed to murder a customs agent at the request of the man he
thought was a drug dealer.
   According to evidence at the trial, Lopez subsequently recruited
Fabian Jiminez Martinez, 23, and Carlos Quintero Maldonado, 26, who
traveled with him from Mexico to participate in the planned
kidnapping, torture and murder of a customs agent invented by the
government.
   ``By the sound of it, it is hard to imagine a more serious
crime,'' said the judge. But she noted ``there is no evidence that
any official of the United States was in any danger at all.''
   As a result, she said, she could not impose the 30- to 40-year
sentences sought by Assistant U.S. Attorney Jimmy Gurule.
   She ordered Lopez' 15-year sentence to run concurrently with the
240 years he was sentenced to in the Camarena case.
   Jimenez and Quintero were sentenced to 10 years each and will be
eligible for parole after serving a third of their sentences.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
