<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Non-Campaign     11-11 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Non-Campaign,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Veteran Mayor Doesn't Campaign, As Usual; Wins, As Usual</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RACINE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raymond Thompson, mayor of this southern
Minnesota town for more than a dozen years, spent the weeks before
the Tuesday election doing what he always does when his term nears
its end: nothing.
   As usual, he didn't file for re-election, he didn't campaign and
he didn't even bother to find out who won. When he got home about
9:30 p.m. from a deer hunting trip to northern Minnesota, he went to
bed.
   As usual, he won.
   City Clerk Shirley Wiles called first thing Wednesday to tell
Thompson he had been swept back into office with a landslide 111
write-in votes. That's in a town with 310 residents, ``including
people and dogs,'' Thompson said.
   The mayor, who owns Thompson Livestock in Racine, ran and was
elected for office once many years ago. After that, he figured if
the people wanted him, they could write him in. If someone else
wants the job, according to his philosophy, let that person have it.
   But someone else has not come forward, so Thompson keeps getting
elected. By his account, he has been mayor for either six or seven
two-year terms.
   Not running has its merits, Thompson said.
   ``I don't promise them (anything), so I don't have to fulfill''
anything, he said.
   And election night party expenses are kept to a minimum.
   ``You don't have a celebration when you're not running,'' he said.
   Now that he's mayor again, Thompson said he plans to do what he's
done before in the job, which pays him $750 a year. He'll keep the
city council ``on the straight and narrow.''
</TEXT>
