<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NuclearPacemaker     11-11 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Pacemaker,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nuclear-Powered, Dual-Chamber Pacemaker More Comfortable, Lasts
Longer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors say a new nuclear powered,
dual-chamber pacemaker implanted in a patient for the first time is
more comfortable than its predecessor and can last twice as long as
those currently in use.
   John Sniffen, 47, of Clifton became the first person in the world
to use the device, according to Newark's Beth Israel Medical Center,
where the 90-minute operation was performed Tuesday.
   The new pacemaker, powered by plutonium, lasts from 20 to 40
years, while a similar lithium battery-powered dual-chamber
pacemaker developed in 1974 must be replaced every five to eight
years, said Dr. Victor Parsonnet, who performed the operation.
   Though nuclear pacemakers have been available for 15 years, they
are of the single-chamber design, which is less comfortable than the
dual-chamber design that imitates the heart's two-step rhythm,
Parsonnet said Thursday at a news conference.
   When the heart beats, its lower part squeezes blood into the
upper chamber, where a second squeeze sends the blood into the rest
of the body.
   The new device, called a Pulsar-N1, alternately jolts the two
chambers with electrical impulses, adapting to the patient's rate of
activity, Parsonnet said.
   Single-chamber nuclear pacemakers, which last about 16 years,
only stimulate the lower chamber of the heart and their action can
be felt by the patient, he said.
   Sniffen, who was listed in good condition, told reporters he felt
``happy to be alive and to be the first recipient of this newest
generation of pacemakers.''
   Wearing a white daisy in his bathrobe lapel, he said that the
single-chamber, nuclear-powered pacemaker he received in 1975 made
him feel ``jolts every once in a while and (I) was totally aware of
it.''
   ``Now I feel good. A little weak from the operation, but other
than that, it's real nice,'' he said.
   Sniffen, a photocopying and facsimile machine salesman, suffers
from intermittent heart block, which makes the heart stop
occasionally and can cause fainting.
   The Pulsar-N1, an oblong device about 2{ inches wide and an inch
thick, is placed between the skin and the muscle of the chest wall.
Two wires are threaded through a vein to the heart, where they are
attached to the upper and lower chambers.
   Parsonnet said that with its greater longevity, the new device
can eliminate the need for replacement operations, reducing the
physical and emotional stress on the patient and saving money.
   ``Theoretically, this pacemaker will last a lifetime,'' said
Parsonnet, who helped implant the first American-made,
single-chamber nuclear powered pacemaker in 1973.
   Patients also can avoid exposure to the X-rays required to locate
the pacemaker each time it has to be replaced, said David L. Purdy,
president of Biocontrol Technology, the Indiana, Pa., company that
manufactures the device.
   The new pacemaker has its drawbacks, however.
   Hospitals must be licensed to implant the devices and patients
have to be registered with the Nuclear Regulatory Commission to use
them, even though experts say they present no radiation danger.
   The device also costs more _ about $6,000 compared with its
$4,500 lithium counterpart. It is also bigger and weighs more.
   ``The major issue is the paperwork and the size,'' Purdy said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
