<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HotelFire     11-11 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hotel Fire,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historic Hotel, Now Empty, Burns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A seven-alarm fire Thursday night ripped
through a historic hotel that was being torn down, and authorities
said they suspected arson.
   There were no reports of injuries.
   Concord Fire Chief Richard Judkins labeled the fire in the
140-room, wooden Highway Hotel ``extremely suspicious.''
   Judkins said people were seen fleeing the area as the fire broke
out, and he noted that electricity to the hotel had been shut off
since it was sold and closed in September.
   The fire broke out about 8:15 p.m. Judkins said it was under
control by 11 p.m.
   Dozens of people gathered to watch in parking lots of nearby
shopping centers and along Interstate 93, which passes by the front
of the hotel.
   The hotel, built in 1951, was a center for political gatherings
in the lead-off presidential primary state. Among those who slept,
ate and headquartered their campaigns at the Highway Hotel were
President Reagan, former Presidents Kennedy, Nixon and Ford, Gov.
Nelson Rockefeller and Sen. Robert F. Kennedy.
   The hotel was being demolished to make way for a shopping center.
Its rooms had been gutted and windows removed, but the building
still stood when the fire broke out.
</TEXT>
