<DOCNO> AP881111-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0104EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     11-11 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Rebel Sees Little Chance For Contra Aid; New Rebel Group
Formed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Nicaraguan rebel says there's
no chance that President-elect George Bush will renew U.S. military
aid for the Contras trying to oust the leftist Sandinista government.
   ``I don't see any future'' for military aid to the U.S.-supported
rebels, said Horacio Arce, who himself abandoned rebel ranks in
September under an amnesty declared by the Sandinistas.
   Arce said Thursday that many rebel military leaders feared well
before the election that opposition to Contra aid in the
Democratic-controlled Congress would continue no matter who won
Tuesday's U.S. election.
   Arce, 33, was known as Commander Mercenario among the Contras,
who have waged a civil war to oust the Sandinistas since 1981. He
said he commanded Contra forces along Nicaragua's Atlantic coast and
the northern border with Honduras.
   In another development, an unsigned communique issued late
Thursday in San Jose, the Costa Rican capital, announced the
formation of a new Nicaraguan rebel organization opposed to a truce
between the Contras and Sandinistas.
   The communique said the group, called the Central American
Democratic Revolutionary Alliance, opposed the cease-fire pact it
said was agreed to by ``reactionary and fascist sectors'' of the
Contra leadership last March.
   ``We commit ourselves to bury forever the Sandinista tyranny,''
the communique said.
   Talks on a definitive truce in the civil war broke down in
September, and each side has accused the other of cease-fire
violations.
   A rebel source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
alliance encompassed a faction of rebel fighters unhappy with the
standoff between the Sandinistas and the political leadership of the
Contras' Nicaraguan Resistance organization.
   His comments could not be immediately confirmed with other rebel
officials.
   In July, seven field commanders claiming to represent 2,700
fighters on Nicaragua's southern front along Costa Rica broke from
the resistance after Enrique Bermudez, the rebel military chief, was
elected to the Contra ruling body.
   The seven commanders denounced Bermudez's election as an attempt
by ``the extreme right'' to gain control of the rebel movement.
   U.S. military aid to the rebels expired Feb 29. Contras who fled
to Honduras afterwards are drawing funds from a humanitarian aid
package.
   Arce said he believed 3,000 to 3,500 rebels were in Honduras when
he abandoned the Contra cause in September.
   Bush has indicated resumption of military assistance would be a
high priority of his administration. Wilfredo Montalvan, a member of
the Contras' political directorate, said this week the rebels would
demand an early military aid commitment from the president-elect.
   President Daniel Ortega said ``it wouldn't be strange'' if Bush
requested more military aid for the Contras but renewed his call for
bilateral talks to resolve protracted problems between the two
nations.
</TEXT>
