<DOCNO> AP881111-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0130EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FederalPay     11-11 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federal Pay,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Criticizes Congress For Reluctance To Raise Federal
Salaries</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is reluctant to raise its pay and that
of judges and other top federal employees because voters unhappy
with such increases often make legislators pay at the polls, says
one congressman supporting an increase.
   ``Members find it excruciatingly difficult to vote on pay
raises,'' Rep. Vic Fazio, D-Calif., told a presidential commission.
``We know our constituents often earn far less than us.''
   Fazio had no formal opposition Tuesday as he won election to a
sixth term, but he said his constituents still will be unhappy with
his support of a pay increase.
   ``My appearance here kicks off my opponent's next campaign,
whoever he or she is,'' joked Fazio, speaking Thursday to the panel,
known formally as the President's Quadrennial Commission on
Executive, Legislative and Judicial Salaries.
   Although no figures have been announced, the commission is likely
to approve higher pay rates next month and the raises for members of
Congress may be linked to a recommendation that outside income _
honoraria _ be eliminated.
   If President Reagan endorses the proposals in his Jan. 9 budget,
the raises would automatically take effect within 30 days unless
both the House and Senate pass resolutions of disapproval.
   By law, the commission meets after each presidential election. It
held a special session in 1986 and recommended raising congressional
salaries from $77,400 a year to $135,000, a 74 percent boost. Reagan
approved a pay raise to $89,500, the current level.
   The pay of other top officials is pegged to that level. For
example, federal judges are also paid $89,500, while federal appeals
court judges make $95,000 and Supreme Court members are paid
$110,700. The chief justice is paid $115,000.
   Fazio agreed with Howard Baker, the former Senate Republican
leader, that Congress has a difficult time approving pay hikes
because of the possible repercussions from voters.
   Having Congress vote on its own salary ``is the granddaddy
conflict of interest of all times,'' Baker said. ``You've got an
electorate that loves to take a bite out of your leg ... there's
nothing that's closer to home than examining the pay of public
officials.''
   Former Chief Justice Warren Burger told the panel the salary cap
has made it difficult for the federal judiciary to retain judges.
   ``Many highly qualified, fine people have declined appointments
to federal courts'' because they can make far more money in private
practice, Burger told the panel.
   ``There are very few judges who are not making less today than in
the last year of their practice, even if they have been on the bench
20, 25 years,'' he said. Many judges appointed at a young age later
resign when they have children in college because they need to make
more money, he said.
   He suggested that federal judges be paid $150,000. ``This would
stop this drain of talent,'' Burger said.
   Baker agreed. ``I am well aware that most Americans would not see
a $60,000 or $70,000 job as compelling evidence of a vow of
poverty,'' he said. ``But when a federal judge makes less money than
a young attorney just out of law school, it seems to me we have
turned our values upside down.''
   Burger was also supported by the American Bar Association, whose
president, Robert Raven, said there is a ``looming crisis'' because
of the salary cap.
   An ABA survey found that 28 percent of the current federal judges
are considering leaving their jobs because they can make far more
money in private law practice, Raven said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
