<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FirstChoice Bjt   11-11 0734</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-First Choice, Bjt,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: James Baker Gets What He Wants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fred Barnes, an astute political analyst, calls
James A. Baker ``Mr. Shmooze'' and describes him in a recent profile
in New Republic magazine as America's most overrated man.
   Barnes acknowledges that Baker was a capable White House chief of
staff and a skillful campaign operative. ``But,'' Barnes says, ``he
has mastered the cynical trick of identifying himself with successes
and disassociating himself from blunders.''
   Barnes cited Baker's timing in signing on as chief of George
Bush's 1988 campaign just as it was about to surge and avoiding
blame for a big tax increase and lack of success in trimming the
trade deficit as treasury secretary.
   The writer also raised questions about the briefing books
prepared for Jimmy Carter in his 1980 debate with Ronald Reagan that
mysteriously fell into the hands of Reagan's campaign team.
   The appellation ``Mr. Shmooze'' refers to the smooth Texan's
careful cultivation of reporters who nearly uniformly give him high
marks for judgment. Barnes thinks if Bush, who was managed by his
friend Baker, had not dropped out of the 1980 Republican campaign he
might have wrested the presidential nomination from Reagan that year.
   All that and current campaign sleaze allegations aside, Baker, if
confirmed by the Senate as the 61s secretary of state, will have the
advantage of extremely close ties to the president. ``He will hit
the ground running,'' said George P. Shultz, who has been in the job
for more than six years.
   Bush gave Baker a quick start by selecting him more than two
months before the new administration takes over. Next Tuesday, Baker
is expected to be at the State Department to begin transition
discussions and to start learning the job.
   His background in foreign policy is limited. He has never been to
the Soviet Union or to the Middle East, with the exception of Saudi
Arabia. His views on U.S. relations with Moscow and on the
Israeli-Arab dispute are unknown.
   His political skills are not.
   Baker played a key and possibly critical role in 1981 in winning
the Senate's approval for the Saudis to purchase advanced radar
planes from the United States. The vote was 52-48. Baker offered
vague legal assurances that Israel's security would be safeguarded
in order to entice a handful of wavering Republicans to the White
House's side.
   It was one of the few arms sales battles any administration has
managed to win over Israel's supporters.
   Baker is experienced in international economics, has traveled to
17 countries and regularly attended National Security Council
meetings at the White House as Reagan's chief of staff and as
treasury secretary.
   The skills of persuasion with which he is credited by Barnes and
other political observers could be a valuable asset in diplomacy.
Personal relations often smooth the way for strategic objectives.
   But clearly Baker's biggest asset is his close tie to Bush, who
will be in charge of foreign policy. Baker should not have any
problems figuring out what the boss has in mind. Nor is he likely to
be harassed by the White House or National Security Council.
   The three-quarters of a mile from the State Department to the
White House has seemed a much greater distance to some recent
secretaries of state.
   At work in their office on the seventh floor, they sometimes had
to wonder what sort of advice the president was getting from the NSC
or from White House staffers.
   Cyrus Vance frequently clashed over policy with Zbigniew
Brzezinski, who was President Jimmy Carter's security adviser. The
disagreements contributed to Vance's decision to resign in April
1980, although the main reason was Carter's attempt to rescue
American hostages through an unworkable military operation.
   Henry Kissinger had no such problem. Under President Richard
Nixon and, for a while under President Gerald Ford, he held the dual
jobs of secretary of state and security adviser. Kissinger wasn't in
the habit of disagreeing with himself.
   Baker's ability to get along with people will help him. Besides,
the chances are he would work well with the two men who apparently
are the leading candidates for the NSC job: Brent Scowcroft, who
held it under Ford, and Winston Lord, the U.S. ambassador to China.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Schweid has covered diplomacy for The
Associated Press since 1973.
</TEXT>
