<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     11-11 0923</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0961</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two days after TV talk-show host Phil Donahue
took on women wrestlers, Geraldo Rivera isn't making any bones about
having his nose broken in a brawl on today's edition of his
syndicated show, ``Geraldo.''
   In the show, taped in New York on Nov. 3, a fight broke out
between black activists and representatives of a professed racist
organization. Rivera was hit with a chair and his nose is broken
when he tried to stop the free-for-all.
   In what is being advertised as an ``unprecedented'' move, Rivera
has taped a special introduction for today's ``Geraldo'' installment:
   ``As most of you already know, and as you can see by the way I
look right now, today's program on `Young Hatemongers' came to an
unexpectedly violent conclusion,'' Rivera says. ``Parents, be
advised that the language and violence contained makes this show
inappropriate for small children.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After three years in the making, a record
album saluting American soldiers has been completed in time for
Veterans Day thanks to help from some top musicians and singers,
including Dolly Parton's sister Stella Parton and instrumentalists
Mark O'Connor and Bela Fleck.
   Singer Bobby Ross, a former member of the 101st Airborne Division
at Fort Campbell, Ky., performs tunes like ``Finally Welcomed
Home,'' ``Saigon State of Mind,'' ``Too Close to the Line'' and ``No
Home for the Brave (in the Land of the Free).''
   Parton did background vocals for the LP, ``Voice of America.''
O'Connor, a finalist this year for Country Music Association
musician of the year, played fiddle and mandolin. Fleck, of the
group New Grass Revival, played banjo.
   ``Mark O'Connor said he was doing this so there wouldn't be
another Vietnam,'' said Don Hoffman, a Navy veteran who spearheaded
the project.
   Country stars George Strait, Ricky Skaggs, Rosanne Cash, Rodney
Crowell and Sharon White are on the board of directors of a
non-profit corporation administering a scholarship fund being
created from the album's proceeds, Hoffman said. The scholarships
will go to descendants of Americans killed in wars.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Violinist Isaac Stern will be the honorary
chairman of a committee to hand out awards named after opera great
Marian Anderson and aimed at furthering the careers of young
American singers.
   The Marian Anderson Celebration Committee will seek to raise
$500,000 for a permanent fund to finance the annual awards. Seed
money of $25,000 has been provided by the Greater Danbury Arts
Council, the Charles Ives Center for the Arts announced Thursday.
   Other members of the committee include Harry Belafonte, Lloyd
Richards, Kitty Carlisle Hart, and Vladmir and Wanda Toscanini
Horowitz.
   Anderson, who has lived in Danbury since she retired in 1945, was
the first black opera star to perform at the Metropolitan Opera in
New York and sang at the inaugurations of Franklin D. Roosevelt and
John F. Kennedy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James A. McGowan, a paraplegic who gained
national attention with his failed attempt to swim the English
Channel in 1986, has been named executive director of a beleaguered
charity that tries to fulfill the dreams of seriously ill children.
   Until recently the assistant director of Temple University's
Office of Disabled Student Services, McGowan, 56, accepted the job
with the Philadelphia-based Sunshine Foundation last week.
   The multimillion-dollar charity was founded by William Sample, a
former Philadelphia police officer. A state investigation has
criticized Sample's handling of $34,000 of the fund's money. The
charity also faces a deficit estimated at $725,000.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The makers of ``The Karate Kid Part III'' are
looking for a new challenger for star Ralph Macchio, but they say
you've got to be young, tough and handsome.
   More than 2,000 hopefuls are expected to try out in open
auditions to be held Saturday in New York and Los Angeles.
   The new male challenger must look no older than 18, be muscular
and athletic, and have a knowledge of boxing, wrestling or karate,
the producers said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maestro Lorin Maazel has filled the void
created by the departure of Andre Previn from the Pittsburgh
Symphony Orchestra four years ago.
   Maazel made his debut Thursday night as music director of the
100-member orchestra, which he first joined in his teens as a
full-time violinist and apprentice conductor.
   ``I enjoy being here. I am an American and I feel my place is in
this country even though I've conducted so much abroad,'' said
Maazel, 58.
   Maazel's appearance Thursday night was his first public act as
the symphony's music director. He had been serving since 1984 as the
orchestra's music consultant.
   Symphony officials are counting on Maazel to be the orchestra's
ticket to greater international recognition and financial success.
The symphony projects a loss in 1987-88 of $1.5 million, its largest
ever.
   Maazel formerly was director of the Vienna State Opera, and for
10 years before that was with the Cleveland Orchestra.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer John Cougar Mellencamp has failed in an
attempt to regain publishing rights to songs he sold 11 years ago
when he was a struggling rock 'n' roller.
   The singer had sued Riva Music Ltd. in a federal court in
Manhattan, saying its president, William Gaff, agreed to sell back
the songs for $3 million.
   But the court recently rejected Mellencamp's contention that Gaff
shook hands on the deal, noting that such agreements are normally
put on paper.
   The native of Seymour, Ind., sold the songs when he was known as
Johnny Cougar.
</TEXT>
