<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     11-11 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHESAPEAKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oinker the pig isn't very choosy about
eating a day's worth of cookies, doughnuts, chewing gum and grain,
but when it comes to soft drinks, don't waste his time by offering
Coca-Cola.
   The swine took the Pepsi challenge, and his mind is made up.
   ``He can drink about a six-pack a day,'' said Oinker's owner,
12-year-old Randy ``Cool'' Proffitt, whose father, Woody, runs the
35-acre Dunn Rovin' Stables where Oinker lives.
   One day at the stables, Randy gave Oinker a can of Coke. The pig
took one taste and flipped the can to the dirt with his snout before
going to the Pepsi can and chugging it, Randy said.
   Other soft drinks have been offered since then, but Oinker
remains loyal.
   ``He won't drink nothing but Pepsi,'' Randy said. ``No orange, no
Dr Pepper. Just Pepsi.''
   It all began when folks who bought a drink from the stable's soda
machine would offer Oinker a swig. Now, it's a regular habit for the
4-month-old, 150-pound porker.
   ``If he hears money go into the machine now, he'll go right to
the machine,'' Randy's father said. ``And, of course, you better
give him some or he'll aggravate you to death.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COSTA MESA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials, barring goats from Goat
Hill, have ordered a family to get rid of their billy named Barney.
   Angela Raj Kumar said her family has been ordered to move Barney
Jr., a 3-foot tall, 80-pound miniature pygmy goat, because their
Goat Hill home is not zoned for livestock.
   The family contends Barney is a pet, not a goat, and has full run
of the house. In fact, Ms. Raj Kumar said, Barney thinks he's a dog.
   ``He does everything with the dogs,'' Ms. Raj Kumar said. ``We
even take him for walks on the Back Bay without a leash. He plays
just like a dog. We give him baths just like a dog.''
   ``A goat is a goat,'' said city Animal Control Officer Robert
O'Brien. ``A pygmy is just a smaller goat. If you let livestock
animals in the neighborhoods, it would smell like old MacDonald's
farm every time the breeze turned toward you.''
   The dispute arose in September when one of Ms. Raj Kumar's
neighbors complained about Barney.
   After being told to get rid of the goat, Ms. Raj Kumar collected
25 signatures on a petition. She presented the papers to City
Council this week.
   ``A lot of them (petition signers) said, `Oh, you have a goat? I
didn't even know,''' Ms. Raj Kumar said. ``And we've had him almost
three years.''
   Barney Jr. spends most of his time in the family's back yard with
a few chickens and a couple of dogs. He's quiet and doesn't small
bad.
   ``He's cheaper to feed than the dogs,'' said Ms. Raj Kumar.
``Plus, he helps me keep the lawn down. I never have to mow.''
</TEXT>
