<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     11-11 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Vacations in Florida; Devotes Some Time to Planning
Administration</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Transition Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GULF STREAM, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush is spending his first days
as president-elect on a fishing, golf and tennis vacation, while
aides back in Washington work on the transition that will put his
administration in the White House next year.
   As he arrived at the West Palm Beach airport Thursday night, Bush
said the transition effort ``couldn't be going better'' in answer to
a reporter's shouted question.
   The president-elect was upbeat as he arrived in the balmy beach
community where he and his wife Barbara were met by Gov. Bob
Martinez. Bush said he was feeling ``great.''
   Asked about a morning meeting wih the leaders of his transition
team, Craig Fuller and Robert Teeter, Bush laughingly said it had
been ```absolutely fantastic'' and then disappeared into his
limousine.
   He is staying at the vacation home of friend William Stamps
Farish III, a 49-year-old multimillionaire who made his fortune in
the oil business. The home is located in the exclusive community of
Gulf Stream near Delray Beach.
   Bush was accompanied by his press spokesman Steve Hart and two
other aides, but none of his transition or campaign advisers.
However, the president-elect was expected to conduct some business
by telephone and told reporters Wednesday that he would spend time
considering cabinet appointments.
   But aides insisted that this vacation was intended for rest and
relaxation after a grueling campaign.
   ``He's very interested in relaxation time,'' Hart said.
   Bush brought his fishing pole and golf clubs along and told
reporters earlier he intended to do some surf fishing and fly
fishing.
   Bush also enjoys jogging and tennis. But Hart told reporters not
to expect much in the way of reports or photo opportunities of the
president-elect's activities.
   On Thursday, Bush met with President Reagan and the Cabinet and
attended the president's briefings with his national security
adviser and his chief of staff.
   At the cabinet meeting, Bush and Reagan received warm applause as
they entered together. Reagan, however, reminded his department
heads, ``We are still in charge until Jan. 20 and are still
responsible for making decisions of the government.''
   The president asked the appointed members of his administration
to submit their resignations to smooth the way for Bush to select
his own team.
   Bush also met Thursday with leaders of an organization of
Afghanistan rebels, Hart said.
   Bush told the chairman of the Afghan Alliance, Burhannudin
Rabbani, that he would support their efforts toward total withdrawal
of Soviet troops and self-determination, but did not pledge any
specific monetary or other support, according to Hart.
</TEXT>
