<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0148EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-Bush Bjt   11-11 0761</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Bush, Bjt,0782</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bases, Debt, Marcos, Suspicion Of Bush Top U.S.-Philippine Agenda</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Debt relief and the future of U.S.
military bases will top Manila's agenda with George Bush but
suspicions remain about the president-elect because of his past
support for Ferdinand Marcos.
   Also, President Corazon Aquino is a friend of defeated
presidential candidate Michael Dukakis from the years when she and
her late husband, Benigno Aquino Jr., lived in the Boston suburb of
Newton.
   Filipino politicians and influential political commentators made
no secret of their belief that the Massachusetts governor would have
been more sympathetic to Philippine interests, especially from the
daunting $28 billion foreign debt inherited from ousted President
Marcos.
   But Mrs. Aquino said she looked forward to working with Bush and
his new administration.
   ``I think that for my part, I can work with President Bush, with
the Bush administration, and I hope that he has seen what we have
done here as far as restoration of democracy is concerned,'' she
said.
   Bush's image in Manila has been largely defined by remarks during
a visit to the Philippines in 1981. During a dinner speech, the vice
president effusively praised Marcos for his ``adherence to
democratic principles.''
   Bush is widely perceived as one of the last major figures in the
Reagan administration to abandon Marcos before he fled to Hawaii in
the February 1986 popular uprising that toppled his 20-year
administration and propelled Mrs. Aquino to power.
   As a sign of that suspicion, numerous commentators have
speculated that Bush may quash racketeering indictments in New York
City against Marcos and his wife Imelda.
   ``The Aquino camp is reported worried about the fact that
President-elect Bush, like outgoing President Reagan, is close to
the exiled Marcos couple in Hawaii,'' wrote columnist Ariel Bocobo
in The Manila Standard.
   ``Speculation in local political circles goes that Reagan, or
eventually Bush himself, may call off all indictments against the
Marcoses in the U.S. and give them a presidential pardon.''
   U.S. diplomats in Manila have repeatedly sought to assure the
Filipino public that judicial moves against Marcos will not be
influenced by politics and that Washington's support for Mrs. Aquino
is bipartisan.
   U.S. diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, say Filipino
suspicions of Bush would be mollified if the new administration
makes good on President Reagan's promise last month of a
multinational aid package for the country's sluggish economy.
   Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus told reporters that prospects
for such a plan may have brightened since Bush has promised to
continue Reagan foreign policy.
   Commentator Amando Doronila said Bush's naming of former Treasury
Secretary James Baker as his new secretary of state indicates ``a
closer integration of the Third World debt issue in the conduct of
U.S. foreign policy.''
   Doronila, writing in The Manila Chronicle, noted Baker, as
treasury secretary, authored the ``Baker Plan'' for U.S. policy
regarding Third World debt. The plan called for restructuring
interest payments and providing new loans for debt servicing,
something Manila has sought from creditor banks.
   Philippine debt is politically entwined with the contentious
issue of the six U.S. military bases, the keystone to American
military power in the Western Pacific.
   The lease on those installations, including Clark Air Base and
the Subic Bay naval base, expires in September 1991. Any extension
must be under a formal treaty ratified by two-thirds of the
23-member Senate, where opposition to the bases is strong.
   U.S. diplomats say they would like to begin preliminary talks on
a new treaty by mid-1989, to allow time for negotiations and for
ratification by both nations' senates by the 1991 deadline.
   A recent review of the current agreement took nearly seven months
to complete, and U.S. diplomats believe negotiations on an entirely
new treaty could drag for more than a year.
   A recent public opinion survey by Ateneo University found about
75 percent of the 1,200 respondents favored retaining the bases.
   But opposition is strong among small but influential groups in
the intelligentsia and the media. Diplomats believe those groups
could sway public opinion away from the bases if Washington's moves
on debt relief and other issues disappoint Filipinos.
   ``Bush may only make America's domination of our country, its
officials bullying ours, more obvious,'' wrote the nationally
circulated newspaper Malaya. ``Americans and their presidents are
expected always to look only after their own interests. It behooves
us to look only after ours.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Reid, based in Manila, has been
Philippines bureau chief of The Associated Press since 1986.
</TEXT>
