<DOCNO> AP881111-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0302EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nigeria     11-11 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nigeria,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sultan Who Caused Riots To Be Installed After Order Restored</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nigerian officials say they will install a
Moslem sultan, whose appointment this week caused violent riots that
killed 10 people, when calm returns to the country.
   Col. Ahmed Daku, military governor of northwestern Sokoto State,
told reporters those disputing the selection of Ibrahim Dasuki to
succeed Sadiq Abubakar should take the matter to court.
   As sultan, Abubakar for 50 years led Nigeria's influential Moslem
community, numbering perhaps 50 million and making up 43 percent of
the population of Africa's most populous nation. He died Nov. 1 at
age 85.
   Thousands of people who wanted Abubakar to be succeeded by his
eldest son, Muhammadu Maccido, took to the streets in protest Monday
and set fire to several public buildings and a commercial bank.
   The official News Agency of Nigeria says Sokoto town has been
calm since Wednesday, although soldiers continue patrolling the
streets. A dusk-to-dawn curfew was imposed Monday.
   Daku said he approved Dasuki's appointment after the nine-member
selection committee of Moslem elders, called kingmakers, ``had
deliberated on the aspirants to the sultanate and passed their
recommendations to the state Council of Chiefs.''
   But reporters in Lagos, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
people in Sokoto believe the military government forced the
committee to choose Dasuki, instead of Abubakar's son.
   Radio Nigeria said the rioters burned several buildings,
including that of Rima Radio and the local branch of the
Luxembourg-based Bank of Credit and Commerce International.
   Dasuki is chairman of the bank's local board.
   Dasuki, a 65-year-old millionaire and former civil servant, has
urged people to remain calm.
   Traditionally, the sultan in Sokoto also is revered by Moslems in
neighboring countries and frequently is consulted by Nigerian
politicians, including those of the other dominant Christian and
animist faiths.
</TEXT>
