<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Liddy-Bankruptcy     11-11 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Liddy-Bankruptcy,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Firm Of Former Watergate Burglar Files For Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The security firm run by former Nixon aide and
convicted Watergate burglar G. Gordon Liddy has filed a Chapter 11
bankruptcy petition seeking protection from creditors.
   International Security & Intelligence Inc., doing business as G.
Gordon Liddy & Associates, claimed ``certain business reversals and
a severe cash flow crisis'' in a petition filed in federal court
here Tuesday.
   Founded by Liddy two years ago, the firm provides armed guard
services to customers, with about 140 guards in the South Florida
area. It also employed an anti-terrorist team called ``Hurricane
Force,'' which Liddy said was available to rescue kidnapped company
executives.
   The Miami-based company, which listed $363,000 in assets and
$747,000 in liabilities, asked the court to allow it to pay a
$40,000 payroll owed employees.
   On Thursday, a bankruptcy court judge agreed to let the firm use
cash for 30 days, with a final hearing tentatively set for Dec. 8.
   International Security said creditors claim they are owed almost
$1 million. The firm disputes some of the debt, including about
$200,000 stemming from a recently failed merger attempt with Walnut
Capital Corp., of Chicago.
   According to the bankruptcy claim, International Security does
not dispute that it owes $278,300, to the Internal Revenue Service.
   Liddy, who was general counsel to President Richard Nixon's
re-election campaign, served 52 months in federal prison for the
1972 break-in at Democratic Party headquarters in Washington, D.C.
He had been hired by former Attorney General John Mitchell, who died
on Wednesday.
   In addition to the security firm, Liddy also runs a polygraph
testing company and has been a frequent speaker on college campuses.
