<DOCNO> AP881111-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0505EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PLOMeeting     11-11 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO Meeting,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Independent Palestine Expected To Be Declared By Palestinian
Legislature</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian leaders meeting this weekend
as a legislature in exile are likely to declare an independent state
in the Israeli-occupied territories, senior PLO officials said.
   The 450-member Palestinian National Council, at a three-day
meeting that begins Saturday, could make its most important
decisions since the Arab League created the organization 24 years
ago.
   The move could have a profound effect on stalled Middle East
peace efforts.
   But gains in last week's Israeli elections by the right, which
opposes giving up any of the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, lend
new uncertainty to the Palestinian issue.
   Senior officials of the Palestine Liberation Organization said
the council will endorse a PLO call for an independent state in the
occupied territories, which Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in
1967 and are home to 1.5 million Palestinians.
   They said PLO plans to establish a provisional government
probably will be delayed and the timing left to the Palestinian
National Council's 70-member Central Council, which oversees
resolutions. The National Council includes non-PLO Palestinians.
   Pragmatists in the PLO and such moderate Arab states as Egypt and
Jordan say declaring independence will be little more than symbolic
unless the National Council produces a realistic political program
that can gain international support.
   PLO leaders have considered a declaration of Palestinian
independence for years, but the idea has gained impetus during the
11-month Israeli uprising, during which at least 310 Palestinians
and 10 Israelis have been killed.
   The rebellion has won widespread sympathy and forced PLO chairman
Yasser Arafat to make hard political decisions he had postponed for
years or risk losing the leadership of increasingly frustrated
Palestinians.
   Arafat got another jolt July 31, when King Hussein of Jordan cut
legal and administrative links with the West Bank, which Jordan
governed from 1950 to 1967, and Palestinians in the Gaza Strip.
   Hussein's action left the PLO little choice but to assume
responsibility as the sole representative of the Palestinians, a
status endorsed by years of Arab summits.
   An important question to be answered in Algiers is how far the
National Council will go toward recognizing Israel.
   Declaration of an independent state will have its legal basis in
U.N. General Assembly Resolution 181 of 1947, which proposed
splitting Palestine into Jewish and Arab states.
   Basing the declaration on the resolution could be interpreted as
implicit recognition of Israel, but that is unlikely to satisfy
conditions Israel and the United States have set for dealing
directly with the PLO.
   Some of Arafat's key aides, and his Soviet allies, believe more
explicit recognition will overcome U.S. opposition and force Israel
to accept peace talks.
   U.N. Security Council Resolution 242 calls for Israel's
withdrawal from occupied land in return for recognition of its right
to exist in secure borders.
   Another reasom for U.S. and Israeli opposition to direct
negotiations is the 1968 PLO Covenant calling for armed struggle and
the destruction of the Jewish state.
   Some prominent Palestinians said the PLO could get around that
quietly, without a formal declaration, by forming a provisional
government that would write a constitution to replace the Covenant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881111-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0512EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-MissingDoctor     11-11 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Missing Doctor,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Message From Mother Of Missing Belgian Doctor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Beirut newspaper today published a
message from the mother of missing Belgian physician Jan Cools
appealing to the people of Lebanon to help free her son.
   ``Please help us to get Jan released so that he can go on helping
people,'' said a letter from Mrs. Cools, published in the
conservative An-Nahar newspaper.
   The letter, written in English and translated into Arabic for
publication, was dated Oct. 21. It did not identify Mrs. Cools by
her first name.
   ``Jan has been lost for five months,'' said the letter. ``We,
Jan's family, haven't heard anything about him since the first day
of his disappearance.
   ``The only thing we can do is to guess: Is he still alive? What
about his health? Has he been hurt? We for ourselves cannot answer
these questions.''
   Cools, 32, disappeared May 21 after leaving his apartment in the
Rashidiyeh Palestinian refugee camp near the southern port of Tyre.
He had worked in the camp for three months with the Norwegian
humanitarian organization NORWAC.
   Police said they had no information about his disappearance. But
the Fatah-Revolutionary Council group, led by terrorist Abu Nidal,
on Sunday said Cools was held by an unidentified Lebanese faction
that has not concluded its investigation of him.
   A statement in May from the so-called ``Popular Committee,''
which runs Rashidiyeh's day-to-day affairs, said Cools was kidnapped
by unidentified gunmen at a road junction near Tyre. It gave no
details.
   Recent reports in Beirut say the faction holding Cools is
demanding a $5 million ransom for his release. But neither the
police nor the Belgian Embassy would confirm that.
   Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The
Associated Press, is the longest-held of the 14 foreign hostages
held in Lebanon. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   The journalist, 41, is being held by a pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem
faction calling itself Islamic Jihad, or Holy War.
   In addition to Anderson, the 13 foreigners missing in Lebanon are
eight Americans, three Britons, an Italian and an Irishman.
</TEXT>
