<1ST_LINE>u a PM-SuperCollider-Reax Bjt   11-11 0677</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Super Collider-Reax, Bjt,0696</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Super Collider A Multibillion-Dollar Prize; Texans Celebrate</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WAXAHACHIE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With a few disgruntled exceptions, Ellis
County residents quickly began celebrating their newfound fortune as
the beneficiaries of the Energy Department's $4.4 billon
superconducting super collider.
   Residents rushed to town squares to pop champagne corks shortly
after learning Thursday that the county just south of Dallas would
get the giant atom smasher, which drew bids from 20 states.
   ``About the only thing that might be similar to this would be
being named the city to host the next Olympics,'' saysid David
Lander, the mayor pro tem of Midlothian, population 5,000.
   Jubilant Texans cheered in celebrations at the county courthouse
and Chamber of Commerce here, the Midlothian City Hall and the Ennis
town square, as high school bands played and bank signs flashed the
good news.
   ``It's a very festive mood,'' said Lander. ``Everyone is very
excited. It's obviously going to be a tremendous boost to our north
Texas economy.''
   The collider is envisioned as a 53-mile underground ring that
will use 10,000 magnets to whirl beams of protons into each other at
energy levels 20 times what is possible in today's most powerful
machines. The goal: to probe more deeply into the origins of matter.
   For many north Texas residents, the project will bring new jobs,
a more technical work force, a stronger housing market, better
schools and prosperity for an area once known exclusively for its
cotton farms and ranches.
   If built, the super collider would bring an estimated 4,000
construction jobs and 3,500 permanent jobs to Waxahachie, population
18,000.
   ``The super collider is an investment in our future,'' said Phil
Bronson of Waxahachie. ``The educational level will come up once we
get all the technical people in here.''
   ``I've been through a lot of land speculation in this county, but
nothing like this,'' said real estate agency owner Tom Crabb. ``The
land values here could double inside the ring _ maybe more.''
   That prospect didn't excite everyone, however, including Dale
Wilburn, a 38-year-old machinist whose family will have to sell its
land to make way for the collider.
   ``I understand they want to break down atoms and see what's
inside them,'' he said. ``I don't really understand much more. It
would be better if they built a pipeline so we could get gas up
north to those Yankees.''
   For others, the potential changes hold more personal importance.
   Bob Hamilton, who lives in a rural development outside
Waxahachie, looks forward to getting a cafeteria. Others dream of a
new hotel, a mall, a couple of nightclubs or a rumored Disney-style
amusement park.
   Crabb, a former Waxahachie Chamber of Commerce president, said he
expects large corporations to set their sights on Waxahachie. Arby's
already has staked out a parcel of land, he said.
   It's estimated the project will pump $270 million into the local
economy, but the windfall would spread far beyond the county line.
   ``This will change our economic and educational base for all
time,'' says Dallas City Councilman Jack Evans, who led a committee
to lure the project to Texas. ``You will see many awards and
benefits coming out of the research that will be done here.''
   The Energy Department's decision got some negative reviews,
especially from the six other finalist states that didn't get the
plum. Politicians from some of the losers _ Illinois, Colorado,
Michigan, Arizona, Tennessee and North Carolina _ called for a
bipartisan review of the selection process.
   Some locals also expressed reservations about the project.
   ``Personally, I hate to see this come, but it can't be helped,''
said county sheriff's Lt. Joe Bob Underwood. ``My brother and I own
a ranch, and this always has been a lot of farm land. But that's
going to change now.''
   Dick Erwin, who bought a house south of Red Oak four years ago,
said he had mixed emotions. ``I'm glad the county's going to get
it,'' Erwin said, ``but I'm sorry I'm going to have to lose my
house.''
</TEXT>
