<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Kristallnacht-Vandalism     11-11 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kristallnacht-Vandalism,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swastikas, Other Anti-Semitic Vandalism Mars Kristallnacht
Remembrance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Swastikas and other anti-Semitic slurs were painted at a Jewish
cemetery in Rhode Island, a Denver synagogue and a Jewish student
building in New York as thousands marked the 50th anniversary of
Nazi rioting that heralded the Holocaust.
   Officials said Thursday the spray painting at the 95-year-old
cemetery in Woonsocket, R.I., took place about Tuesday, the day
before synagogues, churches and schools worldwide remembered
Kristallnacht, or ``The Night of Broken Glass.''
   On Nov. 9, 1938, Nazi thugs went on a rampage, killing scores of
Jews and setting ablaze more than 1,100 synagogues in Germany and
Austria.
   A woman visiting B'nai Israel Cemetery on Tuesday found her son's
headstone among the approximately half-dozen covered with Nazi
crosses, swastikas and other symbols. The main road to the cemetery
was inscribed with slogans such as ``Die Jews'' and the German word
for Jew, ``Juden.''
   ``Today, when I went to the cemetery, it was a very terrible
reminder of things that have happened to us in the past,'' Temple
B'nai Israel President Edith Wittes told a congregation assembled
for a Kristallnacht memorial service Wednesday.
   Police were uncertain whether the desecration was linked to
Kristallnacht, but the timing raised questions, said Detective Sgt.
Ronald Bashand.
   In addition to the Nazi symbols, there were other images with
possible links to Satan worship, such as skulls and an inverted
cross with its arms turned down.
   ``The form of the desecration was clear _ the symbols are here _
everything that made Kristallnacht possible,'' said Rabbi Joel
Chernikoff. ``The sickness that made Adolf Hitler possible is alive
and well today, in our own community.''
   Among the other phrases spray-painted on the road were ``Death''
and ``Napalm.''
   In Denver, swastikas were spray-painted on a synagogue and a
Jewish-owned delicatessan Wednesday night, said Saul Rosenthal,
director of the Mountain States office of the Anti-Defamation League.
   ``They are an unfortunate occurrence on this date,'' he said. ``I
really doubt that it's coincidental.''
   Swastikas were spray-painted on the front door and sign in front
of the synagogue at the Hebrew Educational Alliance, Rosenthal said.
At Steinberg's Deli, swastikas and the slogan ``Jude die'' were
painted.
   ``We see this stuff all too regularly,'' Rosenthal said, but it
was ``very, very emotional to have it take place on this particular
day.''
   At the State University of New York at Binghamton, N.Y.,
swastikas and anti-Semitic slogans were found Thursday morning
spray-painted inside the office of the Jewish Student Union.
   ``I can't even find the word for it, it's so hurtful,'' said
James Oppenheim, president of the student group.
   There was no sign of forced entry at the office and sanctuary,
housed in the basement of the college's student union, Oppenheim
said. The group has about 200 students that coordinate activities on
the campus.
   ``I think it's politically motivated because they didn't do any
damage that we can see,'' Oppenheim said.
   The group had sponsored a candlelight vigil Wednesday night to
commemorate Kristallnacht.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
