<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0842 11-11 0859</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0842,0878</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kate Nelligan Stars in Michael Weller's `Spoils of War' on Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS reactions of other critics at end. No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Playwright Michael Weller set ``Moonchildren,''
his first theatrical success, in the turbulent 1960s. It was
followed some five years later by ``Loose Ends,'' which examined
several lives in the more self-satisfied, if not any more satisfying
1970s.
   Now Weller delves further into the past with ``Spoils of War,'' a
highly personal, not entirely convincing, family drama of the
mid-1950s, with emphasis on the word ``family.'' The play opened
Thursday at Broadway's Music Box Theater.
   A perfect family is what 16-year-old Martin wants more than
anything else. A student at ``one of the best progressive schools in
the East,'' he returns to New York in an effort to reunite his
divorced parents _ Andrew, a cold, reserved photographer, and Elise,
a beautiful, hard-drinking, hard-living romantic.
   Andrew and Elise are left-over leftists, trying to shake off the
effects of the Depression, World War II and Sen. Joseph McCarthy on
their lives. They never quite succeed. Their love lives are equally
messy. Neither has ever had a satisfactory relationship, as the
drama takes pains to point out. Martin has been the only lasting
reminder of their marriage.
   Weller has called the play ``semi-autobiographical,'' but the
center of ``Spoils of War'' is not the teen-age Martin or his father
but the flamboyant Elise. She's the most compelling character Weller
has ever written, and in Kate Nelligan's Tony-caliber performance,
the woman comes vividly to life.
   Miss Nelligan, wearing a striking red wig, invests a lot in the
character, and her hard work pays off. Elise is funny in a
self-mocking way, sexy, vulnerable and most important, intelligent,
even recognizing her own flaws.
   The character is not above borrowing money from her best friend,
a still-committed revolutionary named Emma, played with endearing
sweetness by a terrific character actress named Alice Playten. Elise
also is willing to flirt _ and more _ with Lew, a Midwest building
contractor, if he builds for her a house where she can finally make
a home. He's played with hayseed authenticity by Kevin O'Rourke.
   Almost as interesting as Elise is Martin, the son who is not
above manipulation if it will help bring his parents together.
Christopher Collet mixes the right amount of boyish charm and
deviousness to bring it off.
   ``Spoils of War'' tells Martin's story, a shattering of his dream
about the perfect mother and father.
   It's Andrew, the father, who remains the problem in the play.
When the drama was performed last spring at off-Broadway's tiny
Second Stage, the man was something of a cipher. Weller has made the
role larger but not altogether clearer.
   Andrew, played with an icy intensity by Jeffrey De Munn, tries to
justify his desertion of wife and child as well as his political
causes. His answer _ which won't be revealed here _ drew
unintentional laughter from the audience at the show's last preview.
   It doesn't help that Andrew also comes equipped with a young
girlfriend, Penny, blandly played by Marita Geraghty. The actress is
not as effective as Annette Bening who had the role at Second Stage.
As a result, it's simply no contest between the wimpy girlfriend and
the dominating but desirable ex-wife when they finally have a
showdown.
   Director Austin Pendleton has given the play an austere and
unsentimental production. Despite the overflowing of argument,
Pendleton doesn't allow the drama to turn to mush.
   But he does allow a massive, turntable set of drab living rooms
designed by Andrew Jackness to nearly overwhelm what should be an
intimate drama. The rooms swivel ominously between every scene.
   In the end then, ``Spoils of War'' is not a perfect play, just a
small one. But it certainly is intriguing, chiefly because of the
incandescent Miss Nelligan.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Here are the findings of some other New York critics.
   In The New York Times, Frank Rich wrote that Weller ``seemed on
the verge of a major breakthrough with this work,'' but it didn't
quite deliver.
   He said it is Wellers' ``most absorbing play, always intelligent
and at times moving, but it is still too lumpy, both in the writing
and in Austin Pendleton's erratic direction, to achieve the lofty
theatrical stature promised by its characters and ideas.''
   But the Times called the plan ``compulsively watchable whenever
Ms. Nelligan is on stage.''
   In the Daily News, Howard Kissel wrote that the story is ``less
convincing because its principal combatants are all essentially
selfish, cold people.''
   ``It is hard to know why the son wants to bring his parents
together, since his father left before he was old enough to remember
them as a couple.''
   In the New York Post, Clive Barnes called the play ``emotionally
charged and moving.''
   He said he suspects the play ``is still not the one Weller would
have liked to have written.''
   But while he concluded ``it is not `The Glass Menagerie' or even
an animal in such a zoo _ it remains a touchingly lovely work
touchingly performed.''
</TEXT>
