<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FraudSentence     11-11 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fraud Sentence,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researcher Sentenced In Academic Fraud Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nationally recognized drug therapy researcher
was sentenced to 60 days in a halfway house for submitting false
data to the National Institute of Mental Health on treatment of
mentally retarded children.
   The researcher, Stephen E. Breuning, is believed to be the first
scientist prosecuted by the federal government for faking medical
research.
   U.S. District Judge Frank A. Kaufman on Thursday also sentenced
Breuning, 36, to five years of probation, and ordered him to pay
back $11,352 in salary, serve 250 hours of community service and
abstain from psychological research for at least the period of his
probation. Breuning agreed to stay out of the field at least 10
years, as requested by prosecutors.
   ``It's quite obvious that our society cannot tolerate this type
of fraud,'' the judge told Breuning, a former University of
Pittsburgh psychologist. ``Fraud eats at the very guts of society.''
   Kaufman ordered Breuning to serve his sentence in a halfway house
near his home in Rochester, Mich., where he recently opened a store
selling compact discs and stereo equipment.
   Breuning pleaded guilty Sept. 19 to two counts of making false
statements on grant applications in exchange for the dropping of a
charge that he obstructed an investigation at Bethesda-based NIMH
into the authenticity of his data.
   ``You've paid very, very dearly for what you've done. You will
continue to pay dearly,'' the judge said.
   Prosecutors said that not only was Breuning's career ruined, but
he had hurt research assistants ``who had rested their careers on
his work.''
   The judge called Breuning's actions ``the kind of aberration of
conduct that could (occur among other researchers) in the highly
charged competitive atmosphere'' of academia.
   A remorseful Breuning told the judge that his guilt was
``something I'm very embarrassed and ashamed about.''
   The case sparked a tightening of standards for monitoring
academic research as well as calls for legislation targeting
scientists who fake their data.
   According to prosecutors and a statement of facts in the case,
Breuning's research involved several NIMH-sponsored studies from
1980 to 1984 at the University of Pittsburgh to examine the use of
drugs in controlling hyperactive retarded children.
   The studies purportedly showed that children could be treated
with smaller doses of tranquilizers as well as with stimulants such
as Ritalin and Dexedrine, which had fewer side effects than
tranquilizers.
   In a sentencing memorandum, E. Thomas Roberts, an assistant U.S.
attorney, said Breuning seized on the opportunity to prove the
popular theory that ``less immediate intervention with drugs,''
coupled with other treatment techniques, could be more beneficial to
the children.
   But in his eagerness, Breuning used false data and research
results from other studies, said Roberts and Breuning's attorney,
Charles S. Lazar.
   There was ``no evidence supporting most of the research by Dr.
Breuning,'' the sentencing memorandum said, and much of the research
by his assistants ``was producing contradictory information to that
which Dr. Breuning was officially reporting.''
   Prosecutors said only 25 of 278 children in the studies actually
received the drugs.
   The grants Breuning obtained provided ``significant'' financial
support for the university's psychiatric clinic, Roberts said in
court papers.
   Lazar said in documents that his client, who sought $200,000 in
grants from NIMH, falsified the data because he felt pressured by
the publish-or-perish atmosphere of academic research. He said
Breuning intended to combine previous research with work done at the
University of Pittsburgh, but instead produced a study that was
``careless and misleading.''
   However, prosecutors and Lazar noted, Breuning received no
personal financial benefit from the grants, no children were harmed
by treatment based on his research and the University of Pittsburgh
repayed $162,000 in grants to NIMH.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
