<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SuperCollider-FamilyEviction     11-11 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Super Collider-Family Eviction,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Stands To Lose Farm To Super Collider</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Super Collider-Reax, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAYPEARL, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Olive May Wilburn, 81, learned that
the superconducting super collider was coming, she wept for the home
her family stands to lose, along with the land her late husband
began farming in 1944.
   The Energy Department announced Thursday that it would locate the
$4.4 billion atom smasher, which 20 states had bid for, in Ellis
County, just south of Dallas.
   The project promises to bring a bonanza of jobs, better schools
and other benefits to the area. For Mrs. Wilburn, it promises to
take away the 200-acre farm her husband worked until his death 10
years ago and where her 3-year-old great-granddaughter, Pamela
Hopgood, now plays.
   Plans call for the Wilburn homestead to become the research
campus for the super collider, about midway between Waxahachie and
Maypearl. The farm is about five miles northeast of Maypearl.
   Only Wednesday, the wheat field around Mrs. Wilburn's house was
plowed. Now she doesn't know what to do.
   ``I just kept thinking that maybe it wouldn't come, maybe it
wouldn't happen,'' she said.
   After Texas bid for the super collider, state and federal
officials notified the Wilburns their acreage would be needed if the
state won.
   Mrs. Wilburn's granddaughter, Betty Hopgood, heard the news on
the radio Thursday morning, and told her grandmother.
   The announcement had many in Ellis County jumping for joy, but it
brought grief and anger to the Wilburn family.
   Mrs. Wilburn collapsed on her bed in tears.
   ``I cried, but not too long,'' said Mrs. Wilburn, who with her
husband worked 20 years to pay off the mortgage. ``It don't do no
good anymore. I've got to get out and I don't know where I'm going.''
   ``I hate to see farmers who have worked all their lives for their
land have everything taken away,'' said Mrs. Hopgood.
   ``I understand they want to break down atoms and see what's
inside them,'' said Mrs. Wilburn's grandson, Dale Wilburn, a
38-year-old machinist who lives with her. ``I don't really
understand much more. It would be better if they built a pipeline so
we could get gas up north to those Yankees.''
   Wilburn said he checked local land values and has found some
property selling for up to $6,000 an acre.
   ``I don't know if that would be enough to buy something
comparable,'' he said. ``We'll be out on the street and I don't know
if that will be enough.''
   Mrs. Hopgood, watching Pamela run across her great-grandmother's
kitchen, doubted they will be able to buy enough adjacent land for
the family to live as close to each other as they have.
   ``We'll never be together again, pretty soon,'' Mrs. Hopgood
said. ``We'll be lucky to find land fairly close to each other.''
   Wilburn, looking over a fence line dotted with rusting harvesting
equipment and rusting automobiles, said he is holding out hope the
project will stall.
   ``The government's always talking about something and never doing
it,'' he said. ``Maybe this will never get off the ground. Maybe
they're just talking again.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
