<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Opposition     11-11 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Opposition,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Politburo Members Sent to Soothe Baltics over Constitutional Furor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Politburo members flew to the three Baltic
republics today to deal with growing complaints that proposed Soviet
constitutional reforms will crush current moves toward economic and
cultural independence from Moscow.
   Politburo member Viktor Chebrikov traveled to Estonia, Vadim
Medvedev to Latvia and Nikolai Slyunkov to Lithuania. Their visits
were reported by state-owned media in the Baltics but not by the
national media in Moscow.
   The visits come a day after the Politburo, the top Communist
Party leadership, decided to consider changing draft constitutional
amendments in response to thousands of suggestions, the official
newspaper Pravda reported today for the first time.
   Popular front movements, local governments and Communist Party
organizations in the three republics have denounced reform measures.
At issue are provisions that would eliminate the right of republics
to secede from the Soviet Union and shift power from the 14
non-Russian republics to Moscow.
   The popular front in Vilnius, the Lithuanian Restructuring
Movement meets Sunday to consider the issue and the Lithuanian
Supreme Soviet will meet Thursday. The Estonian Supreme Soviet, or
legislature, is to meet Wednesday.
   Members of the three popular fronts are gathering signatures on
petitions asking the amendments be dropped and re-written from
scratch, said Algimontas Vaishnoras of the Lithuanian Restructuring
Movement.
   The Pravda article also promised future discussion of ``questions
of the status of unions and autonomous republics, to expand the
rights and possibilities in various spheres of economic,
social-political and cultural life.''
   It said the 300-member Central Committee of the Communist Party
plans a special meeting on the subject, but the newspaper gave no
date.
   The Presidium, elected by the Supreme Soviet or parliament, has
received more than 80,000 letters on the proposed amendments, Pravda
reported.
   Most are favorable, it said, but many suggest changes being
reviewed by a special commission of the Supreme Soviet.
   ``No argument will go without attention,'' it promised. However,
it said the leadership planned to tackle many of the issues in later
constitutional reform.
   The Baltic republics are not the only ones with serious
complaints. Human rights activist Andrei Sakharov has publicly
argued that the reform concentrates too much power in a strong
presidency, risking a repeat of the disastrous rule of dictator
Josef Stalin.
   Sakharov also seeks a strong guarantee of free speech in the
constitutinoal reform.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
