<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0487,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito Weakens, Doctors Fear Hemorrhaging</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES five grafs with details, condition weakens. Picks up
6th graf prvs, `Opposition parties ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito spent much of today sleeping, but
palace officials said he managed to watch some television and visit
with a daughter despite his weakened condition.
   They said the 87-year-old monarch, bedridden since Sept. 19, had
a fever of 100.2 F but otherwise was stable.
   His blood pressure, which plunged to 68 over 30 earlier this
week, had recovered to 144 over 70, the palace reported.
   This afternoon, the emperor was awake to see his fourth daughter,
Atsuko, and her husband, Takamasa Ikeda. He appeared weary and only
whispered ``thank you,'' Mrs. Ikeda told Kyodo News Service.
   Hirohito was sleeping when relatives visited him earlier, but did
awaken at midday and watched television, said Shoichi Fujimori,
grand steward of the Imperial Household Agency.
   ``He needs to sleep because his fever has lasted a long time and
made him tired,'' a senior palace official said.
   Hirohito has not discharged blood or received any transfusions
the past two days. But court doctors remain on alert because
internal hemorrhaging could occur any time, palace spokesman Kenji
Maeda said.
   Meanwhile, opposition parties accused the governing Liberal
Democratic Party of using the emperor's illness for politics.
   The Liberals, who hold a commanding majority in the Parliament,
forced controversial tax reform bills through a Parliament committee
Thursday.
   They told opposition parties, which boycotted the committee, that
they had to proceed with passing the bills because the emperor was
ill.
   ``We believe it is against the constitution to use the emperor's
name for their political gain,'' said Tomio Sakagami, a legislator
from the main opposition Japan Socialist Party.
   Opposition members denied they were abusing the emperor's name.
</TEXT>
