<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0719EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CDC-AIDS-Military     11-11 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CDC-AIDS-Military,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Infection Rate In Military Recruits Dropping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fewer U.S. military recruits are infected with
AIDS compared to three years ago, a decline federal health officials
believe is due to men who fear they may be infected not signing up
for duty.
   During the first six months of the military's AIDS testing
program, which was launched in October 1985, 15 out of every 10,000
recruits tested positive for exposure to the AIDS virus. But between
October 1987 and March 1988, 12 in every 10,000 recruits were found
to be infected, the national Centers for Disease Control reported
Thursday.
   ``Our leading hypothesis is that it reflects self-deferral among
high-risk applicants _ people who know they have (AIDS virus)
infections, or suspect they might be at increased risk, are not
coming into the recruitment centers,'' said Dr. Marta Gwinn, an AIDS
specialist with the Atlanta-based CDC.
   That theory is based in part on the fact that while there has
been a ``statistically significant decrease'' in AIDS infection
among male recruits, infection rates among female recruits _ who may
be less likely to think they are infected _ have stayed largely
constant, the CDC said in its weekly report.
   The rate of AIDS infection among male recruits has dropped from
17 per 10,000 in initial testing to 12 in the latest numbers, while
the rate for female recruits has risen from seven per 10,000 to
eight.
   ``Women may be less aware of their risk for ... infection,'' the
CDC said. Only 9 percent of all U.S. AIDS cases have occurred in
women; homosexual or bisexual men account for 68 percent.
   Although AIDS infection rates are lower among military recruits
than the public _ largely because gay men and drug users are subject
to exclusion from military service _ the military test results are
still of interest to researchers, Ms. Gwinn said.
   ``If the incidence of infection were to decline, we might detect
it first in the youngest age groups,'' she said, noting that
military recruits tend to be in their late teens or early 20s.
   ``Were we to see a dramatic decline in the youngest age group, it
would be potentially encouraging,'' she added. ``That is not what is
happening at the present time, though.''
   The military has tested more than 1.5 million recruits for AIDS
infection. More than 2,100, or 0.14 percent, have tested positive.
Federal health officials estimate that about 0.6 percent of the U.S.
population is infected with the AIDS virus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
