<2ND_LINE>PM-Maldives-Inauguration, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0481,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gayoom Installed As President For Third Term</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with Gayoom installed. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Maumoon Abdul Gayoom of the
Maldives was inaugurated today for a third five-year term after
weathering a coup attempt on the Indian Ocean island chain last
week, the government said.
   ``In view of what happened last week, the ceremony was simple.
There was no fireworks, no celebrations,'' said Ahmed Saleem, a
Foreign Ministry undersecretary contacted by telephone from New
Delhi.
   Saleem said 1,200 guests, including delegates from the United
States and India, attended the ceremony in Male, the Maldivian
capital.
   On Nov. 3, an estimated 150 Sri Lankan mercenaries officials
tried to overthrow the government but fled the next day when
hundreds of Indian paratroopers arrived at Gayoom's request.
   At least a dozen people died in fighting between Gayoom's lightly
armed militia and the mercenaries, who officials say were hired by a
former Maldivian leader who lost to Gayoom in a previous election.
   Six other people were killed aboard a cargo ship on which some
mercenaries tried to flee, only to be intercepted by the Indian navy.
   During the inauguration, Saleem said, ``We observed a one-minute
silence in memory of those who died while defending their
motherland.''
   The ceremony took place as scheduled in an open-air stadium,
despite earlier reports it would be moved to the presidential palace
for security.
   The 50-year-old president won a third five-year term Sept. 23 in
a yes-or-no referendum. About 90 percent of votes cast supported him.
   The Maldives is a chain of 2,000 tiny coral islands in the Indian
Ocean. Male is about 370 miles south of India's southern tip.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881111-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0730EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea     11-11 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radical Students Set Fire To Chun's Birthplace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students set fire today to the
provincial home of former President Chun Doo-hwan to press demands
for his arrest on corruption charges.
   Five riot police were injured in the firebomb attack on Chun's
former home in Hyupchon, 175 miles southeast of Seoul. Six students,
some of whom carried steel pipes, were arrested.
   The attack touched off a fire that burned three thatched-roof
structures at the house. The house was inhabited and being guarded
by a platoon-size riot police unit at the time the attack occurred.
   Several fire trucks and 100 village people were mobilized to help
put out the blaze, which took nearly 1{ hours to bring under control.
   The attack was the latest in a series of protests by radical
students to press demands that Chun be arrested and punished on
corruption charges. Major street protests last week attracted tens
of thousands of people.
   Chun, who left office in February, is under severe criticism for
financial and other scandals involving him, his family members and
associates.
   The ex-president denied any wrongdoings while in office, but two
of his close family members have been arrested on charges of taking
bribes and misusing millions of dollars in official funds.
</TEXT>
