<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Prisoner     11-11 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Prisoner,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black South African Leader Seriously Ill, Says Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 75-year-old president of
the outlawed Pan Africanist Congress is seriously ill at a prison
near Johannesburg, newspapers reported today.
   The Sowetan and The Star quoted Urbania Mothopeng as saying her
husband, Zephania, had a ``swollen neck'' and his voice had
``dwindled to inaudible whimpers'' when she visited him last weekend.
   ``His condition was worse than when he was admitted to a
Johannesburg clinic in September, though his legs were not swollen
this time,'' the papers quoted her as saying.
   Mothopeng also was hospitalized in July, but the nature of his
illness has not been disclosed.
   He is held at Diepkloof Prison near Johannesburg.
   Mothopeng was sentenced in 1979 to a 15-year prison term for
furthering the aims of the outlawed Pan Africanist Congress, which
wages a campaign of sabotage to undermine the white-led government.
He was elected president of the exiled organization in 1986.
   The Prisons Service had no comment on Mothopeng's condition or on
Mrs. Mothopeng's comments that she has expected his release since
she was asked last year to sign a document saying she would be
responsible for his medical care.
   Mothopeng has actively opposed the government since the 1940s,
when he joined the African National Congress. He was a teacher fired
from his job in 1952 for his opposition to the government's
discriminatory education policies.
   With some other members, Mothopeng broke away from the African
National Congress in 1959 to form the Pan Africanist Congress, which
advocates black self-reliance and opposes the ANC's contacts with
activists of other races.
   Mothopeng is one of several imprisoned black activists whose
release is demanded by black politicians as a precondition for
negotiating with the government. Nelson Mandela, 70, the ANC leader
imprisoned since 1962, was convicted of plotting to overthrow the
government and given a life sentence.
</TEXT>
