<HEAD>Newspaper Reports Six Koreans Seeking Political Asylum in United
States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six Koreans from the communist north
and pro-Western south have sought political asylum in the United
States in the past two years, a leading South Korean newspaper said
today.
   The Joongang Daily News, quoting government sources it did not
identify, said the U.S. government still is reviewing the cases and
none of them has been granted asylum yet.
   It said four of the defectors were from the south and two from
the north.
   The sources obtained their information through the U.S. Embassy
in Seoul, the paper said. No independent confirmation of the report
was possible because the embassy was closed to observe Veterans' Day.
   Joongang said the U.S. State Department confirmed that the six
sought asylum between October 1986 and September this year, but
refused to identify them for security reasons.
   In Seoul, there was speculation that the South Korean defectors
may include prominent people who worked with former President Chun
Doo-hwan. A parliamentary committee currently is investigating Chun
for alleged corruption and other misdeeds during his seven-year term
in office, which ended in February.
