<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0812EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeadRhino     11-11 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dead Rhino,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rare Rhino Killed in Freak Zoo Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rare Indian rhinoceros apparently died of
shock after getting its head stuck in an 18-inch opening in a zoo
gate, officials said.
   The 2{-ton animal, which had lived at the Los Angeles Zoo for 19
years, had reared up and put its head through the opening, locking
its horn, said zoo director Warren Thomas.
   ``You're dealing with an animal with a relatively limited
intelligence level, and she panicked. It never occurred to her to
turn her head slightly sideways to slip her head out,'' Thomas said
Thursday.
   The animal, named Rhada, was found dead Thursday morning. It
apparently became trapped overnight. The rhino's air passages
remained open, indicating the animal died of shock and not
suffocation, said Thomas.
   The zoo has nighttime care for sick animals but no routine checks
for healthy ones. ``You don't want to disturb them,'' Thomas said.
``You don't want to spook them.''
   The 21-year-old rhino, born in India, was one of 75 in zoos
worldwide and one of few to breed successfully in captivity. About
2,000 of the endangered species live in the wild. Rhinos live to
about 40, Thomas said.
   ``It is a tragedy for us and a tragedy for the species because
she is one of the few successful breeders and her genes are real
valuable in a species survival program,'' said zoo spokeswoman Lora
La Marca.
   Rhada had given birth to two calves, including a 2-year-old male
that was with her in her pen when she became trapped, Thomas said.
   The zoo has two other Indian rhinos.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
