<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthernAfrica-Talks     11-11 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Southern Africa-Talks,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Southern African Peace Talks Resume</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA WATSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South African delegation met with U.S. and Soviet
officials today, hoping that agreement could be reached on a
timetable for a Cuban troop withdrawal from Angola and for granting
independence to South-West Africa.
   Another meeting of officials from South Africa, Cuba, Angola and
the United States, which is mediating the talks, was planned a South
African spokesman said. The spokesman, Roland Darrol, said the South
African delegation came to Geneva ``in a positive frame of mind.''
   He said the head of the South African delegation, Neil van
Heerden, director-general of the department of foreign affairs, met
with U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Chester Crocker today. The
South Africans also met with a Soviet observer delegation, he said.
   The sides are trying to achieve agreement on a withdrawal of an
estimated 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola, where they are backing
the Marxist government. South Africa links independence for
South-West Africa to the troop withdrawal.
   South-West Africa, also known as Namibia, is controlled by South
Africa in violation of a U.N. resolution for independence there.
   The Soviet deputy foreign minister, Anatoly Adamishin, said
Thursday the only remaining issue at the talks is the timing of a
Cuban troop withdrawal.
   A U.S. proposal made in early October reportedly calls on Cuba to
withdraw half of its troops from Angola by Aug. 1, with the
remaining troops to be stationed in northern Angola and withdrawn in
stages by the end of 1990.
   Cuba reportedly wants a 30-month timetable, compared to the 24
months sought by the United States and South Africa.
   A U.S. proposal last month reportedly suggested Jan. 1 as a
target date for independence in South-West Africa, with elections
scheduled Aug. 1.
   Adamishin, speaking through an interpreter Thursday night,
expressed ``cautious optimism'' that agreement on a troop withdrawal
could be reached during the Geneva session, which is scheduled to
end Sunday.
</TEXT>
