<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0850EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-YellowstoneVisits     11-11 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yellowstone Visits,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yellowstone Sets An Attendance Record In October</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mild weather and curiosity
about the damage from last summer's fires helped Yellowstone
National Park set an attendance record in October, officials say.
   Attendance in October increased by almost 50,000 people, or more
than 39 percent, compared to the same month last year, the park said
in a statement Thursday.
   Fires blackened more than a third of the 2.2 million-acre park
and closed most of its major tourist areas during the summer.
   The park said 175,019 people visited the park in October,
compared to a total of 125,597, which had been the previous record
for October. In the last 10 years, an average of 100,500 people
visited the park in the tenth month.
   ``Park officials attribute the significant increase in October
visitation to warm weather and the many visitors wishing to view the
park after the fires,'' the release said.
   The October figures bring the number of people to visit the park
during its summer season, May 1 to Oct. 31, to almost 2.07 million,
a 16.05 percent decline from 1987. The summer attendance record,
2.47 million, was set in 1978.
   The 1988 summer attendance represented only a 5 percent decline
from the 10-year average of almost 2.17 million, said Robert Barbee,
park superintendent.
</TEXT>
