<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BreastImplants 1stLd-Writethru a0492 11-11 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Breast Implants, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0492,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Breast Implants Safe Despite Raising of Concern, Surgeons Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to CLARIFY discussion is about silicone
implants. Pickup 5th graf, ``The group ...''
^By MALCOLM RITTER</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A long-term study of women with silicone breast
implants shows no support for newly expressed concerns about a
cancer risk, and 25 years of experience also shows the implants are
safe, plastic surgeons say.
   ``We certainly wouldn't do it (implant surgery) if we thought
there was a significant risk,'' said George Reading, president of
the American Society of Plastic and Reconstructive Surgeons.
   An estimated 2 million women have received silicone implants,
with 130,000 procedures done every year. Most are for cosmetic
purposes, and the rest for reconstruction after breast surgery.
   The Public Citizen Health Research Group, a private health
advocacy organization, called this week for a ban on silicone
implants, which they said may give a risk of cancer and other health
problems.
   The group contacted the Food and Drug Administration, which had
already scheduled a review of the devices. An FDA document said the
agency ``has been increasingly concerned about reports of adverse
effects from breast implants.''
   Implants are small bags, filled with clear silicone gel, placed
surgically behind breasts to make them appear larger. The procedure
can cost up to around $6,000, Reading said Thursday.
   The FDA said it wants manufacturers of the implants to furnish
scientific data to demonstrate the devices are safe and effective.
   Among other concerns, it cited a study that showed the gel can
produce tumors in laboratory rats. ``Although it is unlikely that
this finding is relevant to humans, the possibility of a cancer risk
cannot be completely ruled out,'' the FDA said.
   The type of tumor seen in the rats is common in rodents but not
in humans, said Thomas Krizek, chairman of the surgery department at
the Pritzker School of Medicine at the University of Chicago.
   Krizek, who has investigated effects of implants in rodents, and
Reading said they have never heard of a woman with an implant
getting that kind of tumor.
   In addition, no significantly higher rates for any kind of cancer
have emerged from a study of about 3,100 implant recipients in Los
Angeles County, said Gary Brody, clinical professor of plastic
surgery at the University of Southern California.
   The women have been followed for 12 years on average after their
implants, and up to 25 years, he said.
   FDA also expressed concerns about fibrous tissue growing around
the implants and causing painful hardening in the breast, the
possibility that gel will leak from the implant and possibly cause
problems with the immune system or a fetus, and the potential of
implants to interfere with the use of X-rays to spot early breast
cancers.
   Fibrous tissue grows around an implant as a natural reaction by
the body, Brody said. Probably less than 10 percent of implant
recipients experience pain or other discomfort, he said.
   ``Every woman is told it's a risk'' before surgery, he said.
Sometimes the problem can be remedied without removing the implant,
but if that fails, most women choose to leave the implant in, he
said.
   Gel has been found in lymph nodes, but the idea of spread beyond
that is only theoretical, Brody said. There is no evidence of any
effect on a fetus, he said.
   Only isolated cases of immune system disturbance have been
proposed as linked to implants, and the evidence is ``not very
convincing,'' he said.
   As for interfering with breast X-rays, Robert McLelland, chairman
of the American College of Radiology's committee on breast imaging,
said implants make for ``a very difficult exam'' because they can
hide breast tissue.
   Implanted women who want a breast X-ray should ask if the
radiologist is familiar with special techniques to remedy the
problem, he said.
   If the radiologist says no, or that no special techniques are
required, ``that would be reason to look elsewhere'' for the X-ray,
he said.
</TEXT>
