<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Tanker     11-11 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tanker,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Search Continues But Little Hope For 27 Crewmen on Tanker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian plane and a Soviet ship searched today
for 27 crewmen from a tanker that broke in two in the stormy north
Atlantic, but authorities said there was little chance they would
find survivors.
   ``It doesn't look like there's any possibility of finding
anybody,'' said Capt. Mort MacDonnell of the Canadian Search and
Rescue Coordination Center in Halifax, Nova Scotia.
   ``The indications are there was a bad fire on the vessel and the
two empty lifeboats which were found were burned,'' he said in a
telephone interview.
   All 27 Greek and Honduran crew members were on the stern section
of the 65,746-ton Odyssey when it broke in two Wednesday and burst
into flames, British-based Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit said.
   The Canadians told British coast guard officials that the fire
started in the stern section and then ignited the oil surrounding
the vessel, spreading the fire onto the ocean surface, Lloyd's said.
The fire burned for hours.
   The bow section of the Liberian-registered tanker remained afloat
until early Wednesday evening when it sank, MacDonnell said.
   Polembros Shipping Ltd. of London, operators of the Odyssey, said
the tanker had a Greek captain, 14 Greek officers and 12 Honduran
sailors.
   ``They haven't found any survivors but they're going to search
again today,'' said a spokeswoman, commenting on condition she was
not identified. ``All the families have been notified. But there
isn't much hope, I'm afraid.''
   Two Canadian military search planes returned to Halifax at
nightfall Wednesday but the Soviet weather ship Passat, the first
ship on the scene, remained in the area, 1,000 miles east of
Newfoundland.
   The Passat was 26 miles away when the distress signal was sent
out and rushed to help, but flaming oil kept it from getting closer
than a mile from the stricken vessel, said British and Canadian
coast guard officials.
</TEXT>
