<HEAD>Shots Fired On Political Leader's Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with details on the shooting. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shots were fired from a speeding vehicle
at the Khartoum residence of Mohammed Osman al-Mirghani, one of
Sudan's most prominent political and religious leaders, police
sources said today.
   There were no casualties in the Thursday night shooting, said the
sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity. They said witnesses
saw three gunmen open fire from a pickup truck, which fled at high
speed.
   The police informants said al-Mirghani was not in the house at
the time.
   Al-Mirghani is leader of the Democratic Unionist Party, the
second-largest partner in the cabinet coalition and in parliament
after the Umma Party of Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi. The
Democratic Unionist Party strongly advocates close relations between
Sudan and Egypt.
   Al-Mirghani also is leader of Khatmiya, one of Sudan's two
principal Moslem sects. El-Mahdi leads the other sect, Ansar.
   The police sources said security forces rushed to al-Mirghani's
residence after the shooting, blocked streets leading to it and
began searching for the attack vehicle.
   They said investigators at the scene counted 18 spent shells
believed to have been fired from AK-47 automatic rifles.
   Al-Mirghani planned to leave early Saturday for Addis Ababa,
capital of neighboring Ethiopia, for talks with John Garang, leader
of the Sudan People's Liberation Army, which has been fighting
government troops in southern Sudan since 1983. The police sources
said authorities were investigating possible motives for the
shooting, including al-Mirghany's peace mission.
</TEXT>
