<1ST_LINE>u i PM-China-Quake 2ndLd-Writethru   11-11 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Quake, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0517,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Quake Injures 71; Homeless In Sunday Quake Doubles To 200,000</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE injury toll from Sunday quake,
CORRECT that quake measured slightly more than 5. Pickup 7th graf
pvs, ``Trevor Page...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China said today that 71 people were injured in a
strong earthquake that struck off its southeastern coast, and the
number reported homeless from an earlier quake on the southern
border doubled to 200,000.
   The official China News Service said several buildings were
cracked and stairways collapsed in the Guangxi Zhuang region during
Thursday's quake, which measured slightly more than 5 on the Richter
scale.
   It occurred four days after a quake near the Burmese border
killed more than 930 people.
   No deaths were immediately reported in Thursday's quake, but 71
people were were hurt, nine seriously, as they scrambled from
buildings in the city of Fangcheng, the report said. It said the
trade city of Canton also was shaken by the quake, which was
centered offshore in the Beibu Gulf.
   Seismologists said the quake may have been an aftershock of the
Sunday quake that devastated dozens of remote towns and farming
villages in Yunnan province, west of Guangxi Zhuang. That quake
measured 7.6 on the Richter scale.
   More than 930 people were killed in that quake, according to a
preliminary count. The official China News Service quoted Yunnan
officials as raising the count of those injured by several hundred,
to 3,261.
   Trevor Page of the U.N. World Food Program said today that
Chinese officials told him 200,000 people were homeless from the
quake, twice as many as previously reported.
   Page said the Ministry of Civil Affairs sent his office a
detailed list of emergency supply needs, including antibiotics,
syringes, portable X-rays, jeeps, plastic sheets, tents, clothing
and canned food.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said Thursday that 75 tons of
medicine and 24 tons of food already had been sent to the quake area
by helicopter, truck and horse-drawn cart. Many villages in the area
can reached only on footpaths and the few existing roads have been
heavily damaged by the quake.
   Xinhua and government offices said they had no updates today on
the death toll. count of dead and injured. Xinhua acknowledged many
remote villages had not yet been reached by rescue teams and that
the casualty figures were expected to rise.
   A strong quake hit the same area of Yunnan in October, and a
quake measuring 5 on the Richter scale hit the Beibu Gulf on
Saturday, one day before the big Yunnan quake.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the strength of an earthquake,
and a quake measuring 6 can cause severe damage in populated areas.
One measuring 7 is 10 times as strong.
</TEXT>
