<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AvtexFibers     11-11 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Avtex Fibers,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Says Payment To Avtex Not A Bailout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financially troubled Avtex Inc., the sole
supplier of rayon yarn used in the space shuttle, has a week to
prove it can make a go of it or give the product rights to NASA
under a $7 million rescue by the agency.
   The money from NASA allowed Avtex to recall 1,300 workers
Thursday at its Front Royal plant, which had closed a week earlier.
   ``I don't look at it as a bailout, because every time we give
them something, they give us something in return,'' said J.R.
Thompson, director of NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center in
Huntsville, Ala. ``We're not in the bailout business.''
   Avtex, based in Valley Forge, Pa., is the sole supplier of the
fiber, used in rocket nozzles for the shuttle and an array of
missiles. NASA has said it has enough of the material on hand for 10
more shuttle flights.
   After NASA gives Avtex the $7 million, the company will have
until Nov. 18 to demonstrate that it will generate enough other
contracts to stay in business, Thompson said. If Avtex cannot do so,
NASA will take the rights to the fiber.
   ``They transfer the rights to NASA as well as the cookbook to
making this rayon fiber to our technical specifications,'' Thompson
said.
   If Avtex convinces NASA it will stay alive, NASA will sign an $11
million contract for more fiber, Thompson said.
   Avtex, in closing last week, blamed a drop in business from the
Challenger disaster, foreign competition for its other products and
environmental regulations that have led to numerous pollution
problems.
   Analysts who study the aerospace industry said that such
dependence on one producer of a vital product is not unheard of.
   During the summer, NASA provided money to rocket maker Morton
Thiokol Inc., which then loaned it to Pacific Engineering and
Production Co. for the rebuilding of a rocket fuel plant that blew
up in Nevada.
   ``It is amazing,'' said Paul Nisbet of Prudential Bache
Securities Inc. ``We've got lots of areas in the whole aerospace and
military industries where there are a lot of potential problems if
sources disappear from view.''
   ``We fight these fires one at a time,'' Thompson said.
</TEXT>
