<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Jenninger-Profile 1stLd-Writethru   11-11 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jenninger-Profile, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0515,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jenninger: Quiet Leader With Reputation For Effectiveness</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with comment that WWII inspired
Jenninger's career, other details. Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``Jenninger,
a...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Kristallnacht</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament President Philipp Jenninger,
whose remarks about Germany's Nazi past ended his 25-year political
career, once said he became a public servant because of his father's
opposition to World War II.
   Jenninger resigned today after he was sharply criticized over a
speech he gave Thursday in which he reminded his audience that
Hitler's rule was ``glorious'' in the view of many Germans.
Jenninger, who also criticized the Nazis, made the speech during a
ceremony marking the 50th anniversary of Kristallnacht, the night
that began the Holocaust.
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl also criticized his close friend and
former aide over the tone of the speech, the conservative Die Welt
newspaper said.
   In his resignation announcement, Jenninger said today that he has
always been an opponent of ``every type of totalitarian rule'' and
that he has been a consistent supporter of Israel.
   Jenninger, in a 1982 interview with West German reporters, said
he went into public service because his father told him the world
must avoid another war like the one started by Nazi Germany in 1939.
   ``Two of my brothers died in the war. My father told me when I
was 12: `Be of service during your lifetime, so that something like
this can never again happen.' That influenced me,'' Jenninger said
then.
   Jenninger, a 56-year-old member of Kohl's conservative Christian
Democratic Union, rode to the highest position in the Bundestag, or
parliament, on a reputation for fairness and effectiveness.
   As a close aide to Kohl, Jenninger was a leading figure behind
persuading East Germany to let more of its people visit or move to
West Germany.
   Jenninger was also involved in preparations for a planned 1984
visit to West Germany of East German leader Erich Honecker, but the
Soviet Union vetoed the trip. Honecker did finally travel to West
Germany in 1987 _ the first East German leader ever to do so.
   Jenninger was born June 10, 1932 in Rindelbach, in what is now
Baden-Wuerttenberg state.
   He received his doctor of law degree in 1957 from the University
of Tuebingen.
   Jenninger began his political career in 1963 as an adviser in the
Defense Ministry.
   From 1966-69, Jenninger worked as a political adviser to
then-Finance Minister Franz Josef Strauss, a powerful
arch-conservative politician who died last month.
   Jenninger won a seat in the Bundestag in 1969 and has been a
member ever since.
   He became the Christian Democratic Union's chief parliamentary
secretary in the Bundestag in 1975, in charge of coordinating the
party's parliamentary affairs.
   When Kohl became chancellor in October 1982, he awarded Jenninger
for his efforts by giving him the high-powered job of state minister
in the Chancellery.
   Jenninger became Bundestag president on Nov. 5, 1984, after
Rainer Barzel quit the post in a corruption scandal.
   The Bundestag members elected Jenninger president with 340 of 469
votes, reflecting the confidence his colleagues had in him.
   The respected Die Zeit newspaper said at the time that Kohl may
have lost Jenninger as his right-hand man, but that Jenninger was an
``emergency victim for the sake of parliament.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881111-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 1009EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-HumanRights     11-11 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Human Rights,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>European Human Rights Commission Will Hear Soering Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Human Rights Commission
said today it will review the case of a West German who is fighting
extradition to the United States, where he is wanted for a double
slaying.
   Jens Soering allegedly helped his U.S. girlfriend kill her
parents in 1985 in Virginia's Bedford County.
   The son of a West German diplomat, Soering lives in London, where
he is fighting extradition to the United States.
   He has appealed to the European Human Rights Commission, arguing
that if extradited he faces a possible death penalty in Virginia.
   Neither Britain nor West Germany have capital punishment.
   The European Human Rights Commission is a body of the 21-nation
Council of Europe. Founded in 1949, the council is the oldest
organization for European unity though its work has been eclipsed in
recent decades by the European Economic Community, or Common Market,
which is a separate organization.
   A spokesman for the European Human Rights Commission's office in
London said the commission has agreed to review Soering's case and
to try to reach an settlement between Soering and Britain.
   The human rights commission's office in Strasbourg was closed for
the Armistice Day public holiday.
   If no amicable settlement can be reached, the human rights
commission will likely send Soering's case to the European Court of
Human Rights for a ruling.
   But that is unlikely to happen before next spring and the case
may remain before the court for months, if not years. Some cases
have taken up to six years to come to a ruling.
</TEXT>
