<DOCNO> AP881111-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 1019EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DoctorsTrial     11-11 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Doctors Trial,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Medical Society Backs Doctors In Antitrust Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The local medical society has thrown
its support behind 24 obstetricians accused of violating state and
federal antitrust law by conspiring to boycott Massachusetts Blue
Shield.
   Massachusetts Attorney General James Shannon filed the suit
against the doctors in federal court Aug. 31, seeking civil
penalties of $30,000 each.
   The 700-member Hampden District Medical Society said the suit was
the first of its kind in Massachusetts. Blue Shield's rates are set
by a quasi-public commission.
   ``Apparently a state-supported monopoly doesn't bother the
attorney general, but he feels that if any two physicians talk about
anything in the corridors, that's collusion,'' said Dr. J. Gordon
Rich, president of the medical society.
   ``We feel there is no conspiracy and the First Amendment rights
of these doctors to free speech have been ignored and trod upon,''
Rich said. ``We feel it is an effort to intimidate and browbeat this
group of physicians and ultimately the entire profession.''
   Rich said area doctors have privately established a fund drive
for the legal defense of the doctors.
   The attorney general accused the doctors of acting together to
protest cost-containment efforts by Blue Shield, which denies
payment for procedures it considers unnecessary and refuses to
compensate non-participating physicians.
   The two dozen physicians, or more than two-thirds of the
obstetricians in the city, had notified the insurer in 1985 and 1986
that they planned to resign. Blue Shield requires a year's notice
and only two physicians actually left the program.
   Doctors who withdraw or threaten to withdraw from an insurance
plan undermine coverage for others and cause higher insurance
premiums, Shannon said.
   But Rich said, ``To the best of my knowledge there was never any
disruption of service to any Blue Shield patients.''
   An attorney for the doctors, Francis D. Dibble, said the doctors
made up their minds about Blue Shield independently and for a
variety of reasons.
   ``Some said they felt Blue Shield was an arrogant and poorly run
organization,'' he said, ``others said reimbursements were too low,
and others were pressured by rising malpractice insurance rates.''
</TEXT>
