<HEAD>Troops Mistake Soldier For IRA Guerrilla, Shoot Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDONDERRY, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British troops shot and
seriously wounded an off-duty British soldier they mistook for a
guerrilla during an IRA assault on a military base, authorities said
today.
   The soldier, who was not in uniform, rushed out of Rosemont base
in Londonderry after several shots were fired at the base Thursday
night, the police and army said in a joint statement.
   He was shot by a member of an army patrol that was responding to
the attack, the statement said.
   The injured soldier, who was not identified, ``had responded with
considerable initiative and courage by taking his weapon and going
out into Creggan Road'' outside the base, the statement said.
   ``One must assume at this moment that the military patrol saw an
armed man in the shadows and unfortunately fired,'' a press
spokesman at the British army's headquarters in Lisburn told The
Associated Press.
   The soldier was in serious condition at the city's Altnagelvin
Hospital, a spokeswoman said.
   The Irish Republican Army, fighting to drive the British out of
Northern Ireland, claimed responsibility for the base attack.
   On Tuesday night, the IRA set off a car bomb at a military
housing complex at Campsie, four miles outside Londonderry, and
caused extensive damage. Two policemen were treated for shock and a
soldier sustained cuts.
   The IRA took responsibility for the bombing and warned the
families of British soldiers to get out of Northern Ireland or face
further attack.
