<1ST_LINE>r a PM-VillageWindfall     11-11 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Village Windfall,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Benefactor's Death May Mean New Life For Eastern Ohio Village</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman who bequeathed $100,000 to
his small community didn't bother to shelter his $69 million estate,
meaning the village will get an additional $6 million in taxes,
officials said.
   ``Oh, my, do we need it,'' Cadiz Mayor John Migliore said
Thursday. ``What we're going to try to do is use it to create jobs
by attracting industry. That's how we can put some of this into
people's pockets.''
   Robert Fleagane, who once counted among his holdings the R&F Coal
Co. and a Columbus insurance company, died Jan. 31 at age 69.
   The village got its first check this month, the bulk of an
initial payment of $2.5 million. The state eventually will get $2.5
million.
   Fleagane had given a pool to the local community center and
helped build a hospital in the eastern Ohio village of 3,800, but
his will took officials by surprise.
   ``That man did not shy away from inheritance taxes. He didn't
shelter it to avoid them,'' said Harris County Treasurer Michael
Cope, who is in charge of investing the money.
   ``I don't know if it was intentional, but I do know he believed
in paying taxes and never taking anything from the government.''
   The village, which has one of the state's highest unemployment
rates, plans to erect a building to house potential industry and
will update its sewage plant and water treatment plant, Migliore
said.
   ``Anybody else in his position would have extraordinary efforts
to shield the estate from inheritance taxes,'' Cope said. ``He chose
to live here even after he sold R&F and he could have lived in
Florida. Robert Fleagane was a special man.''
</TEXT>
