<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Church 2ndLd-Writethru   11-11 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Church, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0480,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church of England Votes to Triple Blacks in Synod</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to ADD details of plan, quotes. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church of England leaders have voted to triple the
number of blacks on their policy-making synod, a move deplored as
``the reverse of apartheid'' by the Conservative government's
representative.
   With little more than half its members present Thursday, the
synod voted 214-74 with 11 abstentions to have at least 24 black
representatives on the 574-member General Synod. The synod currently
has eight black members.
   ``Black people in our midst have a great contribution to make,''
said the Most Rev. John Habgood, archbishop of York. ``We need to
increase their representation in the church as a whole.''
   He said the move would encourage blacks to run for election to
the synod in their church parishes.
   The vote followed a report from the church's Committee for Black
Anglican Concerns, which proposed the change for the next synod
elections in 1990. If 24 blacks are not elected in 1990, the minimum
will be achieved by appointing unsuccessful black candidates with
the highest number of votes.
   Paul Rippon, an English barrister, called the proposal ``deeply
insulting to black people, because it suggests they cannot get into
the synod on their merits.''
   But Barbados-born Wilfred Wood, bishop of Croydon and the
church's first black bishop to serve in England, said after the
vote, ``I'm gratified. ... I hope black people will come forward and
take their places in the Church of England.'' He heads the Committee
for Black Anglican Concerns.
   There are no statistics on how many blacks are in the Church of
England, which has about 1 million regular Sunday worshipers.
   Wood's committee estimates blacks account for about 7 percent of
England's 49 million people. It said the synod's standing committee
suggested it choose a figure. ``We believe that not less than 24 is
about right,'' the report said.
   John Gummer, the Conservative local government minister and a
leading synod member, called it ``apartheid in reverse,'' or reverse
discrimination.
   Joan Wakeling, a deaconess, agreed. ``We are going to need a lot
of work from the lawyers. If we vote for discrimination on behalf of
black people we could find ourselves setting an unhappy precedent.''
   Gummer said the problem is that not enough blacks ran for the
synod, and the church should do more by asking blacks to be synod
candidates.
   Before the debate, synod officials who took legal advice on the
proposal were told by barrister Anthony Lester that by giving
special provision to blacks, they probably would contravene the 1976
Race Relations Act, designed to bring about racial equality for the
country's ethnic minorities.
   Lester advised that the synod's attorneys could probably frame a
measure to circumvent the act, which would require parliamentary
approval.
   The church's laws and changes to them must be approved by
Parliament because the church is a state church with the monarch at
its head.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
