<HEAD>Iran-Iraq Peace Talks Recess</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peace talks between Iran and Iraq recessed today
after seven sessions produced no tangible progress toward
consolidating a cease-fire.
   Both sides agreed to resume the negotiations ``in the near
future,'' possibly next month or in January, said U.N. mediator Jan
Eliasson after the final, 50-minute meeting.
   The atmosphere at the latest round of talks, which began Oct. 31,
was described by Eliasson as ``constructive and sober.'' He said the
climate remained chilly and that both sides still refuse to speak to
each other.
   During coffee breaks, there are ``occasions you could detect
something that could ... be called conversation,'' Eliasson added.
   Iran's foreign minister, Ali Akbar Velayati, said the latest
meetings featured a ``better climate and we do hope that the next
round will achieve practical progress.''
   His Iraqi counterpart, Tariq Aziz, also voiced hope for progress
and said Iraq ``will do its best to make the next round fruitful.''
   Eliasson said both countries reaffirmed their commitment to
uphold a cease-fire in effect since Aug. 20 and to implement U.N.
resolution 598, which calls for a comprehensive peace settlement in
the 8-year-old war.
   He gave both sides credit for accepting a Red Cross proposal to
begin exchanging disabled war prisoners Nov. 20.
   But he acknowledged at a news conference that the talks remain
stuck on various points, including the withdrawal of forces to
internationally recognized borders. Iran insists that the withdrawal
be based on a 1975 border treaty that Iraq insists is invalid.
</TEXT>
