<HEAD>Ex-Detective Testifies Steinberg's Knuckles Were Swollen, Scratched</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired detective testified that the hands of
an attorney accused of beating to death his adopted daughter were
swollen and scratched, but the witness conceded that photographs did
not back up his claims.
   In testimony Thursday at the murder trial of Joel Steinberg,
former Detective William Lachenmeyer said he used a ``cheap'' camera
to take instant photos of the defendant's hands.
   Defense attorney Ira London challenged Lachenmeyer to find any
``observable scars or scratches or open wounds'' on Steinberg's
hands in the photos.
   The detective replied that the photos ``do not depict how his
hands appeared to me.''
   Steinberg, a 47-year-old disbarred lawyer, is charged in the
death of 6-year-old Lisa Steinberg in 1987. The illegally adopted
child died after being admitted to a hospital, bruised and comatose.
   Steinberg has denied beating the girl, contending the child fell
unconscious after choking on food. Doctors and nurses from St.
Vincent's Hospital have testified Lisa's legs, arms, back and chest
were covered with bruises.
   Lachenmeyer said he noticed Steinberg's hands were battered just
before he was arrested.
   ``I asked him to put his hands on the table,'' Lachenmeyer said.
``I observed all of his fingers. They were red and swollen. Two
forefingers and two thumbs were scratched.''
   Hedda Nussbaum, Steinberg's live-in companion, was arrested in
Lisa's death as well, but murder charges were dropped and she is
expected to testify for the prosecution.
   The prosecution contends that she, too, was beaten by Steinberg
and left so incapacitated that she could not act to save Lisa's life.
</TEXT>
