<2ND_LINE>PM-Molestation Trial,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father Gets Life Plus 20 Years In Prison For Molesting Daughters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCEVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A father convicted of molesting two of
his daughters for half their lives drew a sentence of life plus 20
years in prison from a judge who said he could find nothing
redeeming about the man.
   ``You are the most selfish, self-centered and arrogant person
I've ever met in my 36 years on the bar,'' Superior Court Judge
Bryant Huff told Ed R. Dickey, a 45-year-old Lilburn roofing
contractor, on Thursday.
   ``You don't even have the courage to acknowledge that your two
daughters told the truth on the witness stand in your case.''
   Dickey disregarded the advice of his attorney, Ronnie Batchelor,
and made a 20-minute statement in which he maintained his innocence
and charged anew that his daughters were coerced into testifying by
the state social workers.
   The judge also fined Dickey $10,000 and placed him on 120 years'
probation. Dickey will be eligible for parole in seven years.
   Huff stipulated that if Dickey is paroled, he cannot remain in
the presence of a girl for more than five minutes without the
supervision of an adult.
   Dickey was convicted of child molestation and sodomy Nov. 4 after
a trial in which he largely represented himself. He was accused of
molesting the two oldest of his four daughters, ages 16 and 18,
since they were 8 and 9.
   Dickey's wife, Peggy Sue Dickey, was ejected from the courtroom
during the sentencing hearing when she took the stand as a defense
witness and insisted over the judge's warning on reading a statement
calliang for a mistrial.
   Deidra Dickey, 18, also took the stand Thursday, saying no crime
had been committed because she had forgiven her father.
</TEXT>
