<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Czechoslovakia 2ndLd-Writethru   11-11 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Czechoslovakia, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0557,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Czech Police Break Up Seminar</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 8th graf pvs, ``Foreign participants...'' with 5 grafs
to
UPDATE with ambassadors meeting, details. Pickup 7th graf, ``Several
dissidents...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovak police today broke up a
seminar in Prague, arrested several dissidents and warned 16 foreign
participants that the meeting was illegal, sources in Prague and
Vienna reported.
   Banned playwright Vaclav Havel eluded police who rounded up other
dissidents Thursday and managed to reach the Prague hotel where the
seminar opened today, witnesses said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Havel managed to declare the seminar open before being arrested
by plainclothes policemen, according to foreign participants in
contact with the Vienna-based International Helsinki Federation for
Human Rights.
   Havel was chairman of the committee organizing the seminar. The
gathering was sponsored by the human rights movement Charter 77, the
independent cultural group Jazz Section, an activist group called
the Democratic Initiative and the Czechoslovak-U.S. friendship
society.
   The foreign participants in the seminar protested the police raid
to both the Czechoslovak government and the Helsinki review
conference in Vienna.
   Czechoslovakia's ambassador to that conference, Frantisek
Dolezel, defended the nation's recent tough moves against dissidents
and independent rallies today as actions in accordance with national
legislation, diplomats said.
   Petr Uhl, a dissident who was among 20 people arrested during the
last two days but was released Thursday with a few others, told The
Associated Press by telephone from Prague that foreigners attending
the meeting were told by police that it was ``directed against the
interests of the working class.''
   Nine ambassadors from NATO countries and the charge d'affaires
from several other Western countries later met at the Dutch Embassy
for a briefing from the seminar's foreign participants, said Dick
Knook, the Dutch charge d'affaires.
   Knook, who was reached by telephone from Vienna, suggested that
the Western countries might decide on some joint action in response
to the disruption of the meeting.
   He said Gerald Nagler, executive director of the International
Helsinki Federation, told the diplomats that ``a charming lady with
flowers'' arrived at the hotel where the seminar was and gave the
foreigners notes in envelopes.
   The notes said their further participation at the seminar would
be regarded as ``a manifestation of hostility toward
Czechoslovakia.''
   Some foreign participants also were handed envelopes by
plainclothes policemen warning them the seminar was illegal and not
in the interests of Czechoslovakia, the International Helsinki
Federation office in Vienna said.
   Several dissidents were arrested, sources said.
   A Vienna-based Associated Press reporter who met the two-week
deadline to apply for a journalist's visa to cover the symposium in
Prague was told she could not get a visa to go to Czechoslovakia
until Monday.
   The seminar was to focus on Czechoslovakia's past and future. In
a statement, the 16 foreign participants said the seminar was valid.
   ``We consider the continuation of this seminar about the
significance of the anniversaries of 1918, 1938, 1948 and 1968 for
Czechoslovakia and the whole of Europe to be entirely significant,''
the participants said.
   In 1918, after the collapse of the Austro-Hungarian Empire,
Czechoslovakia gained independent nationhood. In 1938, the Nazis
invaded Czechoslovakia's German-speaking area under the Munich
agreement. The communist takeover came in 1948 and in 1968, Warsaw
Pact troops invaded Czechoslovakia to crush liberal communist-led
reforms.
   The leader of those reforms, Alexander Dubcek, left
Czechoslovakia today on his first trip abroad in 18 years, a journey
to Bologna, Italy, to receive a university award.
</TEXT>
