<HEAD>Swedish Prime Minister Could Move to 40-Room Palace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Ingvar Carlsson wants
Sweden to have its own No. 10 Downing Street.
   Carlsson, who lives in a rented apartment owned by King Carl
Gustaf, wants to establish an official residence in a 40-room
building tucked between the prime minister's office and the foreign
ministry, which just went up for sale.
   Its last owner, Leo Sager, bequeathed it to the Roman Catholic
Church on condition his wife could stay as long as she lived. She
died in May at the age of 93.
   On Wednesday, his 54th birthday, Carlsson cleared the idea with
the country's political leadership of having a London-style
permanent home for the prime minister.
   The home would cost about $9.8 million, according to the Sager
foundation, which is selling the building for the church. The
address would be Stromgatan 18.
   Carlsson moved into his home near the royal castle, on orders of
the police, who judged his terrace house in Stockholm suburb of
Tyreso too difficult to guard.
   Although convenient, it was seen as improper for the head of
government to rent an apartment from the king, who is head of state.
   If he gets his birthday wish, Carlsson would have 1,380 square
yards to share with his wife, Ingrid, since their two grown
daughters moved away.
</TEXT>
