<HEAD>Soviet Expert Says Radiation Stronger Than Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet doctor who treated victims of
the Chernobyl nuclear accident said radiation appeared to counteract
drugs given to many patients, a newspaper said Friday.
   Svenska Dagbladet quoted Dr. Angelina Guskova as saying 28 of her
150 patients died. They are among the 33 people killed in the 1986
disaster, the world's worst nuclear accident.
   Guskova was quoted as saying 11 of 13 people who received bone
marrow transplants died. She said the radiation apparently was
counteracting drugs designed to prevent the body from rejecting
transplants.
   Surviving patients who visit her Moscow clinic for regular
checkups are suffering severe psychological problems, Guskova said.
   ``They all had to start a new life, find new jobs and apartments.
That, and the psychological hardship that ... remains for them,
demands our attention and sensitivity,'' she said.
