<1ST_LINE>r p AM-VoteCount     11-11 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vote Count,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Final Vote Count On Minor-Party Candidates Could Take Weeks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush and Michael Dukakis weren't the
only names on many state ballots in the presidential race Tuesday,
but the final vote totals for the minor-party candidates will not be
available for weeks, pending state certification of the tallies.
   Bush received 47.9 million votes to Dukakis' 41 million in the
balloting in unofficial tabulations with more than 99 percent of the
184,660 precincts reporting.
   Those returns come from the principal vote-gathering organization
for the nation, the News Election Service, which tabulated returns
for all states for the two major party candidates on Tuesday and
Wednesday.
   NES, owned by ABC, CBS, NBC, The Associated Press and United
Press International, focuses on a speedy, accurate tally of the vote
of major candidates.
   In some states, unofficial tabulations of third-party candidates
such as Libertarian Ron Paul, New Alliance Party standard-bearer
Lenora Fulani, the National Economic Recovery Party's Lyndon
LaRouche and Independent Populist David Duke were made. But such
figures are not available from all states.
   In many cases, the state government does no tabulation of the
vote until a final, official count. This official canvass of county
returns will be completed in some states next week. But some states
will not certify the returns until early January.
   In 1984, third-party candidates were not a significant factor.
   For comparison, final official totals that year showed Ronald
Reagan receiving 54.4 million votes and Walter Mondale 37.5 million.
The next ranking candidate was Libertarian candidate David Bergland
with 228,314, one-quarter of 1 percent of the vote.
</TEXT>
