<1ST_LINE>u p PM-RIRecount     11-11 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-RI Recount,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>R.I. Gubernatorial Candidates Asks For Recount</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIMBERLY M. SHEARIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic gubernatorial candidate Bruce
G. Sundlun, the apparent loser by a narrow margin in Tuesday's
election, requested a recount today.
   ``Perhaps a mistake was made of some significance,'' said
campaign manager Kenneth Haupt. ``I don't think it's very likely.
Neither does anyone else, really. Still, it should be checked. It
was very close.''
   Republican Edward DiPrete was re-elected by an unofficial margin
of 6,299 votes after Tuesday night's initial machine count, not
including 16,000 still- uncounted absentee ballots and 675 votes
from one late-reporting precinct.
   Haupt said he requested the recount because he owed it to
campaign workers and Sundlun's ``peace of mind.''
   A Sundlun campaign spokeswoman, Eileen Crochiere, said the
campaign is not alleging fraud.
   The governor, who was out of town today, said Wednesday that if
he were in Sundlun's position, he probably would consider asking for
a recount.
   With all but one precinct reporting from Tuesday's election,
DiPrete's unofficial machine total was 195,283 votes, or 51 percent,
to Sundlun's 188,984 votes, or 49 percent. New Shoreham's results
were sent in Thursday.
   A recount would begin Wednesday and probably would take three
days, said Elections Board chairman Joseph DiStefano.
   The recount entails opening all 1,800 voting machines and
comparing the numbers on the meters with those reported on sheets
filled out by precinct workers.
   The last statewide recount was in the 1986 attorney general's
race and did did not change the outcome, DiStefano said.
</TEXT>
