<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Chefs,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Chefs Visit Mississippi Delta Town To Experience Catfish</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANOLA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet visitors and their American hosts
wasted little time bringing up the subject of food as they gathered
for a meal at a traditional Southern home in this Mississippi Delta
town.
   The visitors were three chefs who are touring the United States
cooking Soviet delicacies and learning about American foods.
   ``Ketchup,'' Louisiana chef John Folse told the three during
Thursday's meal as he explained what had gone into a bowl of
barbecue sauce. ``It's a very good English word.''
   Folse, who attracted attention in June by serving blackened
catfish to international dignitaries at the Reagan-Gorbachev Summit
in Moscow, said the culinary exchange with the Soviet chefs was
another step in opening relations between the two countries.
   The tour also will include stops in Baton Rouge, New Orleans, New
York, Atlanta and Los Angeles.
   The Soviet chefs toured a catfish farm and the Delta Pride
catfish processing plant in Indianola on Thursday. They had a
Southern dinner featuring barbecue, fried chicken, catfish, potato
salad and Delta wine.
   The meal was at the home of Stan Berry and his wife, Tricia, who
did the cooking. Guests said the visitors assumed the large Southern
mansion was owned by the state, and had trouble understanding it was
owned by a family.
   Translator Galvina Birjukava said she could appreciate the warmth
of the Southern greeting. ``Russians are known for their
hospitality,'' she said.
   Chef Natalia Tokareva, speaking through a translator, said that
while she was not sure if Mississippi catfish would ever be
availiable in Moscow, her country may learn much from the Delta
industry.
   ``It would be very popular,'' Tokareva said. ``It is quite
possible to raise such catfish in the Soviet Union.''
   False said that during their 12-day tour the chefs would learn
how to cook such things as catfish and crawfish, as well as teach
American chefs about their foods.
   The visit by Soviet chefs is in direct response to Folse's summit
restaurant, said Sam Hinote, president of Delta Pride.
</TEXT>
