<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FamilyReunited     11-11 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Family Reunited,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emigre Reunited With Wife, Daughter After Nearly 12 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet dancer whose wife and daughter
were refused permission to join him in the West for nearly 12 years
was reunited with them in a joyous meeting at Jackson's Municipal
Airport.
   Fridrikh Begelmakher, 37, hugged his 36-year-old wife, Irina, and
the daughter he had last known as an infant and spoke softly to them
in Russian at their reunion Thursday. Begelmakher handed his wife
red roses and a love poem and gave their daughter, Olga, 13, some
daisies.
   ``What is going to be special is that we will be together. That
is what is special,'' said Begelmakher, a Jew who emigrated from the
Soviet Union during the exodus of the late 1970s.
   The family had seen each other only once since Begelmakher left
the Soviet Union with his parents on Feb. 21, 1977. He had expected
his wife and daughter to quickly follow, but they were repeatedly
denied permission to leave until this summer.
   ``The miracle we are witnessing today is something we worked hard
for for a long time. My wife kept applying to leave but was given
unreasonable excuses,'' said Begelmakher, who is chairman of dance
for Jackson Public Schools' Academic and Performance Arts Complex.
   He greeted his wife wearing the black shirt he wore the last time
he danced a ballet with her in the Soviet Union. The shirt is the
last piece of clothing remaining that he took from his homeland.
   Begelmakher said he had penned the poem early Thursday morning.
It read in part: ``I want to learn to talk _ to tell how much I love
you. But most of all I want to learn to love _ to love you.''
   Begelmakher had to divorce his wife, who is not Jewish, in order
to leave the Soviet Union, and the couple plans to remarry here, he
said.
   On July 24, the mother and daughter left the Soviet Union for
Vienna, where they waited for permission to enter the United States.
Begelmakher met them there Aug. 8.On Tuesday, they arrived in New
York, where they stayed with Begelmakher's parents.
   Since he came to the United States, Begelmakher has taught ballet
in many places, including Pennsylvania, Utah, Massachusetts,
Vermont, Idaho, Nebraska and New York. In September, he began
teaching ballet to students in the Jackson Public School system and
leading a four-member dance faculty.
</TEXT>
