<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LiteracyConference     11-11 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Literacy Conference,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ABC Chief, Evangelist Robertson Pledge Support for Literacy
Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC President James Duffy pledged his
network's continued support for efforts to fight illiteracy, telling
a meeting here that the United States has the worst illiteracy rate
of any industrialized nation.
   Duffy noted that ABC and Public Broadcasting Service launched a
program last year to call attention to the problem. Television
programs, public service announcements and other broadcasts have
generated hundreds of thousands of calls to a national hot line, he
said Thursday at the Governor's Third Annual Statewide Literacy
Conference.
   Late next spring, ABC plans another program on literacy, he said,
and part of that will include live broadcasts from ``town meetings''
to determine how selected communities are dealing with the problem
of illiteracy.
   Also Thursday, television evangelist Pat Robertson pledged $1
million to fight illiteracy in Mississippi.
   Robertson, chairman of the board of Christian Broadcasting
Network and the host of ``The 700 Club,'' told a news conference
he'll also lead efforts to raise another $5 million from private
donations to help teach reading and writing to adults and youths.
   Robertson, speaking at the Voice of Calvary Ministries in
Jackson, said his program would establish a statewide network of
educators and volunteers to move Mississippi into the top 10
literacy rankings over the next 10 years.
   Duffy told the meeting of educators, state officials and business
leaders: ``The fact is that illiteracy cannot be identified with any
one state or region or ethic group or in any one socio-economic
group. It is everywhere in the country.
   ``There are 23 million Americans who cannot read or write at the
fourth-grade level. There are 35 to 36 million who cannot read or
write at the eighth-grade level.
   ``The question is whether the leadership is aware of the problems
... fully aware of the fundamental significance of what it means in
this country,'' Duffy said.
   ``We do have the worst illiteracy rate of any industrialized
nation in the world. Thirteen to 15 percent of the national
workforce is functionally illiterate.
   ``We have a human resource problem in this country that threatens
our competitive position in the world. This is the economic
imperative behind the rapidly growing literacy movement in this
country,'' the ABC president said.
</TEXT>
