<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 1312EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i BC-Jenninger-Excerpts     11-11 1248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Jenninger-Excerpts,1274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Excerpts of Speech By Philipp Jenninger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from the
Kristallnacht 50th anniversary speech by West German Parliament
President Philipp Jenninger. The 26-page speech was translated into
English by The Associated Press.
   The Jews in Germany and all the world today remember the events
of 50 years ago. Also we Germans remember what happened in our
country a half century ago, and it is good that we do this in both
states on German soil. Because our history cannot be divided into
good and bad, and the responsibility for the past cannot be divided
according to the arbitrary geographic postwar order.
   
   What happended 50 years ago today right here in Germany, had not
occurred since the Middle Ages in any civilized country. And, even
worse: the rioting did not come from the expression of a motivated,
spontaneous public rage, but an action thought up, supported and
called for by state leadership.
   
   The ruling party in the form of its highest representatives,
suspended rights and laws. The state itself became the organizer of
crimes. Instead of purposeful laws and ordinances, with whose help
the insidious deprivation of Jews was carried out for years, public
terror took over. A minority of several hundred thousand were
declared fair game, their possessions and property left to the
destructive rage of an organized mob.
   
   Far more than 200 synagogues were burned down or demolished,
Jewish cemeteries were ravaged, thousands of businesses and homes
damaged and plundered. About 100 Jews found their death, about
30,000 were dragged to concentration camps; many of them never
returned. What cannot be described in numbers is the torment,
oppression, humiliation, mishandling, and degradation.
   
   (Nazi propagandist Joseph) Goebbels, the director of the entire
action, in some ways made a mistake in his calculations, when no one
_ domestic or foreign _ believed in the fiction of `spontaneous
public hate.' That was seen to by the inactivity of police and
firemen who stood around and let the synagogues burn, and only acted
when Aryan property was endangered.
   
   Later, party court proceedings verified with cynical openness
that the uniformed SA troops (the storm troopers) and the other
arsonists and murderers only carried out the will of the leadership.
In the end, only those who had made themselves guilty of sexual
relations with a non-Ayran were punished.
   
   The public for the most part remained passive; that was the
attitude in regard to anti-Jewish actions and measures in the
following years. Only a few joined in the rioting _ but there was no
rejection, no resistance worthy of mentioning. Reports speak of
consternation and shame, of pity, yes even disgust and horror. But
only a very few were sympathetic, gave practical solidarity,
assistance or help. All saw what happened, but the majority of them
looked away and said nothing. Also the churches were silent.
   The term Reichskristallnacht is today rightly seen as
inappropriate. But it described appropriately the mood and feelings
then: a mixture of embarassment, irony and playing down. Above all
it was the expression of painfully being moved and of ambivalance of
one's own feelings faced with open responsibility of the party and
state leadership.
   
   For the fate of the Germans and European Jews, Hitler's successes
were perhaps even more fateful than his crimes and misdeeds. The
years from 1933 to 1938, even from a distant retrospective and in
the knowledge of what followed, still are a fascinating thing today,
since throughout history there was hardly a parallel to Hitler's
triumphal procession during the first years.
   A reattaching of the Saarland, implementation of common military
duty, massive arming, conclusion of the German-British fleet
agreement, occupation of the Rhineland, the Olympic Summer Games in
Berlin, the annexation of Austria, and the Great German Reich, and
finally, just a few weeks before the November pogrom the Munich
Agreement, the dividing up of Czechoslovakia _ the Versailles treaty
was really only a scrap of paper, and the German Reich at once was
the hegemonial power on the old continent.
   For the Germans who overwhelmingly had felt the Weimar Republic
as the consquence of foreign, political humiliation, this all must
have appeared to be a miracle. And not only that, from massive
unemployment came full employment, from massive misery came a type
of prosperity for most levels. Instead of desperation and
hopelessness there was optimism and self-confidence.
   Didn't Hitler bring to reality what Wilhelm II had only promised,
that is to lead the Germans to glorious times? Wasn't he chosen by
Providence, a Fuehrer such as is given to a people only once in a
thousand years? Certainly in free elections Hitler had never gotten
a majority of the Germans behind him. But who wanted to doubt that
in 1938 a large majority of the Germans stood behind him, identified
with him and his policies? Certainly, there were some malcontent
grumblers who wanted no peace and quiet and were persecuted by the
SD (the Nazi security service) and the Gestapo. But most Germans _
and in fact from all levels, from bourgeoisie as well as from the
working class _ could be convinced in 1938 that they were to be
seeing in Hitler the greatest statesman of our history.
   And still something else cannot be overlooked. All of the
astounding successes were collectively and individually an
additional slap in the face for the Weimar system.
   And Weimar was not only synonymous with foreign policy weakness,
party quarrelling, and change of government, with economic misery,
with chaos, street fights and political confusion in a broad sense,
it was also a synonym for parliamentary democracy, for checks and
balances and citizens rights, for freedom of the press and freedom
to assemble, and finally for a maximum amount of Jewish assimilation
and emancipation.
   That means Hitler's successes discredited additionally above all
the parliamentarily established system of freedom, the democracy of
the Weimar itself. For many Germans there wasn't even the question
of which system to prefer. People enjoyed perhaps in some walks of
life fewer individual freedoms. But it was better for individuals
than previously. The Reich was undoubtedly great, yes greater and
more powerful than before. Hadn't the leaders of Great Britain,
France and Italy visited Hitler just then in Munich and aided him to
another one of these successes that hadn't been believed possible?
   And as far as the Jews were concerned, hadn't they claimed for
themselves in the past a role that wasn't right for them? Hadn't
they deserved being put back in their place? And above all, didn't
the propaganda _ apart from the wild exaggeration not to be taken
seriously _ correspond in essential points to their own conjectures
and convictions?
   And when it got so bad, as it was in November 1938, people could
still say, using the words of a contemporary _ what's it to us, look
away if it terrifies you. It is not our fate.
   Many Germans let themselves be blinded and seduced by the Nazis.
Many through their indifference made the crimes possible. Many
became criminals. Everyone must answer for himself the question of
guilt and its suppression.
   But what we must all be united against is the raising of
questions about historical truths, the miscalculation of the
victims, the renunciation of facts. Whoever wants to charge guilt,
whoever says that everything wasn't so _ or not completely so bad,
he is making an attempt to defend where there is no defense.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881111-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 1313EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NorthwestPilots 1stLd-Writethru a0540 11-11 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northwest Pilots, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0540,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mediation Request Postpones Strike Threat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with strike deadline vote; PICKS
UP 5th graf pvs, `Under mediation ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Mediation Board intervened in the
labor dispute between Northwest Airlines and its 4,800 pilots,
averting the possibility of a strike at midnight tonight.
   The board stepped in at the request of Northwest Chairman Steven
Rothmeier.
   Members of the Air Line Pilots Association voted overwhelmingly
Monday through Thursday to set a midnight strike deadline. But a
walkout is illegal under mediation, and the union will not strike,
said spokesman Tim Barzen.
   Contract talks between the carrier and pilots reached an impasse
Nov. 1 over wages, work rules and fringe benefits. Union spokesman
Pete Quortrup said negotiators disagree on more than 100 issues.
   With 85 percent of the union's pilots voting this week, nearly 97
percent said they would support a strike, union spokesman Andy
Murphy said today.
   Under mediation, wages and work rules remain unchanged. Mediators
handle negotiations until there is a settlement or an impasse, at
which point the board will offer arbitration.
   If either side rejects the offer, there would be a 30-day cooling
off period before Northwest could impose a contract or the union
could strike.
   ``We intend to schedule mediation sessions at an early date. As
soon as we get someone available,'' said Charles Barnes, executive
director of the National Mediation Board in Washington.
   Redmond Tyler, a Northwest spokesman, said the threat of a strike
did not appear to affect ticketing for flights over the weekend.
   Pilots are flying under two contracts _ one covering 2,000 pilots
who flew for Republic Airlines before its 1986 merger with
Northwest, the other covering 2,800 pilots who flew for Northwest or
have been hired since the merger.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881111-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 1338EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-UrbanArchaeologists Bjt   11-11 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Urban Archaeologists, Bjt,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Under Rumbling Traffic, Archaeologists Unearth 17th Century Boston</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a $9.25-a-day parking lot under an elevated
downtown highway, urban archaeologist Ricardo Elia is searching for
17th-century Boston.
   Elia and a team of Boston University archaeologists are using
trowels and brooms to probe repositories of urban detritus before
construction workers using dynamite reclaim the land forever to move
the Central Artery underground.
   ``You just couldn't conceive of someone getting a research grant
to rip up a parking lot under the artery and see what's there,''
Elia, who heads a 10-person BU archaeology team staying several
steps ahead of construction, said as traffic rumbled overhead
Thursday.
   After about a month of digging, the archaeologists have unearthed
the soggy timbers of a wharf that a John Eustis bought in 1709 on
property abutting what was then Boston's waterfront.
   The $846,000 federal- and state-funded project to search for
Colonial Boston is part of a gradual movement to recognize the
significance of what lies buried under America's cities.
   While maps, deeds, bills of sale and other historical documents
have been preserved, the physical remains of early America are
scarce, archaeologists said.
   Urban or historical archaeology is only as old as the National
Historical Preservation Act of 1966. Since then, New York,
Baltimore, Philadelphia, Alexandria, Va., Charleston, S.C., and
Savannah, Ga., all have let archaeologists examine land before
development.
   ``What we are getting nationwide are little snapshots on what
happened in the past in the centers of cities,'' said Ron Anzalone,
staff archaeologist for the federal Advisory Council on Historic
Preservation in Washington.
   ``We learn an awful lot about how Boston developed, about how
everyday life occurred, that you just can't get from tax records,''
he said. ``In many communities there would be no other way to know
about the early history and how it relates to the development of the
United States.''
   The university team has moved from Eustis' land a quarter mile to
the other shore of old Boston, digging under the asphalt on the site
of a 19th century mattress company warehouse and below that the 17th
century estate of John Codman.
   ``So much of Boston has been dug up that you've lost much of the
archaeological history already,'' Elia said. ``The 17th and 18th
centuries are just not very visible today.''
   Boston prides itself on history, yet very little remains of
Colonial Boston. In fact, the Paul Revere House in the North End is
the only 17th-century house standing, and it has been heavily
restored.
   One reason is that 1630 Boston was much smaller than 1988 Boston,
much of which consists of landfill upon which the city gradually
expanded. Another is that many of the city's old buildings burned
down.
   Elia said the planned excavation of 10 sites along the Boston
highway could indicate how houses were designed and built, what
people ate and how commerce occurred.
   Preliminary digging about one foot deep into a 40-by-20-feet
L-shaped site on the Blackstone Allright parking lot has revealed a
stone foundation of the three-story mattress warehouse. An elixir
bottle half-filled with a yellow liquid turned up Thursday.
   The deeper archaeologists go, the more artifacts they will find
on the site, which housed stables, outhouses and a variety of
buildings.
   So far, they have found shards of Wedgewood pots, a wide-bore
stem pipe, a layer of manure from a stable and other urban artifacts.
   The archaeologists used computer generated overlays of a 1630
outline of the Shawmut peninsula, modern maps and utility charts to
determine potential excavation sites along the multibillion-dollar
Central Artery project, scheduled to be completed in 1998.
   Three of the 10 sites have been excavated and the others should
be completed by mid-December. Archaeologists will spend the winter
analyzing timber samples and other artifacts before deciding whether
a more thorough digging is needed.
   Whatever they find, much more will remain hidden.
   ``You're digging in a city that has continued to build upon
itself since the beginning,'' said graduate student David Landon, a
staff archaeologist of the project.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
