<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL PARK, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mary and Gerald Peters wanted all of
their six children to have a part in naming the latest addition to
the family.
   The result: Eric Michael David Stephen Joshua Kevin Carl Quentin
Jesse Alexander William Peters.
   ``It was a little unique to me, but I have six other kids, and
each one of them wanted to give him a name,'' said Gerald Peters,
who has given three of the children multiple middle names.
   The parents picked Eric, Kevin, Carl and William, and the
siblings filled in the gaps for the baby, born Oct. 26.
   Gerald Peters began the tradition of multiple middle names,
belatedly and with his wife's approval, because he dislikes his
first name and wanted his children to have choices. He does,
however, like his middle name so much that all the boys have a
``William'' in their name.
   ``The children who don't have multiple middle names ask why,'' he
said. ``They think it's cool. They say, `Dad, how come you didn't
give us more names?'''
   Gerald William Jr., 12, contributed the name Stephen; Lucinda
Louise, 11, submitted David and Joshua; Terrence (but please call
him Terry) William, 7, recommended Michael; Nathanael (Fred)
Frederick William, 6, suggested Alexander.
   ``Matthew Lawrence William, 3, gave us Jesse, the only name he
could say,'' Peters said. ``Michelle Heather Sandra Louise Peters,
1{, is just a baby so we gave her Quentin. We figured this way, when
she got older, she wouldn't argue with us that she didn't get to
name him, too.''
   The rest of the baby's names came from his parents' desire for a
nice round number of middle names _ 10.
   But what do they call him for short?
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a pop quiz that even the teacher flunked.
   With more than 200 lawyers, jurors and other people crammed into
his King County Superior courtroom for the start of Washington's
Centennial celebration Thursday, Judge Gerard Shellan asked whether
anyone knew who was president of the United States when the state
joined the Union on Nov. 11, 1889.
   No one answered.
   ``It was Grover Cleveland,'' Shellan said. ``He was the president
of the United States who approved the admission of the state of
Washington into the Union.''
   Wrong. It was Benjamin Harrison, who took over from Cleveland
earlier in 1889 after beating him in the 1888 election.
   Shellan acknowledged his mistake later.
   ``I looked it up after bringing it up in court,'' Shellan said.
``I obviously should have looked it up first.''
</TEXT>
