<HEAD>Judge Rules Parents Have No Right To Children's Background</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge ruled that adoptive parents have no
constitutional right to records detailing abuses suffered by their
children before adoption.
   U.S. District Judge Barefoot Sanders also ruled Thursday that the
Texas Department of Human Services does not have to help pay for
psychiatric care needed later by children who were abused before
being adopted.
   The rulings were in connection with a lawsuit filed in May by six
sets of adoptive parents from the Dallas area.
   The parents charged that the state failed to disclose their
children's histories of abuse. One family said it learned of its
13-year-old adoptive son's sexual and physical abuse only after he
threatened to kill family members.
   The families had asked the court to compel the state to release
background information on their adopted children and provide
financial assistance of up to $20,000 a year in some cases.
   State officials maintain they provide parents with all essential
information about children with special needs before adoptions
become final.
