<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ArmisticeDay     11-11 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Armistice Day,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Royalty Join Armistice Day Commemoration in Paris</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Welsh Guards in bearskin caps and American
``doughboys' in vintage uniforms marched past Prince Charles and
President Francois Mitterrand on Friday in ceremonies marking the
70th anniversary of the end of World War I.
   Thousands of people lined the Champs Elysees under sunny skies
during the Armistice Day parade. Soldiers dressed in World War I
uniforms and modern French military units took part.
   Princess Diana, dressed in a black coat and veiled hat, stood
near her husband as bells rang out at the precise moment they
sounded on Nov. 11, 1918, announcing the surrender of Germany.
   The Armistice Day parade came on the last day of the British
royal couple's five-day visit to Paris. They also attended a
ceremony at Notre Dame Cathedral honoring British killed during
World War I.
   Mitterrand planned to visit the Armistice monument at Rethondes,
50 miles north of Paris, where French presidents pay homage every 10
years to countrymen killed in both world wars.
   The last president to make the Armistice pilgrimage to Rethondes
was Valery Giscard d'Estaing in 1978.
   Rethondes is where France surrendered to Hitler in 1940,
beginning four years of Nazi occupation.
   More than 10 million people died in World War I, one of the
bloodiest wars in history. The Treaty of Versailles and other
treaties that ended the war radically changed the face of Europe and
the Middle East.
   In Belgium, the Duke of Kent and several British World War I
veterans attended an Armistice Day ceremony at the Menen Gate in
Ieper.
   The arch, which straddles a road leading to the nearby town of
Menen, bears the names of nearly 55,000 British soldiers who fell in
the trenches of Flanders but whose remains have never been found.
   Buglers from the Ieper fire brigade played ``Taps'' to honor
those who fell.
   The Duke also attended services at Ieper's Anglican Church and at
the town's cathedral before visiting some of the many thousands of
war graves that dot the Flemish countryside.
   The ceremonies were attended by several British World War I
veterans, now in their nineties.
   The area around Ieper saw some of the fiercest fighting of the
war, culminating in the battle of Passchendaele on a muddy ridge
eight miles away.
   The area around this West Belgian town still lives with the
legacy of the war. The Belgian army uses a special bomb squad that
regularly retrieves explosive devices left from the war, including
unexploded cannisters containing poison gas.
   Last week, the squad found 156 German mustard gas shells at
Schoonaarde, 40 miles east of Ieper. The shells were discovered by a
contractor who was leveling a building site.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
