<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Jeffrey     11-11 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Jeffrey,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dancer, Choreographer Howard Jeffrey Dead At Age 53</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dancer and choreographer Howard Jeffrey, who
worked with Barbra Streisand and the late Natalie Wood in plays like
``West Side Story'' and movies like ``Funny Girl,'' has died of
complications from AIDS. He was 53.
   Jeffrey was born in Philadelphia and raised in Los Angeles where
he was a child radio actor and dancer who joined the Ballet Theatre
when he was 18.
   He died Nov. 2 in Los Angeles and will be memorialized in a New
York City service Nov. 18.
   After working as Jerome Robbin's chief aide on ``West Side
Story,'' Jeffrey became choreographer and teacher for its touring
companies and later performed a similar role for Miss Wood in the
film version of Leonard Bernstein's acclaimed music-drama.
   He worked with Miss Wood on ``Inside Daisy Clover'' and with
Barbra Streisand on ``Funny Girl'' and ``Funny Lady.' He was an
assistant to Gene Kelly for ``Hello Dolly'' and to Vincente Minnelli
for ``On A Clear Day You Can See Forever,'' again with Miss
Streisand.
   Jeffrey then entered film production and was associate producer
for ``The Seven Percent Solution,'' ``The Turning Point'' and
``Nijinsky.'' He produced two of Bette Midler's films, ``Divine
Madness'' and ``Jinxed,'' and Mel Brooks' ``To Be or Not to Be.''
   Survivors include his mother and brother.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
