<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MuseumTheft     11-11 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Museum Theft,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Artifacts Stolen From University Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 55-pound crystal ball believed to have been
made for the empress dowager of China and a 2,000-year-old bronze
statuette of the Egyptian god Osiris were stolen from the University
Museum, officials said Friday.
   The artifacts, displayed in locked cases, were discovered missing
Friday morning by a guard. They last were seen at 8:15 p.m. Thursday
night, said Laurie Fenlason, museum spokeswoman.
   The case containing the crystal ball was smashed, while the case
containing Osiris had been lifted and unscrewed from its base, Ms.
Fenlason said.
   Robert H. Dyson Jr., director of the museum, on the University of
Pennsylvania campus. Dyson declined immediate comment except to say
that the police and FBI were investigating.
   The crystal ball has been the central artifact on exhibit in the
museum rotunda. It was insured for $100,000, Ms. Fenlason said. The
ball is 10 inches in diameter and is made of rock crystal. It dates
from the late 19th century.
   The 10-inch statuette, valued at $15,000, dates to the Ptolemaic
era.
</TEXT>
