<1ST_LINE>r i AM-StalinVictims     11-11 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stalin Victims,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Artists Hold Concert in Memory of Stalin Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A concert featuring Soviet musicians, poets,
playwrights and artists will be staged here Sunday in support of an
officially sanctioned Soviet committee building a monument to Josef
Stalin's victims.
   The Adelphi Theater concert is intended to restore cultural works
repressed under Stalin's 29-year regime ``and the living work of
today ... (which) cannot proceed without the history of those who
were killed,'' said the organizer, actress Vanessa Redgrave.
   ``It is in prose and poetry the story of what Stalinist
bureaucracy is,'' she told a news conference.
   Ms. Redgrave and British film director Sir Richard Attenborough
will be among those addressing a rally before the concert, which
will include poetry and prose recitations, excerpts from plays,
songs and music.
   Among the performers will be British actress Susannah York,
American playwright Martin Sherman and Soviet poet Sergei Yursky.
   Proceeds from the concert at the 1,500-capacity theater will go
toward building a monument in Moscow to Stalin's victims.
   Under Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, Stalin and his
legacy have come in for increasingly severe criticism. In July, the
Communist Party Politburo approved the building of the monument.
   A public council to supervise the construction and maintenance of
the monument was formed in August. Among those selected for the
council were dissident and Nobel Prize laureate Andrei D. Sakharov
and poet Yevgeny Yevtushenko.
</TEXT>
