<HEAD>Medical Board Bars Gynecologist from Performing Surgery
^Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, `After a ...' to CORRECT that probe was
already under way when governor issued response; Contents may offend
some readers.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gynecologist accused by patients of
performing vaginal reconstructive surgery without their knowledge
has been barred from practicing surgery in Ohio while the state
medical board investigates.
   The board announced the action against Dr. James C. Burt in a
statement Thursday.
   ``The limitation, which was obtained through an agreement with
Dr. Burt, does not prevent the board from pursuing further
disciplinary action,'' the board said. ``The investigation of Dr.
Burt's medical practice remains an urgent priority.''
   Burt's attorney, Earl Moore, declined to comment on the board's
action.
   Some former patients have charged that Burt performed surgery
designed to enhance their sexual responsiveness while they were
under anesthesia for other procedures, and that the operation made
intercourse excruciatingly painful.
   After a CBS-TV report on the allegations Oct. 29 and the
disclosure that the board had been investigating Burt, Gov. Richard
Celeste called on the board to expedite its probe.
   Burt has said the picture CBS painted of him was ``100 percent
erroneous and false.''
   No criminal charges have been filed against the doctor.
   Several women have filed malpractice suits against Burk over
surgery they claimed injured them.
</TEXT>
