<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hirohito     11-11 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Watch For Blood Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors were monitoring Emperor Hirohito carefully
Friday for signs of more bleeding after his blood pressure and
temperature rose, palace officials said.
   Hirohito spent much of the morning sleeping, but talked actively
with his son, Crown Prince Akihito, when he visited during the
afternoon, Imperial Household Agency spokesman Kenji Maeda said.
   The emperor's fourth daughter, Atsuko Ikeda, and her husband also
visited the bedridden monarch, and said he appeared weary and only
whispered ``thank you'' to them, Kyodo News Service reported.
   Maeda said the 87-year-old emperor's blood pressure at late
afternoon was 138 over 60, compared with 110 over 54 the previous
day. A normal reading is about 120 over 80.
   Physicians were concerned that his higher blood pressure could
increase the chances of additional internal bleeding in the area of
his upper intestine, officials said.
   Several times since his condition worsened on Sept. 19, Hirohito
has discharged large amounts of blood from his bowels because of
internal bleeding. After each large discharge his blood pressure has
dropped dangerously, and doctors fear his weak body has become less
able to recover despite emergency blood transfusions.
   The emperor's temperature rose to 100.4 Friday from 99.5 on
Thursday, while his pulse rate climbed to 100 from 86, Maeda said.
Hirohito's normal temperature is about 95.9.
   Maeda said the emperor had not discharged any blood Friday for
the third straight day and was not given any transfusions. The
monarch has received 41 pints of blood since he fell ill.
</TEXT>
