<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-Beauty     11-11 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-Beauty,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Has First Beauty Pageant Since Communist Victory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-year-old university student was
crowned ``Miss Beauty'' this week in the first such contest in
Vietnam since the Communist Party came to power in 1975, Vietnamese
media said.
   The winner _ identified by the Vietnam News Agency as Bui Bich
Mai and by Radio Hanoi as Bui Bic Phuong _ received a tiara worth
about $70.
   The first-year student in the Foreign Languages Department of
Hanoi University beat nearly 90 contestants ranging from 16 to 28
years old.
   The first runner-up was Nguyen Thu Mai, a student at the Army
School of Arts, who received about $38.
   In the semifinal Wednesday, contestants wore summer dresses,
including the long national dress, the ``ao dai,'' and swimsuits,
Radio Hanoi said.
   Ten women were chosen as finalists Thursday in the contest held
in Hanoi.
   Other contestants received the titles ``Graceful Ao Dai,''
``Capital's Miss Elegance,'' ``Miss Fashionable,'' ``Miss Manners,''
and ``Person Who Makes the Earth Beautiful.''
   ``Apart from their gracefulness and charm, the contestants were
also required to answer questions about the Communist Youth Union
and society,'' the Vietnam News Agency said.
   The contest was sponsored by the Tien Phong, or Vanguard, weekly
publication for youth.
   ``This is the first such contest organized since the
reunification of the country and in honor of the 35th founding
anniversary of the weekly,'' the agency said.
   Vietnam has been ruled by a doctrinaire autocracy since North
Vietnam defeated U.S.-backed South Vietnam in 1975, but conditions
have been somewhat relaxed after more pragmatic leaders took office
in 1986.
</TEXT>
