<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Wildlife     11-11 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Wildlife,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Law to Crack Down on Wildlife Poachers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new law will take effect March 1 in China to
protect endangered wildlife from poaching that involves even the
state's security personnel, a pro-Beijing newspaper reported Friday.
   Frontier guards and armed police in some provinces have used
their weapons to wantonly hunt wildlife, the New Evening Post quoted
an unidentified official from the Chinese Ministry of Forestry as
saying.
   Illegal hunting of more than 20 endangered species such as the
giant panda and golden monkey is getting worse, the report said, and
the new law will be designed to put a stop to it.
   Other illegal activity such as smuggling wildlife products also
is on the rise, the report said, noting that 1,639 pounds of musk
was smuggled to Japan in the first four months of 1987. Since last
year, three giant panda skins and three golden monkey skins were
smuggled into Hong Kong, the newspaper said.
   Since 1986, authorities seized 251 red deer and elk that were
shot dead by hunters in Inner Mongolia. In Anhui province, more than
30 Yangtze River crocodiles were poached.
   Tigers and leopards in southern China were among other endangered
species bagged by hunters.
   The newspaper did not provide details of the laws provisions or
what penalties poachers would pay for hunting endangered species.
</TEXT>
