<2ND_LINE>AM-Jet Stowaway,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Landing Gear Jams; Stowaway's Remains Found In Wheel Well</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Contents of following may be offensive to some readers.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PALMA DE MAJORCA, Balearic Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities found the
remains of an apparent stowaway in the landing gear of a Boeing 737
after the aircraft had trouble lowering its wheels, officials said
Friday.
   The chartered Air Europa jet carrying 111 passengers left
Hanover, West Germany, on Thursday and landed on this Spanish island
in the Mediterranean.
   Authorities said the aircraft experienced problems with its
landing gear during its approach to Son San Joan Airport, forcing it
into a holding pattern for two hours.
   Once the right side of the landing gear lowered properly, the jet
landed without incident, Air Europa said in a statement.
   The ground crew subsequently found blood and other remains, a
ring and a piece of candy in a landing gear well, ``which led them
to believe in the existence of a stowaway,'' the Palma-based company
said.
   The crew informed local authorities of their findings, but no
body was found despite an intensive search, police said.
   Company director Tomas Cano was quoted by the Spanish national
news agency EFE Friday as saying the person who hid in the jet's
landing gear ``sentenced himself to death, due to the inevitably
fatal lack of oxygen in the well and the extremely low
temperatures'' during flights.
   Police in Hanover originally thought the stowaway may have been
an 11-year-old boy reported missing on Thursday. The boy had been
taken to a school bus by his mother but never arrived at school,
raising fears he may have tried to stow away on the Air Europa jet.
   But police said the youngster had fled to look for his father.
The boy's parents are separated, police said.
</TEXT>
