<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0648,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Efforts Resume For Regional Peace Settlement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 7th graf, ``Soviet deputy...'' to UPDATE
with comment from Angolan ambassador; picks up 8th graf pvs: ``But
South...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four nations resumed talks Friday on securing a
Cuban troop pullout from Angola and an independence plan for
South-West Africa, also known as Namibia.
   Delegations from South Africa, Cuba, Angola and the United
States, which is mediating, opened the new round with a series of
discussions, a South African spokesman said.
   The spokesman, Roland Darrol, said his delegation came to
Switzerland ``in a positive frame of mind.''
   No plans were immediately announced for full meetings of the four
sides, all of which have sent mid-level officials to the talks.
   The closed-door talks, part of a series begun in May, are due to
end Sunday. They are intended to prepare for a furtherround in
Brazzaville, Congo, the date of which have not been set.
   The goal is an accord on the withdrawal of an estimated 50,000
Cuban troops backing a Marxist government in Angola. A pullout
agreement is South Africa's condition for granting freedom to
South-West Africa, the former German colony between South Africa and
Angola that Pretoria has controlled for 73 years.
   Soviet deputy foreign minister Anatoly Adamyshin, in Geneva as
observer, said Thursday that the length and timing of the Cuban
pullout was the only remaining issue to be settled.
   Angola's ambassador to the United Nations, Manuel Pedro Pacavira,
said in New York an agreement on the withdrawal of Cuban troops is
near and may come during the current talks.
   But he said the troop withdrawal is not the major hurdle.
   ``We cannot say that the main obstacle (to an agreement) is the
timetable,'' Pacavira told reporters. He blamed South Africa's
``attitude of interference'' in Angola's affairs for the current
impasse in the talks.
   But South African delegation leader Neil van Heerden indicated he
would also raise an alleged breach by Angola of its pledge to keep
Namibian guerrillas north of the 16th parallel in Angola.
   Military units of the South-West African People's Organization
fighting for Namibian independence have bases in southern Angola.
   Pretoria originally proposed Nov. 1 as target date for
implementing a U.N. independence plan for Namibia.
   As it became clear that goal would not be met, a U.S. proposal in
early October reportedly called for Cuba to withdraw half of its
contingent from Angola by Aug. 1. The remaining troops were to be
confined to northern Angola and withdrawn in stages by the end of
1990.
   Cuba reportedly wants a 30-month timetable, six months longer
than that offered by Washington and Pretoria.
   Washington reportedly suggested Jan. 1 as a new Namibia target
date, with elections scheduled Aug. 1.
   But meeting the date seems unlikely, according to sources in
South Africa, because the U.N. says it would need at least six weeks
to assemble a peacekeeping force after the signing of an accord.
This would mean that an agreement would have to be signed by
mid-November.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
