<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FederalPay     11-11 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Federal Pay,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Hears Argument For Higher Judges' Pay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increasing numbers of judges are quitting the
federal bench because they can make far more money in private legal
practice, two former judges and the American Bar Association said
Friday in urging a pay increase for the jurists.
   ``The long neglect of the basic need of our federal judges for
fair and just salaries has reached the point where the effective
functioning of the federal court system is endangered,'' said Robert
D. Raven, president of the ABA, in testimony before a presidential
panel studying pay increases for top federal officials.
   Raven said an ABA review found that dozens of federal judges
intend to quit because they can earn more in private practice.
   Raven's statement was echoed by two former judges, Robert Duncan
of Columbus, Ohio, and Lynn C. Higby of Panama City, Fla. Both told
the commission they quit to earn more money.
   The panel is known formally as the President's Quadrennial
Commission on Executive, Legislative and Judicial Salaries and it
meets after every presidential election to review the salaries of
members of Congress, judges, and top executive-branch officials,
including Cabinet officers.
   If the panel recommends a pay increase and that proposal is
endorsed by President Reagan in the budget he sends Congress on Jan.
9, the hike would go into effect unless both the House and Senate
vote against it within 30 days.
   Members of Congress and federal judges are now paid $89,500,
while federal appellate judges are paid $94,500.
   The panel focused Friday on judges, hearing testimony that
lawyers in private practice can earn far more than the jurists.
Former Chief Justice Warren Burger told the panel earlier that
judicial pay should be raised to $150,000.
   ``Compensation is the single most important factor in the
decision of judges to shorten their tenure,'' said Raven. ``This
threat to the stability of the federal judiciary can be averted if
the promise of adequate judicial compensation is finally kept.''
   Duncan was a judge for 11 years, until he resigned in April 1985.
``A reason for my resignation was abysmally low pay,'' he said.
   ``In 1985, I was earning $76,000 per year, certainly compensation
substantially more than most Americans were earning, but grossly
less than lawyers with 33 years' experience,'' he said.
   Duncan said he liked being a judge and ``the decision to leave
the bench was agonizing.''
   But he accepted an offer from a Columbus law firm in 1985 because
``at age 57, I had limited productive years ahead and I also knew
that if I entered private practice, I could afford to educate our
youngest daughter, repair our house, my wife could retire and
finally, my earnings are somewhat comparable to the income earned by
a number of law school classmates.''
   Higby was a judge in Pensacola, Fla., until he quit in 1982 to go
back to a law firm.
   ``Fortunately, I was able to return to the private practice of
law earning as much, if not more, than when I went on the bench and
most importantly, was able to fulfill my obligation to my (three)
children to see that they had the same educational opportunity that
was given me by my parents,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
