<1ST_LINE>r i AM-East-West     11-11 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-East-West,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Ambassador Demands Follow-Up Conference In East</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief Soviet delegate to the 35-nation
Helsinki conference on European security and cooperation indicated
Friday that Moscow may jeopardize other agreements at the forum if
it isn't allowed to hold a human rights conference in 1991.
   At a news conference, Yuri B. Kashlev dismissed demands from the
United States and Britain for better Soviet human rights performance
before the West could agree to Moscow holding the conference, citing
what he called those countries' poor records on human rights.
   The Soviets have agreed to a proposal that the Moscow conference
be the third in a series of annual conferences on human rights
planned after the Vienna meeting finishes this year or early in 1989.
   The first two conferences are slated for Paris in 1989 and
Copenhagen in 1990.
   ``By and large, this is a very reasonable, optimum structure,''
Kashlev said in a speech to a closed-door plenary session of
diplomats from the 35 nations at the conference.
   ``But if someone wants to break a part of it, the whole structure
will be put in doubt,'' he added.
   He noted only one follow-up meeting in the Helsinki process had
been held in the East bloc since the Soviet Union, the United
States, Canada and all European nations bar Albania signed the
Helsinki Final Act in 1975.
   ``Those from across the ocean are virtually saying that no
follow-up meetings can be conducted in Socialist countries,''
Kashlev said. ``We will not allow that to happen.''
   The dispute over the Moscow conference is one of the main
outstanding quarrels to be resolved before the Vienna conference,
started two years ago, can wind up.
   Diplomats from East, West and neutral nations say that most other
outstanding disagreements have been resolved, paving the way for new
East-West talks on limiting conventional arms and human rights
provisions hailed as unprecedented on all sides.
   Asked about recent police crackdowns in Czechoslovakia, Kashlev
noted that ``there are some developments which cause disputes'' in
East bloc countries, but defended the Czechoslovak behavior as being
in accordance with national laws.
   ``Many of the events causing regret in the West are conducted
with provocative intent,'' he charged.
   Czechoslovakia's recent behavior has provoked speeches from the
U.S. and British delegations charging Prague is violating the spirit
and the letter of the Helsinki accords on security, cooperation and
human rights in Europe.
</TEXT>
