<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 1641EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-RIGovRecount     11-11 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-RI Gov Recount,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sundlun Requests Recount in Governor's Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIMBERLY M. SHEARIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Bruce G. Sundlun's campaign on
Friday asked for a recount in the gubernatorial election he narrowly
lost to incumbent Gov. Edward DiPrete.
   Kenneth Haupt, Sundlun's campaign manager, hand-delivered the
letter to the Board of Elections, where workers labored through the
Veterans Day holiday to count about 16,000 absentee ballots. Sundlun
hoped those ballots would decrease further the margin between
himself and DiPrete.
   ``It was a very close election, and we thought we owed it to the
campaign staff and all the people who worked hard for him,'' Haupt
said. ``We also owed it to Bruce and his piece of mind to make sure
that the vote that was reported on Tuesday was in fact what happened
on Election Day.''
   Absentee ballots from nine communities, including strongly
Democratic Providence, added 143 votes to the unofficial 6,299
margin by which DiPrete led Sundlun.
   The Elections Board had counted about 5,000 of the mailed-in
ballots and expected to finish counting Saturday, said Janet
Armstrong, secretary to the board.
   Sundlun's spokeswoman, Eileen Crochiere, said neither Haupt nor
Sundlun was alleging fraud.
   ``We're pretty realistic that there may be some shifting in the
numbers, but it probably won't change,'' Haupt said.
   DiPrete, who was out of town, had said Wednesday that if he were
in Sundlun's position, he probably would consider asking for a
recount.
   Joseph DiStefano, Elections Board chairman, said any recount
would begin Wednesday and take at least three days.
   The recount entails going to all 1,800 voting machines, opening
the back with representatives from each campaign present, and
comparing the numbers on the meters in the machines with the numbers
reported on sheets filled out by precinct workers, DiStefano said.
   State police are guarding the machines, Ms. Armstrong said.
   Ms. Armstrong said the election results cannot be certified until
after the recount. The last statewide recount was in the 1986
attorney general's race, and did not change the outcome, DiStefano
said.
   With all but one precinct reporting from Tuesday's election,
DiPrete's unofficial machine total was 195,283, or 51 percent, to
Sundlun's 188,984, or 49 percent.
</TEXT>
