<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Shuttle,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Silent on Flight Plans for Their Shuttle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviets on Friday were silent about plans for
the maiden flight of their space shuttle Buran despite statements
from a top space official the previous day that an announcement
could be expected.
   ``Tomorrow we'll finish all preliminary experiments with Energia
and Buran,'' Alexander I. Dunaev, director of the Soviet commercial
space agency Glavkosmos, told a news conference Thursday. ``Tomorrow
we'll be able to tell you the exact time of launch.''
   The first attempt at launching the Buran _ which is Russian for
snowstorm _ was scrubbed Oct. 29 at only 51 seconds before blastoff
when a computer sensed that an equipment platform had not pulled far
enough away from Energia, the booster rocket that will carry the
orbiter aloft on its first unmanned mission.
   State-run Radio Moscow reported Tuesday that Buran and Energia
were on the launch pad at the Baikonur space center in Kazakhstan in
Soviet Central Asia, and said the shuttle's launch would take place
in the next few days.
</TEXT>
