<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Cosby,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Gets Reprieve As Cosby Signs for Another Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC can heave a sigh of relief _ Bill Cosby has
agreed to keep his top-rated ``The Cosby Show'' on the network for
another season.
   The show, which premiered in 1984, turned Thursday night into a
ratings blockbuster for NBC and made the network, which had never
previously won a season, into the No. 1 network four years in a row.
   NBC Entertainment President Brandon Tartikoff said he was
``ecstatic'' about the announcement.
   ```The Cosby Show' has been the symbol of success and quality at
NBC for the past five years,'' Tartikoff said. ``Knowing that it
will return for the 1989-90 season allows an entire company to sleep
better at night.''
   Cosby had always said he would only do the show for five seasons,
which would have made this season its last on the air.
   ``I will work even harder to ensure that people get what I
consider to be quality,'' Cosby said in a statement released
Thursday. ``I love my job and take great pride in doing it.''
   Cosby stars as Heathcliff Huxtable, a Brooklyn obstetrician with
a lawyer wife and a brood of five often exasperating children.
   The sit-com was a hit from its debut on Sept. 17, 1984, and has
been the No. 1-rated prime-time network television show for three
seasons in a row. Only ``All in the Family'' managed the same feat,
ranking first for five years in a row in the early '70s.
   The show won three Emmys in 1985, for best comedy series, writing
and direction. The show has also won a Peabody award, three NAACP
Image awards and a Humanitas award.
