<2ND_LINE>AM-Pit Bull Attack,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Killed by Pair of Pit Bull Dogs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two pit bull terriers were in the custody of
an animal control warden Friday after they attacked and killed a
graduate student who was on his way to a friend's house, authorities
said.
   Kevin B. Cull, 25, of De Kalb, suffered severe bites on his
ankles, legs, hips and arms. He taken to Central Du Page Hospital,
where he died Thursday night, said hospital spokeswoman Trish
Hummell.
   DuPage County Coroner Richard Ballinger speculated the injuries
were sustained shortly before Cull was found and said an inquest was
scheduled.
   Cull was attacked as he was walking up a driveway to visit
friends, police said. After encountering the dogs, Cull apparently
retreated to his car, where he was found by another houseguest.
   The houseguest took Cull to the Kane County Sheriff's Department,
Sheriff F. John Randall said.
   A radio operator at the sheriff's office said he did not know who
owned the dogs or the name of the friend. Authorities said no
arrests had been made.
   The dogs were captured but no decision had been made Friday on
whether to destroy them, officials said.
   Cull was a graduate student in analytical chemistry at Northern
Illinois University.
