<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 1616EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-USNavy     11-11 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-US Navy,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ministry Reportedly Tried To Hush Errant U.S. Navy Missiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Navy destroyer fired practice missiles
dangerously close to a Japanese coast guard vessel, and the Foreign
Ministry tried to hush up the incident, a Transport Ministry
spokesman said Friday.
   The Foreign Ministry asked a top Transport Ministry official not
to report Wednesday incident, in which the USS Towers fired the
missiles that landed behind the Japanese ship in Japanese
territorial waters, the spokesman said.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman denied his ministry tried to cover
up the incident. By custom, both ministry spokesman spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Japanese news reports quoted the top Transport Ministry official
as saying the incident, which took place outside the destroyer's
designated firing zone, could have violated international law.
   The Foreign Ministry spokesman identified the top transport
official quoted in the press reports as Transport Minister Shintaro
Ishihara. But the Transport Ministry spokeman would not identify the
official.
   The Towers was conducting firing drills about 10 miles off the
Boso Peninsula east of Tokyo when it fired the missiles that landed
about 1,000 feet behind the coast guard patrol boat Uraga. No
injuries or damages were reported.
   Practice missiles contain an inert, or dummy, warhead and do not
explode.
   Japan claims territorial waters about 13 miles from shore.
   Some of the 3,230-ton Uraga's 46 crew members reported seeing
15-foot columns of water when the missiles hit.
   A Japanese Defense Agency official told Kyodo News Service that
it ``was like firing a pistol in Ginza,'' a bustling shopping
district in Tokyo.
   The U.S. Navy expressed regret Thursday after the coast guard
complained, the Foreign Ministry spokesman said.
   Adm. Huntington Hardisty, commander of U.S. Pacific forces,
called on Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita and Foreign Minister
Sosuke Uno to apologize, the spokesman said.
   He said the Navy is investigating the incident.
   A U.S. military spokesman, Marine Sgt. Jake Rodriguez, said there
would be no comment on the incident before Monday, and U.S.
diplomats were not available because of Veterans Day, a U.S.
national holiday.
   The Foreign Ministry spokesman quoted Hardisty as saying he also
regretted stray bullets hitting local residences during military
drills on Okinawa in southwestern Japan, adding that those accidents
were also under investigation.
   U.S. forces on Okinawa have been involved in a series of recent
accidents, including an October fire on a U.S. Marine base that
burned 30 acres of woodland.
   About 46,000 U.S. servicemen are stationed in Japan.
</TEXT>
