<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ZooPanda     11-11 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zoo Panda,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panda Crowds in Cincinnati Below Projections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crowds visitng the Cincinnati Zoo to see a
giant panda have not met expectations, and there could be a
shortfall in revenue to for an international program to encourage
panda breeding, officials said.
   The 290-pound Chia Chia arrived in September from the London Zoo.
The 16-year-old male will stay until Nov. 28, when he is to move on
to permanent new quarters at the Chapultepec Zoo in Mexico City to
take part in a breeding program.
   When the Cincinnati Zoo opened its giant panda exhibit Sept. 3,
officials predicted 500,000 people would visit, bringing in $200,000
to fund a permanent panda home in Mexico and perhaps as much as
$400,000 more for an international panda conservation fund.
   But with 17 days remaining, zoo officials are not sure the
$200,000 has been raised by the 300,000 people who have come to see
Chia Chia.
   ``We're hoping we at least make that,'' zoo executive director Ed
Maruska said.
   Most of the money raised so far from the panda is earmarked for
the Chapultepec Zoo, which has the best record outside pandas'
native China for breeding the animals.
   That would leave little for the conservation fund that is to be
jointly administered by the London and Cincinnati zoos. The fund was
a key point Cincinnati Zoo officials used in winning U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service permission to exhibit Chia Chia.
   The zoo advanced the Chapultepec Zoo $120,000, Maruska said. He
said his zoo will likely pay the additional $80,000 even if revenues
after expenses do not reach that.
   ``I can't speak for the Zoological Society, but I don't see how
we could do anything else,'' Maruska said.
</TEXT>
