<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Inmates-Asbestos     11-11 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Inmates-Asbestos,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Inmates Claim Asbestos Exposure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Current and former prison inmates have sued
the Texas Department of Corrections, claiming some prison work
details forced them to handle asbestos without protective equipment.
   The suit, filed this week in Travis County district court by 23
current and seven former prisoners, said the inmates breathed
asbestos particles and the substance ``became packed in (their)
noses, mouths, eyes and hair.''
   The inmates, seeking unspecified damages, claim the department
violated their civil rights and was negligent.
   Lung tests have been performed on some inmates, and ``the records
reflect that the tests are given because of exposure to asbestos,''
the suit said. It didn't say whether the inmates developed
asbestos-related illness.
   TDC spokesman David Nunnelee said, ``I'm not going to respond to
any of that while this is in litigation.''
   Emily Young, a Dallas lawyer handling the suit, said the inmates
contacted her, but she declined to comment further.
   The lawsuit said the inmates were ordered to remove asbestos
insulation with their bare hands and without breathing devices or
other protective equipment.
   ``The asbestos was then thrown on the floor, and broomswept, dry,
by other inmates,'' the lawsuit said. ``The sweeping of the dry
asbestos fibers would cause the previously airborne asbestos fibers
to again become airborne.''
   The inmates stuffed the insulation into garbage bags that were
thrown into pickups, the suit said. Then, it said, ``prison guards
ordered one or more inmates to physically search through the bags,
completely unprotected, for inmates who might be trying to escape.''
</TEXT>
