<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AstronautHomecoming     11-11 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Astronaut Homecoming,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iowans Honor Discovery Astronauts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLINTON, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two astronauts who flew aboard the space
shuttle Discovery returned to their home state Friday to the cheers
of hundreds of flag-waving parents and children.
   A high school band struck up the national anthem while George
``Pinky'' Nelson and David Hilmers stood at attention on a flatbed
truck bearing a sign, ``Welcome Heroes. The Pride of Clinton
County.''
   ``Thank you for playing the national anthem,'' Hilmers said.
``Ever since the mission, hearing the national anthem gives me a
particular sense of emotion.''
   Hilmers said he felt anxious on the launch pad moments before the
Sept. 29 liftoff, but thoughts of home calmed him.
   ``I knew back here in Clinton County that many prayers were going
up with us,'' he said. ``It made the launch much, much easier.''
   The successful Discovery mission revived the U.S. space shuttle
program, which had grounded since the Challenger exploded on Jan.
28, 1986, killing its seven crew members.
   Nelson, 38, born in Charles City, and Hilmers, who was born in
Clinton but reared in DeWitt, were greeted by an enthusiastic crowd
of people craning necks and pointing fingers as the airplane
carrying the astronauts landed at the tiny airport here.
   ``Those two men are real heroes who were willing to go up in
space after that tragic Challenger accident,'' said Paul Eastland,
73, of Clinton. ``We're all pround of them.''
   Behind Eastland stood Betty and Joe Soletski of De Witt.
   ``All of them are really special _ they have to be to take that
job,'' Mrs. Soletski said.
   ``If I was young enough, I'd like to go. I'd love to go on one of
those shuttle trips,'' her husband said. ``I think that's where our
future lies anyway.''
   Later at a school, the astronauts recounted their experiences in
space. They also told students not to forget Veterans Day.
   ``What Veterans Day is to me is that it means there are things in
life far more important than life itself,'' Hilmers said. ``There
were people who felt their country was important enough that they
risked their lives for it.''
   ``Pinky and I, we felt returning the nation to space was a goal
worth risking our lives for,'' he said.
</TEXT>
