<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HoagieHassle     11-11 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hoagie Hassle,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen Cleared of A-Salt on State Trooper's Sandwich</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FERNDALE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge cleared a convenience store clerk of
disorderly conduct for serving an oversalted ham sandwich _ a
practical joke that a trooper with high blood pressure found in bad
taste.
   Trooper William Cruz testified Thursday that although ham is
naturally salty, he is a ``picky eater'' and knew that salt had been
added to the hoagie state Trooper Barry Gaston picked up for him at
a 7-Eleven store on July 24.
   Cruz's supervisor, Cpl. Joseph Fuentes, said he tasted the
sandwich and assigned Gaston to investigate. Store clerk David
Uriarte, 16, and Paul Newmayer, 21, of Ottsville, were charged
shortly afterward.
   Fuentes noted at the time that Cruz's high blood pressure could
be aggravated by salt, and said the charge was a message to
pranksters not to mess with troopers' food. But Ferndale District
Justice Elizabeth Leonard acquitted the teen-ager after a 2{-hour
trial, and even the local prosecutor belitted the troopers' bid for
no-salt assurance.
   ``They must not have had anything to do that day,'' Bucks County
District Attorney Alan Rubenstein said of the decision to
investigate.
   Newmayer was convicted earlier of disorderly conduct, which is
punishable by up to a $300 fine. He testified that while waiting at
the 7-Eleven to meet some friends, he put extra salt on the
ham-and-cheese hoagie. He said Uriarte was ``in'' on the practical
joke, but Uriarte denied any part in the tampering.
   Rubenstein said he considered the charges so ridiculous he would
not prosecute the case if Newmayer's conviction got to the Common
Pleas Court level on appeal.
   ``If messing up food were a criminal offense, my mother-in-law
would be in jail,'' Rubenstein told the Philadelphia Daily News.
</TEXT>
