<DOCNO> AP881111-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 1807EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Voyager-Neptune     11-11 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Voyager-Neptune,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Adjusts Voyager 2's Trajectory To Neptune</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Voyager 2 spacecraft, flying through
space 2.6 billion miles from Earth, fired its thrusters Friday to
change course for its August 1989 picture-taking encounter with the
planet Neptune, NASA said.
   ``Responding to radio signals radioed from Earth, Voyager 2 fired
its hydrazine thrusters for three minutes and 29 seconds beginning
at 6:55 a.m. PST,'' said a statement issued by the space agency's
Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
   Flight engineering manager Lanny Miller said radio signals sent
to Earth by the space probe indicated the maneuver succeeded.
   The pre-planned course correction will bring Voyager 2 some 6,200
miles closer to the solar system's eighth planet, but another major
maneuver next April and several subsequent but minor trajectory
changes will be required before the Neptune flyby, said laboratory
spokeswoman Mary Beth Murrill.
   The spacecraft _ which passed by Jupiter in 1979, Saturn in 1981
and Uranus in 1986 _ is scheduled to sweep within 3,000 miles of
Neptune's cloud tops at 9 p.m. PDT next Aug. 24, taking pictures
with its television camera.
   Five hours later, it will fly within 24,000 miles of Neptune's
moon Triton, which scientists believe may have lakes of liquid
nitrogen.
   Murrill said Voyager 2 is 414.7 million miles from Neptune, one
of the solar system's giant, gaseous outer planets.
   Radio commands to the probe and its response signals are
transmitted through large, dish-shaped radio antennae that make up
the Deep Space Network operated by the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration in Spain, Australia and Goldstone, Calif.
   Voyager 2 is so far away that the signals take four hours to
reach it, even traveling at the speed of light.
   The Neptune encounter will be the last of the so-called ``grand
tour'' of the outer planets by the Voyager probes. Voyagers 1 and 2
were launched from Cape Canaveral, Fla., in 1977. Voyager 1, which
visited Jupiter in 1979 and Saturn in 1980, now is headed out of the
solar system.
   Scientists have called the Voyager mission humanity's most
productive space exploration effort because the two picture-taking
probes learned hundreds of times more about the outer planets than
all previous studies combined.
   NASA scientists have said that by 1995, when both probes are
searching for the edge of the solar system, the total cost of the
mission will be about $920 million, which is less than half what the
Pentagon spends during one workday.
   Among key Voyager discoveries were active volcanos spewing sulfur
on Jupiter's moon Io, an icy volcanism that produced glacier-like
flows on some of the Saturnian and Uranian moons, and the discovery
of at least 17 previously unknown moons: three at Jupiter, at least
four at Saturn and 10 orbiting Uranus.
   The probes also discovered new rings encircling Jupiter, Saturn
and Uranus; orange smog and ethane-methane rain on Saturn's moon
Titan, and dozens of giant hurricanes on Jupiter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881111-0186 </DOCNO>
