<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--NoCrabs     11-11 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--No Crabs,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>S.F. Crews Find Few Crabs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crab fleet is returning with empty pots
this week, suggesting crabs are scarce along the coast near San
Francisco.
   Last year, the catch came to a little more than 3 million pounds
in the coastal region between Half Moon Bay and Bodega Bay. That was
the biggest catch since 1959-60.
   The catch in the 1950s generally ran about 4 million pounds, but
fell to 400,000 pounds or less by the late 1960s. It jumped back in
1986-87 to 1.6 million pounds.
   This year's season opened Tuesday, but most boats stayed in to
allow crew members time to vote. The weather was bad Wednesday, but
by Thursday, it became evident that crabs were scarce.
   ``It's not even an eighth of what the boats got last year,'' said
Joe Cincotta, manager of the Alioto Fish Co. ``Last year, they got
eight to 12 crabs per pot. Today, it was two or three.''
   Phil Swartzell of the state Department of Fish and Game said the
marketing agreement set a price of $1.50 a pound.
</TEXT>
