<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GravureFire     11-11 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gravure Fire,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Standard Gravure Hurt But Not Immobilized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion crippled almost half the
presses at a company that publishes magazines for newspapers around
the country, but its president said Friday that production demands
will be met.
   ``We will handle all of our customers needs through industry
support and off-loading of business to other people in our
industry,'' said Michael Shea, president of Standard Gravure Corp.
   The explosion Thursday night ripped through the huge plant,
injuring 20 people and forcing the evacuation of an adjacent
building that houses Kentucky's largest newspaper.
   Shea said three of the plant's seven presses were damaged in the
blast and two fires which preceded it.
   Standard Gravure publishes Parade magazine as well as magazines
for newspapers in Dallas, Detroit, Pittsburgh and St. Louis. The
company also prints Sunday newspaper inserts and catalogs and
distributes to all 50 states.
   Shea could not estimate the amount of the damage, but on
Thursday, company spokesman Jack Uhl said the loss would be
``substantial.'' One or more of the $10 million presses may have to
be substantially rebuilt, Uhl said. The company is insured.
   The next two weeks would be critical, Shea said. ``We don't know
how much longer it might take to get back into total operation. He
said he hoped to have the four undamaged presses running by late
Friday.
   The plant, which employs about 475 people, was open Friday, and
Shea said workers would continue to ``come to work for the immediate
future.''
   Employees received a memo Friday detailing the events of Thursday
night.
   Eighteen of the injured were firefighters, many of whom were
blown off their feet by the force of the explosion at about 7:25
p.m. Of the seven who remained hospitalized Friday in Humana
Hospital-University of Louisville, four were listed in fair
condition; two in the burn unit were listed in fair condition, and
one in the critical care unit was in stable condition, a spokeswoman
said.
   Officials said most of the firefighters suffered burns on their
faces and hands, and one suffered a fractured skull.
   Two Standard Gravure employees were listed in stable condition at
Methodist Evangelical Hospital, also suffering burns on their faces
and hands.
   The Courier-Journal, housed in an adjacent building, published an
eight-page edition that was limited in circulation to the metro
Louisville area. Some of the newspapers were printed at the
Lexington Herald-Leader under an emergency agreement, while the rest
came off the Courier's home presses.
</TEXT>
