<1ST_LINE>r w AM-B-1BGrounding 1stLd-Writethru a0663 11-11 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-B-1B Grounding, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0663,320</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS top 3 grafs to update with 48 planes inspected</NOTE>
<HEAD>Air Force Nears Halfway Point in Safety Checks of Bombers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force had completed safety inspections
of nearly half of its B-1B bombers by late Friday in the effort to
return the grounded fleet to flight status in the wake of a crash in
Texas.
   Two days after the fleet was grounded following Tuesday's crash
near Abilene, Texas, 48 of the 98 long-range bombers had passed the
mandatory inspections, said Capt. Julie Holland, a spokeswoman for
the Strategic Air Command in Omaha, Neb. She said no further
announcement would be made until next week.
   The check-ups, which require about three hours per plane, were
going smoothly, she added.
   The bombers were grounded Wednesday, one day after a B-1B crashed
and burned near Dyess Air Force Base, Texas, outside Abilene. The
crew of four managed to eject safety.
   The plane was the second B-1B to be lost in 14 months.
   There has been no official comment on the cause of Tuesday's
accident, although witnesses reported seeing fire around the plane's
left two engines before the crash. The grounding order specified a
mandatory inspection of electric, fuel and hydraulic fluid lines.
   SAC, which is responsible for land-based nuclear bomber and
missile forces, has described the grounding and inspection order as
a ``normal precaution'' in the wake of a major accident.
   The bombers have been deployed at Dyess; Ellsworth AFB, S.D.;
Grand Forks AFB, N.D., and McConnell AFB, Kan.
   According to Holland, 16 B-1B's at Dyess have so far been
inspected; 5 at Ellsworth; 13 at McConnell, and 8 at Grand Forks.
   The four-engine, swing-wing B-1B is designed to fill the gap
between the aging fleet of B-52 bombers and the new B-2 ``Stealth''
bomber, the first of which is to be unveiled later this month.
   The B-1B, built by Rockwell International Corp., has a maximum
speed of about 1,000 mph and a range of more than 7,000 miles.
</TEXT>
