<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0652 11-11 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0652,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Blames U.S. For Impeding Peace Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to include request for emergency extension;
PICKS up 5th `The United States'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega accused the
Reagan administration Friday of sabotaging a meeting of Central
American leaders and renewed his call for a peace zone in the region.
   ``What impedes these talks ... are the American policies, the
American pressures that do not rule out a solution by force,'' the
president said to a group of politicians and lawmakers from
Honduras, Guatemala, Costa Rica and El Salvador, all of which are
U.S. allies.
   Central American presidents had considered meeting later this
month about the peace plan they signed Aug. 7, 1987. The pact,
written by President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica, seeks to end wars in
Nicaragua, El Salvador and Guatemala.
   Nicaragua's official Radio Sandino reported Friday that Ortega
asked the National Assembly to extend a 30-day state of emergency
imposed Oct. 20, two days before Hurricane Joan struck. An emergency
in effect since 1982 was lifted last January to comply with the
regional peace plan.
   The United States backs the Nicaragua rebels, known as Contras,
in their 7-year-old war to oust the leftist Sandinista government.
   Ortega sharply criticized the United States for interfering in
the affairs of the Central American nations.
   ``The attitude of the American government tries to condition aid,
tries to say to the Central American governments, `here is what we
will do and how we will do it,' (and) interfere in decisions taken
within the constitutional mark,'' Ortega said.
   The United States cut off aid to the Sandinistas in 1981, almost
two years after they took power in a 1979 revolutionary war.
President Reagan on Thursday renewed a trade embargo started in 1985.
   The Sandinista president called on the nations in the region to
unite ``to convert Central American into a zone of peace, a neutral
zone, free of all foreign military presence.''
   Foreign military advisers from the Soviet bloc, especially Cuba,
are in Nicaragua. U.S. troops or military representatives are in the
other four nations.
   Ortega called on Central American nations to work ``to contain
the growth of arms and look for a rational balance of force.''
   Nicaragua's neighbors, especially Honduras and El Salvador, say
that the Sandinista government threatens the region by maintaining
300,000 people under arms, including the armed forces, militia and
reserves.
   The Managua meeting, sponsored by the European Economic
Community, was held to discuss the formation of a Central American
parliament.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
