<2ND_LINE>AM-Oregon-Congress,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smith Narrowly Wins Re-Election To Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Denny Smith won a fifth term in
Congress with a margin of 670 votes over Democratic challenger Mike
Kopetski after the final ballots were counted Friday in Oregon's 5th
District race.
   The final, unofficial tally showed 111,157 votes for Smith and
110,487 for Kopetski, a state representative.
   The election hinged on some 20,000 absentee and previously
uncounted ballots in Clackamas County.
   The margin of victory was great enough to avoid an automatic
recount.
   Recounts are automatic if the victory margin is less than
one-fifth of 1 percent of the total votes cast.
   Smith's re-election leaves the House with 174 Republicans and 259
Democrats. Two races, one in Florida and one in New York, remained
too close to call, but Democrats held narrow leads in both contests.
</TEXT>
