<1ST_LINE>r i AM-TerroristAppeal     11-11 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Terrorist Appeal,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Upholds Sentences in 1985 Airport Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court upheld on Friday the conviction of
terrorist Abu Nidal and two other Palestinian guerrillas for a 1985
Rome airport attack in which 16 people were killed, television
stations reported.
   The Rome Court of Appeals confirmed life sentences imposed in
February on Abu Nidal and Rashid el-Hamieda, described as a top
lieutenant, and the 30-year sentence given Mahmoud Ibrahim Khaled.
Only Khaled is in custody.
   More than 80 people were wounded in assaults with grenades and
automatic weapons on the check-in counters of TWA and the Israeli
airline El Al at Leonardo da Vinci airport the morning of Dec. 27,
1985.
   Four Americans were among the dead, including an 11-year-old
girl. A nearly simultaneous attack at the Vienna airport cost four
lives, including those of two terrorists, and 47 people were wounded.
   Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabry al-Banna, and Hamieda were
accused of organizing the Rome airport attack.
   All three men were convicted of massacre and illegal arms
possession. Khaled could be released on parole in about 14 years.
   Abu Nidal's group, called the Fatah Revolutionary Council, has
been blamed since 1972 for more than 100 attacks in Europe, Asia and
the Middle East. He split with Palestine Liberation Organization
chief Yasser Arafat in 1973.
</TEXT>
