<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-11 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Falls in the Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell Friday in the Rocky Mountains, dumping 10 inches on
Summitville in southern Colorado and whitening the ski slopes at
Alta, Utah, with 6 inches.
   Most of the nation had dry, seasonably cool weather, but showers
and thunderstorms struck northern Texas and southern Oklahoma, and
there was rain at the lower elevations of Colorado and northwestern
New Mexico.
   A snow advisory was in effect for the mountains of Colorado and
south-central mountains of Wyoming, where 4 to 6 more inches of snow
was expected at elevations above 8,000 feet.
   The storm, one of several from the Pacific that have brought snow
to the Colorado mountains this week, was accompanied by winds that
at times reduced visibility and made driving hazardous on mountain
passes.
   The Colorado Avalanche Information Center said the recent
snowstorms already have raised the snowpack in the northern Colorado
mountains to 2 to 3 feet, with drifts of 4 to 5 feet above
timberline.
   Brisk southeastery winds accompanied the dry air across much of
the central United States, while blustery northwest winds blew
across New England. Gale warnings continued in effect along the
coast of Washington and Oregon.
   The Southeast and Southwest enjoyed sunny skies with temperatures
in the 60s and 70s. In the North, temperatures rose only into the
30s in the upper Mississippi Valley and Great Lakes region and
reached the 40s in the northern Plains. Southern Florida and extreme
southern Texas warmed into 80s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 26
degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 88 degrees at Harlingen, Texas.
   The low for the nation early Friday was 16 degrees at Mason City,
Spencer and Waterloo, all in Iowa.
   Lights in the sky over Vermont early Friday were believed to have
been one of two families of meteorites that are visible during the
middle of November.
   It was 48 years ago on Nov. 11 that a blizzard struck the Great
Lakes and upper Midwest, killing more than 154 people, including 59
dead in shipwrecks on Lake Michigan. Up to 17 inches of snow fell in
Iowa, where thousands of cattle died, and whole towns were isolated
by huge snowdrifts.
   For Saturday, the National Weather Service forecast called for
showers and thunderstorms from central Texas and eastern Oklahoma
across the Tennessee Valley and the central Gulf Coast states; rain
from the middle and upper Mississippi Valley across the Ohio Valley
and the Great Lakes region, with snow near Lake Superior. In the
West, rain was forecast from the northern and central Pacific coast
across the northern half of the Plateau. Fair to partly sunny skies
were expected elsewhere.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 40s across most of the
northern United States, but with highs only in the upper 30s from
Minnesota to upper Michigan and in northern Maine; above 70 from
Southern California through much of Texas to Florida and southern
Georgia, with highs in the 80s in south-central Texas and the
Florida peninsula; in the 50s and 60s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
