<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-NearMiss     11-11 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Near Miss,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Says Two Jetliners Narrowly Missed Collision at Toronto Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two jetliners carrying 201 people on domestic
flights came within 1,700 feet of colliding after taking off from
Toronto's Pearson International Airport, the Toronto Star reported
Friday.
   It said one plane went into a dive to avoid the other in the
incident Sunday. No injuries were rported.
   Denis Begin, an investigator for the Canadian Aviation Safety
Board, was quoted by the newspaper as saying the planes should have
been at least 3.1 miles apart with 990 feet between altitude levels.
The Star said the two planes came as close as 1,700 feet and one was
flying at a level only 98 feet above the other.
   Near misses are not routinely reported in Canada and the Star
said it learned of the incident through a passenger who called to
report it.
   It said the incident involved a Canadian Airlines Boeing 737 with
90 people on board that was leaving for Montreal and a Wardair
Airbus 310 with 111 people that was headed for Ottawa.
   Passenger Tom Nelson, a Toronto electronics engineer who was on
the Canadian Airlines flight, told the Star that the plane dropped
suddenly.
   ``It was a very abrupt action. Then we saw the flashing lights
from the other plane go by. We just couldn't believe our eyes,'' he
was quoted as saying.
