<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     11-11 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports More Than 900 Who Fled During Coup Have Returned Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 900 people who feared arrest
after a military coup in September and fled to areas controlled by
rebel groups have returned to their homes, a government spokesman
said Friday.
   Several thousand people who had participated in demonstrations
demanding democracy went to rebel-controlled zones near the border
with Thailand when Gen. Saw Maung seized power Sept. 18 and crushed
the protests.
   His government claims some of those who fled went to the rebels
to receive military training and weapons. The government urged all
of them to return and said it would act only against those who had
committed criminal offenses.
   As of Thursday 919 people, most of them students, have returned
home, government spokesman Kyaw Sann told a news briefing.
   He denied reports that large numbers of people who took part in
the anti-government demonstrations had been imprisoned.
   ``There are no political prisoners,'' he said. ``Those detained
are involved in violation of existing laws. Except for those who are
involved in serious offenses most were released after
interrogation.''
   Kyaw Sann was asked about demands by some political parties that
the nightime curfew and the ban on public demonstrations be lifted.
He said the law and order situation has improved but not enough to
remove those restrictions.
   Opposition parties also have called for the reinstatement of
government employees fired by the military government.
   Kyaw Sann said no action was taken against government workers
``for simply taking part in demonstrations. Action was taken only
against those who exceeded the permissible regulations. Most of them
were pensioned off and some dismissed.'' He did not say how many
workers had been fired.
</TEXT>
