<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TunnelExplosion     11-11 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tunnel Explosion,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tunnel Where Three Men Died Remains Closed, Investigation Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LIGHTFOOT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High levels of explosive methane gas lingered
underground Friday, hampering investigation of a sewer tunnel blast
that killed three workers.
   No one would enter the 2,000-foot tunnel until levels of methane,
a gas formed when organic materials decompose, had dissipated, said
Pat Freeman, safety director for the S.A. Healy Co.
   ``We want it completely purged,'' he said. ``We still don't know
what kind of reading you're going to get way up in the head.''
   Investigators from the Milwaukee County District Attorney's
office and the U.S. Occupational Safety and Health Administration
videotaped the site of Thursday's blast but did not enter the tunnel.
   Healy Co. is looking for a contractor to drill a hole at the head
of the tunnel, which would allow the methane to escape and could
speed up the process, Freeman said.
   ``The investigators from the DA's office do want to get down as
soon as we can get in,'' he said. Methane levels should be low
enough next week to allow investigators to enter the tunnel, Freeman
said.
   Phillip Van Kuiken, OSHA safety supervisor, declined to discuss
the investigation, as did Richard Heath, who was representing the
district attorney's office at the scene. Officials are unsure what
caused the blast.
   The explosion ripped through the tunnel at about 9 a.m. as the
three workers carried monitoring equipment to check high levels of
methane that forced workers to evacute.
   Rescue workers, who had to clear explosive fumes and remove
twisted wreckage while contending with poor lighting and knee-deep
mud, took eight hours to remove the bodies.
   Jim Rezka, project engineer, said he would favor installing
remote-controlled methane monitoring equipment that would allow
measurement of gas levels without workers having to enter the tunnel.
   ``There's always a chance of human error,'' he said. ``There'd be
a lot to be said for a (remote-controlled) monitoring system. Even
though they were following a set procedure, anything could have set
off an explosion.''
   The dead were identified as Ron Kohne, 49, tunnel superintendent
from Big Sandy, Tenn.; Tony Bell, 25, shift foreman from Sturgeon
Bay; and Rick Sochacki, 34, of Holland, Ill.
</TEXT>
