<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SewageSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0679 11-11 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sewage Spill, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0679,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massive Sewage Spill Causes Closing of Seven Miles of Beach</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 3rd graf to UPDATE with blockage
continuing, councilman demanding investigation. Picks up 4th graf:
`The Health ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of thousands of gallons of raw sewage
that spilled into a creek forced authorities to close seven miles of
beach near Marina del Rey as a health hazard.
   The spill, discovered Thursday afternoon, was caused by blockage
in a 45 inch-diameter pipe that carries raw waste to a treatment
plant. The sewage overflowed, erupting through an opening that had
been covered by a bolted plate, and ran into Ballona Creek and down
into Santa Monica Bay.
   ``We're talking minimally hundreds of thousands of gallons,
possibly millions. This is a biggie,'' said Anna Sklar of the
Department of Public Works.
   The blockage, which workers were still trying to clear late
Friday, may have been caused by failure of the brick lining of the
decades-old sewer where it crosses under the creek, she said.
   ``This is one of the worst spills we've had. It is also becoming
too frequent,'' said City Councilman Zev Yaroslavsky, who is
expected to challenge Mayor Tom Bradley for election next year.
   ``We have a sewer system we are investing a lot of money in right
now and our citizens are not getting their money's worth,'' he said.
``I'm going to ask for an investigation on Monday.''
   Ms. Sklar said sewage mainly overflowed during the morning and
evening peak-usage periods and stopped in between.
   The Health Department posted signs warning beachgoers to stay out
of the water from the Venice Pier to Grand Avenue in El Segundo, and
lifeguards said Friday that most were heeding the warnings,
including youngsters out of school for Veterans Day.
   ``There are tons of kids down here surfing, but they aren't in
the contaminated area,'' said Capt. Steve Voorhoos of the Los
Angeles County Lifeguard's South Bay headquarters. He estimated
crowds in the thousands.
   ``We're attempting to keep the kids out, but some don't hesitate
to go in. All we can do is warn them.''
   Despite sunshine and temperatures in the 70s, few would have
ventured into the chilly 59-degree water anyway, lifeguards said.
Even wetsuit-clad surfers moved into non-contaminated areas to enjoy
the 3 foot waves.
   At Venice Beach, lifeguard Lt. Randy DeGregori said: ``You don't
notice anything that you can see or smell. We haven't really had a
problem. There are lots of surfers here but they aren't in the
closed area.''
   The cause of the blockage was unknown, but vandalism was a
possibility because a sewer cover near the spot had been removed,
Ms. Sklar said. However, it also could have been popped up by the
force of the backup, she said, and authorities were still
investigating.
   ``It's clear that because of the contamination that occurred at
the beach, that the line was blocked for several hours and maybe for
a couple of days,'' she said.
   Crews thought they had cleared the blockage, but later the
problem had returned and sewage was flowing into the creek again,
Ms. Sklar said.
</TEXT>
