<2ND_LINE>AM-Human Baggage, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0736,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airline Employee Stuck In Baggage Compartment When Plane Takes Off</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to reflect that plane was a 747, compartment
was also heated, handler OK, ADDs comment from company spokesman.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Continental Airlines baggage handler stuck
in the baggage compartment of a plane took off for Chicago from
Newark International Airport on Friday, but was back on the ground
10 minutes later, police said.
   The Boeing 747 made a U-turn for an emergency landing after the
crew heard banging coming from the plane's heated, pressurized
baggage section, said Lt. Frank Kraft of the Port Authority police.
   Baggage handler Darrin Jones, 22, of Newark, got off the plane by
himself and was discharged from Elizabeth General Medical Center
after an examination. ``He was fine,'' said Doug Harris, hospital
spokesman.
   His trip on Flight 383 departed Newark at 6:09 p.m. and was back
on a Newark runway at 6:19 p.m., Kraft said.
   Ned Walker, a spokesman at Continental's Houston headquarters,
said it was the first time the carrier has inadvertently shipped a
handler. ``We will certainly look into circumstances surrounding
this isolated incident,'' he said.
   After Jones got off the plane, Flight 383 took off again for
Chicago without any problem, Walker said.
</TEXT>
