<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Salvador-RebelTruce 1stLd-Writethru a0713 11-11 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Rebel Truce, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Declare Truce for OAS Meeting In San Salvador</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout UPDATING with no response from Salvadoran
government but Salvadoran commander rejects cease-fire offer;
Salvadoran army reporting 19 rebels killed; CORRECTS spelling of
Leonel Gonzalez, sted of Lionel. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDAJOY FENLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvadoran guerrillas said Friday they will
observe a cease-fire during an Organization of American States
meeting in San Salvador next week, but an army commander rejected
the rebels' proposal.
   ``We have decided to suspend the military campaign and declare a
five-day truce during the meeting,'' said Joaquin Villalobos, a
leader of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, the
umbrella organization of leftist Salvadoran rebel groups.
   Villalobos told a news conference in Mexico City that the rebel
truce would run from 6 p.m. Sunday to 6 p.m. Friday. He also said
the rebels would respond if the army attacked.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz is scheduled to attend the
opening session of the OAS conference Monday.
   There was no immediate response from the Salvadoran government to
the rebels' statement but Col. Mauricio Vargas, speaking with
reporters in El Salvador, called the guerrillas' announcement
cynical.
   Vargas is commander of the 3rd army brigade in the eastern
province of San Miguel where the guerrillas are most active.
   ``They (the guerrillas) should not play with an entire people's
desire for pacification,'' Vargas said.
   ``Peace is not a momentary truce,'' he added. ``It should not be
manipulated on the international stage to give the impression that a
certain will exists where it does not in fact exist.''
   Vargas said he would not suspend military operations in the
eastern zone.
   ``We have not entertained the idea of interrupting the
fulfillment of our constitutional duty, which is to combat those who
are killing the people,'' he said.
   Guerrillas have increased their attacks in San Salvador, capital
of El Salvador, and security has been tightened around the city in
recent weeks.
   Villalobos and Leonel Gonzalez, another rebel leader, expressed
hope that President-elect George Bush would change U.S. policy
toward El Salvador, and condemned the military and economic policies
of Salvadoran President Jose Napoleon Duarte.
   Gonzalez proposed talks with the Salvadoran government before
scheduled elections in March and said the rebels would set no
preconditions.
   The last meeting between government and rebel representatives was
in October 1987 in San Salvador. The guerrillas have rejected the
government's demands that they first lay down their arms.
   Insurgents began fighting U.S.-backed governments eight years ago
and more than 65,000 people have been killed, most of them civilians.
   In a related development, the armed forces in San Salvador
reported that troops killed 19 guerrillas in three clashes Thursday.
It gave few details and did not mention casualties among government
forces.
   The communique said eight rebels were killed in northeastern
Morazan province, seven at a coffee plantation in the central sector
and four in the southeastern province of Usulutan.
   The Salvadoran rebels claimed they killed a policeman who was on
a bus in San Salvador. A report on the rebels' clandestine Radio
Venceremos said the policeman was killed Thursday night and added:
``The enemy is not safe anywhere.''
</TEXT>
