<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru     11-11 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>50 Wounded At Protest; French Priest Arrested Following Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Friday fired buckshot to disperse
demonstrating students, wounding 50, and a French priest was
arrested following a bombing in Lima, authorities reported.
   They said that in another development guerrillas from a small
Marxist organization seized the Lima headquarters of a Peruvian
press association and denounced the killing of a comrade who they
said was murdered by a rival faction.
   Hundreds of students at the state university in Ayacucho, 235
miles southeast of Lima, held an unauthorized street march through
the city, demanding increased government financial support for the
school, police said.
   School officials said 50 demonstrators were wounded when police
opened fire with buckshot to scatter the students. Police said three
policemen were injured in scuffles.
   Authorities said members of the Maoist Shining Path guerrilla
group, Peru's largest and most violent rebel organization,
infiltrated the march and set off two bombs in the city.
   Ayacucho is the birthplace and stronghold of the Shining Path
rebels, whose eight-year fight to gain control has taken more than
12,000 lives, according to government figures.
   In Lima, police Gen. Fernando Reyes said the Rev. Jean Marin
Mondet of France and three Peruvians were arrested at Marin Mondet's
Roman Catholic church after a bomb explosion there Friday.
   Reyes declined to discuss the circumstances surrounding the
blast, which caused damages but no injuries, saying it was still
under investigation.
   Literature of the pro-Cuban Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement
was found at the church, Reyes said. Marin Mondet had been arrested
on suspicion of terrorism in the early 1980s but was released for
lack of evidence, according to Reyes.
   Members of the Journalists Association of Peru said eight armed
members of the Revolutionary Leftist Movement seized the group's
headquarters, holding 12 journalists for 15 minutes while painting
slogans on the building's interior walls.
   The assailants condemned the Tupac Amaru band, claiming it killed
one Revolutionary Leftist member and kidnapped and tortured two
others.
   Both groups endorse Cuba-style Marxism. They had been allied from
January 1987 until the middle of this year. The Revolutionary Left
accused the Tupac Amaru movement of trying to dominate activities.
   The Tupac Amaru group began armed actions in Lima in 1984. The
Revolutionary Leftist Movement has existed since the 1960s but
rarely carries out violent attacks.
   Neither group is believed to be linked to the larger and more
violent Shining Path organization.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
