<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Nixon-Analysis 1stLd-Writethru a0693 11-11 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nixon-Analysis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0693,300</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to correct quoted number of GOP senators in
January 1981</NOTE>
<HEAD>Nixon Says GOP Strong At The Top But Weak Below</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush owes nothing to the radical right
or any other group except the voters for his victory, and his
personal triumph was at the same time a Republican Party defeat,
says Richard Nixon.
   ``The party's weakness is vividly demonstrated by its record over
the last eight years,'' Nixon wrote in the last of 12 political
columns for the Sunday Times of London, appearing this Sunday.
   ``When Reagan was inaugurated in January 1981, the Republicans
had 53 senators and 192 congressmen,'' he wrote. ``After eight years
of peace, six years of prosperity, an enormously popular president,
and two more landslide presidential victories, the GOP will have 45
senators and 172 congressmen.''
   Nixon says that Reagan had the total support of the GOP right
wing in 1980 but that Bush had ``only implacable opposition from the
radical right. Bush owes nothing to them, or indeed to any interest
group except the biggest one: the voters.''
   Although the party has in the past stood for peace, freedom,
national unity and national strength, Nixon said, in the campaign
just past ``the best argument the party seemed to be able to make
for itself this year was that Jimmy Carter wasn't one of its
card-carrying members.''
   ``It is not enough just be anti-liberal,'' he wrote.
   While Bush won 4-1 in the electoral votes, it has been largely
overlooked that Bush's margin in 11 states was three percent or less
and ``a shift of only 535,000 votes in these states would have
elected Dukakis,'' he wrote. Included among the eleven are vote-rich
Illinois, California and Pennsylvania.
   Democratic party winners of the past _ Franklin Roosevelt, Harry
Truman, John Kennedy and Lyndon Johnson _ all were domestic-policy
liberals, Nixon said, but all were credible conservatives on foreign
policy on national defense.
   Dukakis' weakness, Nixon writes, ``was that unlike the Democratic
winners in the past, he was perceived to be weak on defense and
foreign policy.''
</TEXT>
