<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--US-SovietAdventure     11-11 0147</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--US-Soviet Adventure,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet and American explorers plan joint crossing of Bering Strait.
Eds: spelling of Shparo cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and U.S. adventurers are planning to journey
from the Soviet Union to Alaska across the Bering Strait, the Soviet
Embassy reported Friday.
   It said Paul Schurke of Emily, Minn., proposed the trip to Soviet
Dmitri Shparo this summer after Shparo traveled with a
Canadian-Soviet team to the North Pole.
   The report said Schurke and Shparo plan to lead a team of up to
12 people, most of whom would be native Siberians or Alaskans.
   It said Schurke is now in Moscow planning the trip and that he
went by dog sled to the North Pole in 1986.
   The embassy news release said the journey could begin as early as
February in the Siberian city of Anadyr and end two months later in
Kotzebue, Alaska.
</TEXT>
