<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 2315EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MurderVideo     11-11 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Murder Video,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Videotape Shows Defendant's Varied Personalities</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note use of `bastard' in 7th graf, ``She ain't ..., may offend
some readers.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETH CITY, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors in a murder trial began
watching a videotape Friday in which the defendant, under hypnosis,
assumes the voice of ``Satan'' and other personalities and describes
killing his 19-year-old daughter.
   On the tape, Thomas Lee Bonney's voice took on a demonic snarl as
he was interviewed under hypnosis by a psychiatrist.
   ``You're just a mortal,'' the Chesapeake, Va., man growled,
eyebrows arched, long fingernails clicking on the tabletop. ``You
don't know nothing.''
   ``Satan'' and three other of Bonney's 10 purported personalities
revealed themselves in 23 hours of videotaped interviews with Dr.
Paul F. Dell.
   Dell, a psychiatry professor at Norfolk's Eastern Virginia
Medical School who was retained by the defense, diagnosed Bonney as
having multiple personalities.
   Superior Court Judge Paul M. Wright viewed potions of the tapes
Thursday and ruled they could be shown to the jury. Lawyers said the
presentation of the tapes could last into next week.
   Bonney, 45, is charged with the first-degree murder of his
19-year-old daughter, Kathy Carol Bonney. Her body was found last
November dumped next to the Dismal Swamp Canal, just inside North
Carolina's border with Virginia.
   She was nude and had been shot 27 times. Bonney, who could
receive the death penalty if convicted, pleaded innocent by reason
of insanity and unconciousness.
   On the tape, Bonney assumed the feeble voice of Mammy, his
long-dead maternal grandmother, and called out for Kathy Bonney.
   ``Can you hear me, Kathy?'' Mammy said. ``I'm so old, so old. But
I gotta fix supper. Maybe you'll change your mind. Eat some supper
now.''
   ``She ain't supposed to be living in here,'' Satan interrupted,
referring to Bonney's dead daughter. ``She won't be in here long,''
Satan vowed. ``She called me a bastard.
   ``The gun went off. ... She was sitting there screaming, and I
was hollerin'. And I said, `What are you gonna do?' And she said,
`I'm gonna shoot you, you bastard.'''
   ``I know everything,'' Satan said. ``I am strong. I can do what I
want to, when I want to. I control Tom. He's dumb ... a wimp ... a
goody-goody, talking that Jesus garbage all the time.''
   Suddenly Viking spoke up, a noble, friendly personality and the
first to reveal itself during Bonney's evaluation by Dell.
   ``He's gonna shoot her!'' Viking screamed excitedly, apparently
reliving the night Kathy Bonney died. ``He's gonna shoot her! No!
No! I've got to protect her! Don't shoot her! I love her.''
   Bonney seemed composed as he watched Thursday, he later was
unsteady on his feet as he left the courthouse later. Asked what he
thought of the tape, Bonney said, ``It didn't look like me. I've got
more hair than that. That wasn't me.''
   Wright's decision to allow the tapes to be shown was the second
victory in as many days for defense attorneys John W. Halstead Jr.
and John S. Morrison.
   On Wednesday, the judge excluded from evidence the most damaging
of several incriminating statements Bonney made to police about his
daughter's death. That statement was prohibited because it was not
made available to the defense until after testimony began in the
four-week-old trial.
   Kathy Bonney had argued with her father on the darkened roadside
about a love letter to a married boyfriend, whom Satan called ``that
stupid newt.'' Then, according to the Satan personality, Kathy
Bonney ``called him a bastard. She sorta goofed when she called him
that.''
   ``She thought she was talking to Tom,'' Satan said. ``But she was
talking to me.''
</TEXT>
