<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Napoleon-Auction Adv21   11-11 0767</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Napoleon-Auction, Adv 21,0785</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs Nov. 21 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Rare Napoleon Letter, Books, Manuscripts to be Auctioned</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, date of auction is Nov. 29</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rare glimpse of Napoleon Bonaparte's military
genius goes to the auction block later this month with the sale of a
handwritten letter outlining secret plans to invade England.
   Written by Napoleon on Dec. 7, 1803, to Adm. Ganteaume, the
letter details three different and daring strategies for maneuvering
60 French ships across the English Channel. In one plan, the idea
was to trick the British into thinking the vessels were on their way
to Egypt.
   ``Let us be masters of the strait for six hours and we will be
masters of the world,'' Napoleon wrote. ``I don't have to tell you
that secrecy is everything.''
   The objective was to cover his army's planned invasion from
Boulogne.
   The first two plans outlined how Napoleon wanted to assemble his
fleets at various places for the final assault from Boulogne. In the
third, a fleet at Rochefort was to leave for Toulon and wait until
an expedition left for Egypt. Then the fleet would head for Boulogne
while a fleet at Brest sailed for Iceland in the North Atlantic.
   The third plan was the most complex because moving one fleet to
Toulon and sending another toward Iceland was designed to trick
Britain's Lord Nelson into heading for Alexandria, Egypt, while
British land forces would be tied up protecting the country's
western coast against the fleet headed of Iceland.
   None of the plans was ever carried out. The invasion fleet was
repeatedly struck by storms and a major part of the fleet was
engaged in a disastrous expedition to Haiti in the Caribbean.
   The letter, nevertheless, is one of the highlights of the
auction, to be held Nov. 29 at the year-old Drouot-Montaigne auction
house off the Champs Elysees in Paris under the auspices of
auctioneers Ader-Picard-Tajan.
   Also up for auction will be 50 pages of letters by the French
novelist Stendhal written while he was following Napoleon's armies
in 1812-13. His account of the Battle of Bautzen _ ``We can see
quite well, from noon to three, all that can be seen of a battle,
namely nothing'' _ would later inspire the famous account of the
Battle of Waterloo in ``The Charterhouse of Parma.''
   In other letters, Stendhal describes the horror of the burning of
Moscow, while complaining about his empty stomach and nagging
toothache and the grossness of his compatriots.
   On Oct. 4, 1812, Stendhal wrote to his sister: ``We left the
city, illuminated by the most beautiful fire in the world. ... The
moon, I believe, shone above the fire. It was a great spectacle, but
one had to be alone to see it. This is the sad condition which
ruined for me the Russian campaign: to have been with people who
would have shrunken the coliseum and the sea of Naples.''
   Sure to delight history buffs and bibliophiles, the auction also
features rare first editions, manuscripts and letters belonging to
Jacques Guerin, one of France's leading collectors and the man who
defended the young Marcel Proust before ``Remembrance of Things
Past'' was universally acclaimed.
   Guerin's collection includes works by dozens of French authors,
including an unusually rare and precious eight-volume edition of the
works of Moliere, long considered the inventor of French high
comedy. Bound in fine, antique Moroccan leather, the books are one
of four first editions of its kind and experts say they are in
excellent condition.
   The Moliere edition dates from 1673, the year of his death, and
is thought to be a first attempt at a complete edition of his works.
   Previous sales in 1984 and 1986 of works from Guerin's extensive
collection brought record prices, said a spokesman for auctioneer
Jacques Tajan.
   ``There will be even more interest this time because of the
beauty of the books and manuscripts, their rareness and especially
the spirit that runs through them,'' Tajan said.
   Other books from Guerin's collection include King Louis XIV's
personal copy of Racine's ``Esther,'' written to celebrate the Sun
King's generosity, the queen's devotion and religious harmony in
France under his reign.
   The play appealed so much to Louis XIV that he would attend
rehearsals and follow the dialogue with his own gold and
leather-bound copy of the text.
   Other works to be auctioned include an original manuscript of
Guillaume Apollinaire's famous ``Le Pont Mirabeau,'' and works by
poets Stephane Mallarme, Paul Verlaine and Arthur Rimbaud.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Nov. 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
