<DOCNO> AP881111-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 1148EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Wales-TheValleys Adv22   11-11 0752</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wales-The Valleys, Adv 22,0775</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs Nov. 22 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Things are Looking Up in Wales' Derelict South Valleys</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLYDACH VALE, Wales (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Where ugly coal-slag heaps stood just
a few years ago, luxury homes now overlook two man-made lakes and
green hillsides in this small vale of the Rhondda Valley, once the
heart of Wales' coal-mining industry.
   Porth Decorative Products, a local company that makes Christmas
ornaments, plans to built a bigger factory on the other side of the
water.
   A site has been set aside for a school, and an application to
build a rugby field is awaiting the approval of local authorities.
   Clydach Vale, about 20 miles north of Cardiff, the Welsh capital,
is an example of how things are changing in Wales.
   ``The last five years have been nothing short of dramatic.'' said
Tony Roberts, deputy chief executive of the Rhondda Borough Council.
   Peter Walker, the British government's Welsh secretary, said:
``The valleys of the 1990s are going to be very much better, nicer,
enjoyable, lively and diverse than anything they've had this
century.''
   Coal was found in the 1800s in the more than a dozen valleys
spread over an area of about 860 square miles in south Wales and
turned the country into the energy capital of the world.
   But its cruel legacy endures, with its depressing scars.
   Welsh writer Richard Llewellyn poignantly warned of it in his
1939 classic, ``How Green Was My Valley.''
   The late Llewellyn's main character, a miner's son called Huw
Morgan, says: ``Our Valley was going black, and the slag heap had
grown so much it was halfway along to our house. Young I was and
small I was, but young or small, I knew it was wrong, and said so to
my father.''
   Today, at the floor of the valleys lie the black remains of the
coal pits, and the winding gear with its wheels and pulleys. You can
still see the railway lines snaking along the abandoned colliery
buildings. Rising upward on the steep hills are the remaining slag
heaps, their blackness visible through the grown-over grass.
   Up the hillsides climb the coal workers' sturdy, terraced houses
in inexorable rows. Many are run down, and some still have outdoor
toilets.
   Large numbers of the area's 700,000 people remain unemployed _
the Rhondda's jobless rate is 25 percent compared with the overall
Welsh rate of 10.3 percent _ largely because of the Welsh coal
industry's continuous decline for the last 60 years.
   In 1920, more than 270,000 workers were employed in hundreds of
pits in the coal industry in south Wales.
   Today, after being especially hard hit by the recession of the
early 1980s, as well as a year-long coal miners' strike in 1984,
just 11 coal mines are left, employing about 7,500 workers.
   The local people's health still suffers from a poor diet and from
having worked in the mines, and tightly knit communities remain
isolated, exacerbating their problems.
   But the transformation has indeed begun, sparked by a complex
combination of national government interventon, local government
initiatives and private enterprise.
   Walker, the Welsh secretary, this past summer launched a new,
three-year program, estimated to cost more than $885 million, to
accelerate the revival.
   The program aims to reduce unemployment by funding training,
offering grants to attract outside investment and giving assistance
to new and small-business men. It also, among other things, is
spending money to improve health services, roads, and public
buildings, the latter so that the valleys' musical heritage can
flourish.
   Already, unemployment has decreased by 13,000 people to 37,000
since January 1986, and in the past nine years, some 350
government-funded factories have been built.
   About 2,900 acres of derelict land have been reclaimed. Usable
land has been particularly valuable in the steep valleys, where it
was scarce long before slag was dumped.
   Some of the slag heaps that were removed were found to contain
combustible coal, and that was sold.
   So far in the 1980s, 45,000 homes have been improved, and private
builders have put up new ones.
   New shops are opening up and the major brewers in the area,
Whitbread and Bass, are spending millions of dollar refurbishing
their pubs.
   ``It's going to be a success,'' David Waterstone, chief executive
of the Welsh Development Agency, said about the revival. ``It's the
change of mood that is the most important thing. Once they want
things to happen, they happen.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs Nov. 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
