<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 1656EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a p AM-TVLegacy ADV14   11-11 0948</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TV Legacy, ADV 14,0967</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Nov. 14, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Campaign Aftermath: `Negative Ads Work. Use Them.'
^By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the presidential campaign entered its last
two weeks, Democratic Party Chairman Paul Kirk declared at a news
conference that ``the American people know this election belongs to
them, not to Roger Ailes.''
   True or false, it was telling evidence of the pervasive influence
exerted by the man who shaped President-elect George Bush's kinder,
gentler media image and orchestrated slashing attack commercials
against Democrat Michael Dukakis.
   The task was basic: Tear down Dukakis and build up Bush. And
experts agree, the execution was brilliant. But on the morning
after, some are concerned about the legacy left by the relentless
attack strategy.
   ``The Bush campaign has been rewarded with the White House for
the most negative broadcast campaign in the last 30 years,'' said
Kathleen Hall Jamieson, a political communications expert at the
University of Texas.
   ``The lesson is clear,'' added Larry Sabato, an elections
specialist at the University of Virginia. ``Negative ads work. Use
them.''
   The two academics said a greater proportion of the candidates'
advertising was negative and the attack spots were on the air for
longer than ever before in a presidential campaign.
   ``Candidates don't bother with the positive phase anymore,''
Sabato said. ``They never go completely positive either at the
beginning or the end.''
   Bush's ads, reflecting his campaign themes and news coverage,
lashed out at the Massachusetts governor on everything from
pollution in Boston Harbor and problems in a state prison furlough
program to Dukakis' stands on defense and the death penalty.
   Jamieson said voter savvy, news coverage and opponent
counter-attacks generally are sufficient to check the impact of
false, distorted or misleading political advertising.
   ``This year has made it very clear that the existing protections
only work if the other side is equally competent in its use of
advertising and debates and if the press does its job very, very
well,'' she said. ``Dukakis didn't respond in ads. He didn't respond
in debates. This year, until the last two and a half weeks, the
press was expected to do it alone. And the press alone can't do it.''
   Dozens of media professionals offered reams of advice to Dukakis
over the course of his campaign. Early in the game, several
suggested that he might capitalize on ``positive curiosity'' by
starting his TV campaign right after the convention in July. He
waited until September, consequently losing a chance to define
himself before the Bush onslaught.
   Others pleaded with Dukakis to take a dramatic step to seize
control of the campaign agenda _ in the second debate, for example,
ask Bush to agree to a moratorium on negative ads or challenge him
to a weekly man-to-man debate until the election. He didn't, and by
virtually all accounts lost the debate.
   Most advertising ideas never made it as far as film or videotape.
Hundreds of scripts were received, and hundreds were shelved. And
unlike Ailes, an inner-circle strategist for Bush from the outset,
no Democratic media expert was let into the Dukakis loop.
   ``We were in another room. We weren't working together,'' said
Theodore Voss, a New York advertising consultant who helped recruit
talent for the campaign. Furthermore, the ad department was ruled by
a group of high-level campaign officials that one insider likened to
a jury needing a 12-0 vote to make any decision.
   In short, Dukakis sorely needed a Roger Ailes.
   ``The thing that was wrong was not having a strong advertising
director to set direction, to motivate and to say yes or no,'' Voss
said. ``There's no question in my mind that the ads could have been
superb had there been better organization.''
   Hoping to break through the inertia and bureaucracy, the
Sawyer-Miller Group in New York took to writing, producing and
paying for Dukakis spots on its own on the chance they might be used.
   The tactic worked in some instances, but the group struck out
with what might have been a key environmental ad _ a hard-hitting,
lightning-fast response to Bush's famous Boston Harbor attack ad
that was finished and shipped the same day the Bush spot first
aired. It was never used.
   When the national Dukakis campaign finally went negative, it
focused for a long time on the Dan Quayle veep selection and the
``packaging of George Bush.'' Neither message had the gut-level
appeal of crime or militarism or patriotism or clean water, the hot
buttons pushed so skillfully by Bush and Ailes.
   Ailes had a few things going for him in addition to the
ineptitude of the Dukakis ad campaign. Republicans and some
Democrats cite peace, prosperity and other successes of the Reagan
years. Scott Miller, of Sawyer-Miller, said Bush's unformed public
image was another advantage.
   ``What Roger had to work with was an advertising man's dream _ a
product without a label on it, that he could define and shape pretty
much the way he wanted,'' he said. ``I don't believe there's another
such candidate on the national scene in either party.''
   Kirk and others have denounced Ailes as the dark genius behind
Bush's airwaves assault, but Miller defended his GOP compatriot and
said the ultimate responsibility for questionable Bush tactics lies
with Bush.
   ``It's not up to Roger Ailes to make the decision that he's
asking the candidate to say things that contradict his values or
positions or ethics. It's up to the candidate to say `that's not me'
or `I won't do that,''' Miller said. ``Roger did what he was paid to
do and he did an excellent job.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Nov. 14</NOTE>
