<2ND_LINE>BC-Ticker Talk, ADV 14,0679</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Nov. 14</NOTE>
<HEAD>Now Is A Bad Time For Weak Hearts To Buy _ Or Sell _ Insurance
Stocks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For small investors, the best thing to do about
the turmoil in the California insurance industry is to sit still. At
least for now.
   The outcome of the battle over the rate-reducing Proposition 103
in California is too uncertain to permit informed speculation about
which way the stocks of the insurers are headed, analysts say.
   ``Our strategy right now is if you own, do nothing. There will be
better opportunities later on the speculative side,'' said Carol
Manning, an analyst for Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   ``The uncertainty is so strong that you can't assess who
ultimately will be most adversely affected. You also cannot at this
point in time assess the companies that will take advantage of
whatever opportunities will develop from the change in the law,''
Ms. Manning said.
   ``Once we begin to know what rules will prevail, then you can
begin to make assessments as to what companies will be either
adversely or positively affected,'' she said.
   Proposition 103, which was approved by California voters this
past week, requires an immediate reduction of at least 20 percent in
property and casualty insurance rates, including auto rates,
throughout the state.
   At first it would seem that such a proposition would knock the
legs out from under the stocks of companies that do a lot of
business in California. That has not happened, for two reasons:
   1. Passage of Prop 103 was widely expected, and almost anyone who
wanted to sell did so well in advance.
   2. Because of legal challenges and action in the state
legislature, Prop 103 may never go into effect, although some kind
of rate relief is almost certain.
   Consider Mercury General Corp., a Los Angeles-based auto insurer
that has publicly said that Proposition 103, if it took effect,
would force the company out of business.
   So what happened on Tuesday, when California voters trooped to
the polls to pass the proposition? The stock rose 50 cents a share
in over-the-counter trading.
   The stock backed off 12{ cents a share on Wednesday. But it shot
up $1.12{ to $14.62{ on Thursday, after the California Supreme Court
temporarily stayed the proposition to allow time for a review of its
constitutionality.
   In short, an investor who got cold feet and sold at Monday's
closing price would have missed out on an 11 percent profit in just
three days. Anyone who wanted to get out should have done so back in
early 1987, when Mercury General touched $25 a share.
   Besides Mercury General, other insurers who get the bulk of their
revenue from the California market include 20th Century Industries
Inc. and Zenith National Insurance Corp.
   Fireman's Fund Insurance Cos. and Ohio Casualty Insurance Co. get
about a quarter of their revenue from California, Ms. Manning
estimates.
   At the other extreme is U.S. Fidelity & Guaranty Co. _ known as
USF&G _ which counts on California for less than 5 percent of its
premiums. The slight exposure to California is one reason Ms.
Manning recommends the stock.
   Most analysts say voters in other states will not rush to enact
their own Proposition 103s when they see the turmoil generated by
California's, including the number of insurers that say they will
stop doing business in the state.
   For the insurance companies, the ideal solution would be
legislative and judicial reforms that would discourage frivolous
litigation and fat jury awards. With reforms in place, they could
afford to roll back rates and still stay in business.
   ``What happens from here is the $64 question,'' said John Snyder,
an assistant vice president at Firemark Insurance Research, an
investment banking and research firm in Parsippany, N.J.
   ``It's a very sensitive time for the stocks,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday editions, Nov. 14</NOTE>
