<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0516</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale price inflation slowed to zero last
month as food costs dropped for the first time since February, the
Labor Department says.
   The drop in food prices, 0.1 percent at the wholesale level,
reflects an easing of the effects of the summer drought, analysts
said Thursday.
   Including energy and other products, wholesale prices overall are
only 2.9 percent higher than a year ago. Consumer prices have risen
about 4.5 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration is projecting that
the federal budget deficit in fiscal 1990 deficit will be $132
billion, up $21 billion from its forecast of three months ago.
   The projection made Thursday is $32 billion over the limit set by
the Gramm-Rudman balanced-budget law. To comply with the law, the
incoming administration of president-elect George Bush will have to
come up with $32 billion in spending cuts or face the prospect of
raising taxes.
   The deficit climbed to $155.1 billion in the fiscal year ended
Sept. 30 and could top $160 billion this year, many economists say.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The booming housing market in the Northeast
cooled off in the July-September quarter, while prices of existing
homes rebounded in the industrial Midwest, a real estate trade group
says.
   The National Association of Realtors said home prices continue
soaring in California, but appreciation rates in the once red-hot
markets of New York, Boston and Hartford, Conn., were below the
national average. The median price in Philadelphia fell by 3.5
percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas has beaten out six other states in a
high-stakes race to capture the $4.4 billion superconducting super
collider, which, if Congress finds the money to build it, would be
the largest scientific instrument ever constructed.
   The announcement Thursday by Energy Department Secretary John
Herrington drew immediate protests from losing states.
   State officials had waged a years-long battle to win the giant
atom-smasher and the jobs and scientific prestige that will accrue
to the project's home state.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Supreme Court temporarily has
blocked deep cuts in auto insurance rates mandated by voters.
   A spokesman for legislative leaders said Thursday they might ask
Gov. George Deukmejian to call a special emergency session to deal
with the uproar over the rate-slashing measure.
   ``The voters have spoken and they expect the state Legislature to
implement Proposition 103,'' the leaders said in a draft of a letter
to the governor.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration has removed most of
the remaining bans imposed 47 years ago on at-home production by the
garment industry to combat exploitation of immigrants and other
low-wage workers.
   New regulations eliminating the homework prohibitions in five
clothing industries will take effect Jan. 8. However, a ban will
remain on homework in women's apparel.
   Lifting the prohibitions will give workers increased flexibility
and improve competitiveness of U.S. industries, Labor Secretary Ann
D. McLaughlin said Thursday.
</TEXT>
