<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0042EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     11-11 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Producer Prices Flat, Housing Prices Stall in Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices of wholesale goods and housing in the Northeast are
showing some temporary improvement, according to two new reports.
   The government said Thursday in its regular monthly report on
producer prices that wholesale inflation slowed to zero in October
as food costs dropped for the first time since February.
   Fresh-fruit prices fell 9.2 percent to lead a 0.1 percent decline
in food prices, reflecting an easing of the effects of the summer
drought, the Labor Department reported.
   Food prices had been climbing at an annual rate of 8 percent
before the reversal, which appeared to buck the latest trend of
government reports showing strong growth in the economy.
   But analysts cautioned against reading too much into the report.
They said consumers can expect a second round of drought-related
increases next spring when shortages of meat and pork appear because
of earlier-than-normal slaughters this year.
   ``It's just temporary,'' said Michael Evans, who runs a private
economic forecasting firm in Washington. ``Next year we'll see the
lag effects of the drought and food prices will be up sharply
again.''
   Energy prices rose a slight 0.3 percent in October as a 4.6
percent increase in natural gas prices caused primarily by shortages
in the Northeast was offset by a 10.1 percent decline in home
heating oil prices and no change in gasoline prices.
   The housing market report from the National Association of
Realtors said home prices continue soaring in California, but
appreciation rates in the once red-hot markets of New York, Boston
and Hartford, Conn., were below the national average in the third
quarter. The median price in Philadelphia actually fell by 3.5
percent.
   Home prices in the New York metropolitan area, including Long
Island and northern New Jersey, rose to $192,600 in the quarter, up
1.2 percent from the same period a year earlier.
   Prices were up 1.0 percent in Boston to a median of $184,100,
meaning half of the homes sold for more and half for less.
   Nationally, the third-quarter median resale price for
single-family homes was $90,200, up 3.9 percent from a year earlier.
   The financial markets showed little change Thursday, but worries
persisted about the dollar and how President-elect George Bush will
deal with the U.S. trade and budget deficits.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which had fallen
9.25 points Wednesday after Bush's victory, declined 3.55 to close
at 2,114.69.
   The dollar finished unchanged against the Japanese yen but lower
against other major currencies in foreign exchange trading.
   Bond prices, which had been hurt by the dollar's recent weakness,
improved as rumors surfaced late in the day that the central banks
of the major industrial powers might increase their support for the
dollar by coordinating their purchases of the currency on the open
market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
