<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Auction,0129</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cash Management Bills Yield 8.07 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department has sold 37-day cash
management bills at an average discount rate of 8.07 percent.
   The discount rate understates the actual return to investors:
8.25 percent with a $10,000 bill selling for $9,917.10. A total of
$11.03 billion in bills were sold out of bids totaling $48.66
billion. The bills sold Thursday will be issued Nov. 15 and repaid
Dec. 22.
   They are intended to help smooth the flow of government revenue
until the Treasury can issue $9 billion in 30-year bonds. Congress
last month passed legislation authorizing the bonds and the
department plans to auction them later this month or early in
December, after President Reagan signs the legislation.
