<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0046EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Japan-USTrade Bjt   11-11 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-US Trade, Bjt,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Growing Trade Surplus, Currency Fluctuations Await Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush may avoid the worst of the trade
friction that has plagued U.S.-Japan relations during the Reagan
administration, but the huge trade imbalance and currency
fluctuations will remain major issues in the next four years.
   Trade figures released Thursday showed Japan's surplus with the
United States declined less than expected in October, falling 3
percent to $4.83 billion from $4.98 billion a year earlier. It was
the 10th straight monthly decline.
   Japan's overall trade surplus rose 13 percent to $7.69 billion
from $8.85 billion a year earlier.
   October's marginal decline in the bilateral trade surplus is an
indication the trade imbalance is proving more stubborn than had
been expected, said Peter Morgan, chief economist at Barclays de
Zoete Wedd Securities Japan Ltd.
   ``There's some question of how sustainable the decline is. We
were actually looking for a faster rate of improvement, but it's not
coming through,'' Morgan said.
   Although lower oil prices are a major factor depressing growth in
the value of Japan's imports and hence contributing to the
ballooning trade surplus, overall imports are weak relative to
Japan's strong domestic economic growth.
   If the U.S. trade deficit does not shrink quickly enough, there
will be heavy pressure in the United States to drive the dollar down
further against the Japanese yen and West German mark, Morgan said.
   Japan has successfully weathered retaliatory U.S. trade sanctions
and the impact of the yen's appreciation against the dollar on its
exports, fueling economic growth with domestic economic demand. But
wild fluctuations in currency exchange rates could destabilize even
the robust Japanese economy, analysts say.
   Japanese business and government officials expressed confidence
following the election that the Bush victory was a welcome sign of
continuity.
   ``We don't distinguish between Ronald Reagan and George Bush.
They are working toward this noble cause (U.S.-Japan ties) as a
team. There is no reason to think (Bush) would be acting differently
from Mr. Reagan,'' said Yukio Okamoto, director of the Foreign
Ministry's First North America Division.
   The new U.S. trade act directs the new president to restrict
imports from nations that accumulate trade surpluses because of what
he deems unfair trade practices.
   Nevertheless, Bush's support for free trade _ ``We need to
increase our exports, not shut our borders,'' he has said _ has
reassured Tokyo.
   Bush advisers have said the president-elect feels new policies
are needed to cope with changing global economic patterns.
   ``That means, with our allies, to develop a system which will
replace the kind of trade, economic and monetary system put in place
by the Bretton Woods conference (of 1944), dominated by the dollar
in the post-war world, which has collapsed...'' said Gen. Brent
Scowcroft, foreign policy adviser to the Bush campaign.
   In addition to improving trade, Japanese leaders would like to
see the United States trim its federal budget deficit.
   ``Reagan left the problem of huge fiscal and trade deficits. The
Bush administration will have to pay back his debts,'' stated an
editorial in the Yomiuri Shimbun, Japan's largest newspaper.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881111-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0047EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Time Bjt   11-11 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Time, Bjt,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Time Plans Expansion To Survive Wave of Media Consolidations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. hopes to enlarge its already
substantial entertainment and television operations and plans to
expand aggressively outside the United States to assure its place
among the global media giants in the mid-1990s.
   J. Richard Munro, chairman and chief executive, and N.J. Nicholas
Jr., president, told financial analysts Thursday that potential
acquisitions or partnerships could include movie or programming
production companies, television networks, cable operations or
publishing concerns.
   They refused to be more specific, but Munro cautioned that Time's
interest in making deals ``doesn't mean we are going to jump at
whatever junk food comes along.''
   Media analyst Peter Appert of C.J. Lawrence Morgan Grenfell said
Time appeared to be ``laying out their plans for us, but I don't
sense that anything is in fact imminent.''
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Time rose $1 a share
to $105.50.
   Munro said recent foreign takeovers of big U.S. media companies
indicate foreigners ``are playing a worldwide game'' that Americans
must join or find themselves in second place.
   Among recent buyouts were Australian-based News Corp.'s $3
billion acquisition of Triangle Publications, publisher of TV Guide,
and British publisher Robert Maxwell's $2.6 billion purchase of
Macmillan Inc.
   Munro said that by the mid-1990s, the media and entertainment
industry will be composed of a limited number of global giants.
   ``Some will be European, some Asian, the rest American ... Time
Inc. intends to be one of these companies,'' he said.
   Nicholas said Time is looking for companies with a high return
or, absent that, a major strategic benefit for Time.
   Munro said the dollar's decline has helped foreign companies bid
successfully for U.S. media concerns. He said regulatory changes
over the next three years that will permit television networks to
own cable systems and to own and syndicate their own productions
also should encourage consolidation.
   ``Every player in the media-entertainment business _ at least
every smart one _ will be trying to do the same thing: to build
enterprises that can lay off the risk of increased production costs
over as many worldwide distribution systems as possible,'' he said.
   Time, the biggest U.S. magazine publisher, already has an
interest in cable television through its 80 percent ownership of
American Television and Communications Corp. the nation's second
largest cable operator. It is involved in programming through its
Home Box Office Inc., the pay television network.
   Time reportedly was in failed merger talks earlier this year with
Warner Communications Inc., the entertainment giant with interests
in film making and cable operations.
   Both Munro and Nicholas said they could not comment on those
reports.
   Nicholas said Time had no intention of selling its Scott,
Foresman & Co. educational publishing unit, which reportedly was on
the block earlier this year. He said it offers international
expansion possibilities.
   In mid-September, Time's stock ran up sharply on speculation that
it was considering a leveraged buyout or a restructuring.
   Munro did not directly address that matter, but told the analysts
that Time's management and board ``don't regard this as just another
media company to be leveraged or dismantled in the interests of
short-term gain.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
