<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0047EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Pillsbury Bjt   11-11 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury, Bjt,0630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Judge Leaves Pillsbury Poison Pill In Place</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite court challenges in two states,
Pillsbury Co.'s ``poison pill'' continues to be a potent defense
against a $5.23 billion takeover bid from Britain's Grand
Metropolitan PLC.
   Hennepin County District Court Judge Thomas Carey on Thursday
rejected a request from dissident shareholders to block the takeover
defense and said no to their request to force Pillsbury to discuss
Grand Met's $60-a-share tender offer.
   But after hearing from the shareholders that Pillsbury's board
was engaging in ``unlawful entrenchment'' by spurning the suitor,
Carey urged the food and restaurant company to sit down and talk
with Grand Met.
   Said Larry Commers, a lawyer for Grand Met: ``It's a step in the
right direction.''
   Pillsbury stock closed up 12{ cents Thursday at $58.62{ per share
in New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Pillsbury's board of directors on Oct. 17 rejected the tender
offer as inadequate and on Monday offered shareholders the
alternative of a special dividend and stock in Burger King, which
would be spun off as a separate public company. Pillsbury Chairman
Philip Smith also said further moves to enhance shareholder value
are under consideration.
   Jack Chestnut, a lawyer representing shareholders in a
class-action suit, said the deal proposed by Pillsbury so far would
be worth only about $43 a share. Leaving the pill intact stifles
Grand Met's all-cash offer, which could be withdrawn, he said.
   ``Now is the time to put a deal on the table,'' Chestnut said.
``What harm is there, your honor, really, in forcing these two
corporate behemoths to sit down and negotiate?''
   Grand Met has said the pill makes the cost of a takeover
prohibitive and has sued in Delaware Chancery Court to have it
lifted. That request was denied Monday by retired Justice William
Duffy, who ruled that as of Oct. 17, Pillsbury's directors had not
abdicated their responsibility to shareholders in rejecting Grand
Met's offer as inadequate.
   Carey said Pillsbury's board has been diligent in its handling of
the takeover bid, but he restrained the company from raising legal
issues such as state ``tied-house'' statutes to impede possible
negotiations.
   Pillsbury has sued Grand Met in 14 states on grounds that a
takeover would violate those laws, which forbid liquor distillers
from selling alcohol at retail outlets.
   Grand Met, a liquor, gambling and franchise conglomerate, has
said it would sell the full-service restaurants owned by Pillsbury
if the takeover succeeds.
   Steven Rothschild, an attorney for Pillsbury, said Pillsbury's
board has an obligation to keep the poison pill in place in the face
of an inadequate offer. He said Grand Met's own financial advisers
have said the value of Pillsbury stock is more than $60 a share.
   Under the ``poison pill,'' or shareholders' rights plan,
Pillsbury shareholders could buy stock in the company at half price
should a hostile suitor acquire 20 percent of Pillsbury shares. For
Grand Met it could increase the cost of a takeover to $20 billion.
   Nearly 75 percent of the outstanding Pillsbury shares have been
tendered to Grand Met, which has extended the expiration date for a
second time to Nov. 14.
   Chestnut claimed Pillsbury shareholders stand to lose more than
$1 billion if Grand Met withdraws its offer.
   Separately, Pillsbury filed suit in Washington, D.C., to
invalidate a Maritime Administration decision approving the
ownership transfer to Grand Met's parent, Wendell Investment, of 61
barges and tugboats owned by a Pillsbury subsidiary.
   The suit, filed in U.S. District Court, alleged the agency
violated procedures in approving the transfer of American-owned
vessels to a foreign buyer if Wendell and Grand Met take over
Pillsbury.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
