<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AMDLayoffs     11-11 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AMD Layoffs,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AMD Announces Layoffs Amid Other Signs of Weakening Industry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Further signs of a weakening
semiconductor industry have surfaced with the announcement that
Advanced Micro Devices Inc. will lay off up to 1,000 workers because
of fewer orders from personal computer makers.
   And W.J. Sanders III, chairman and chief executive officer of
AMD, on Thursday characterized prospects for immediate improvement
in his company as bleak.
   ``Based on current order levels, we expect sales to decline in
the fourth quarter and foresee no material improvement in the
immediate future,'' Sanders said.
   The layoff announcement came on the heels of monthly figures by
the Semiconductor Industry Association showing a 21.6 percent
decline in shipments by semiconductor manufacturers worldwide to
U.S. customers in October, the biggest decline in 13 years.
   Furthermore, the association's book-to-bill ratio of 0.92 for
October, released Wednesday, was the lowest since 1986, and a 9
percent decrease from 0.97 in September.
   Industry analyst Michael Gumport of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
in New York the drop the largest montly decline on record.
   ``It's definitely heading south. It's not a very good report,''
said John Girton, vice president of research at Van Kasper & Co. in
San Francisco.
   But a number of analysts said they did not expect the industry to
go into a major tailspin.
   ``I still think we're looking at the worst of the news now,''
said Gumport.
   The high-tech industry research firm Dataquest Inc. in San Jose
recently predicted moderate industry growth in 1989 followed by
improved sales. That would follow expected industry dollar growth of
35.8 percent in 1988.
   Advanced Micro Devices, the nation's fifth-largest computer chip
maker, recently laid off 1,400 workers in Malaysia and the
Philippines after an expected summer pickup in sales failed to
materialize.
   The company announced Thursday it will cut employees from all
four of its domestic manufacturing plants, located in Sunnyvale and
Santa Clara in California and Austin and San Antonio in Texas, but
most cuts will be made in the San Francisco area, said spokesman
John Greenagel.
   The cuts will occur in areas where entire projects will be phased
out, he said.
   ``We are eliminating certain programs that are not promising...in
order to concentrate on resources and on growth markets,'' said
Greenagel, who would not comment on which programs would be cut.
   Company officials blamed the reduction on weakening demand for
integrated circuits from personal computer customers, including
Hewlett-Packard Co. and Apple Inc.
   Michael Stark, an industry analyst at Robertson, Colman &
Stephens, of San Francisco, said the layoffs indicate the company's
troubles have been compounded by its difficulty in making memory
chips with advanced manufacturing processes already mastered by
competitors.
   The company employs about 5,500 people in the Bay area and 3,000
people in Texas. Worldwide, AMD employs about 15,800 workers and is
the largest company in the world exclusively manufacturing
integrated circuits.
   During 1987, AMD recorded $997 million in sales and lost $48
million. The company recorded $53 million in profits during the
first nine months of this year, but expects to lose money during the
fourth quarter, officials said.
   The SIA's figures showed that U.S., Japanese and European chip
makers had shipped $1.02 billion in chips to U.S. customers in
October, compared to $1.3 billion in September.
   The SIA's book-to-bill ratio of 0.92 for October means that chip
makers received $92 worth of new orders from U.S. customers for
every $100 worth of chips shipped.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
