<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     11-11 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Sharply In Active European Trading, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell sharply in active European trading
today before the Bank of England reportedly stepped in to buy
dollars late in the morning. Gold prices were higher.
   The dollar fell to a 10-month low against the Japanese yen and to
five-month lows against the West German mark and the British pound
before the Bank of England reportedly started buying dollars and
selling yen on behalf of the Bank of Japan at about 11 a.m..
   Foreign exchange dealers expressed surprise that other major
European central banks had not entered the market to boost the
dollar.
   Dealers said the Japanese central bank intervened in Singapore
after the Tokyo session ended today, buying dollars after the dollar
fell below 123 yen, dealers said.
   The West German Bundesbank might wait until next week before
intervening to support the dollar, a Milan trader said. He argued
that the absence of many traders due to a holiday in several
European countries meant any dollar buying by central banks on the
open market would have less ``psychological effect.''
   However, another Milan trader said the dollar may have bottomed
out and could rebound later in Friday's session.
   ``I can't believe that the dollar can keep falling every day,''
the trader said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.40 yen to a closing 123.70 yen. Later, in London,
it fell further to 122.65 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday's
prices, included: 1.7365 West German marks, down from 1.7565; 1.4595
Swiss francs, down from 1.4765; 5.9335 French francs, down from
6.0065; 1.9615 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9825; 1,296.25 Italian
lire, down from 1,311.00; and 1.2230 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2246.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.8135 from $1.7970
Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $419 a troy ounce, down
from $419.75 bid late Thursday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a higher recommended price of $420.75.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $420.80, up from $419.70 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $3.18 to close at a bid of
$421.05.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.40 a troy
ounce, down from Thursday's $6.48.
</TEXT>
