<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 0742EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     11-11 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Soars On Tokyo Market, Hit High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices soared across the board on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange today, pushing the main price index to a record high while
the U.S. dollar hit a 10-month low against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the most widely
followed price index of the exchange, rose 323.15 points, or 1.15
percent, to close at a new high of 28,489.57. The previous record of
28,423.38 was set Aug. 5.
   The dollar closed at 123.70 yen, after opening at 123.80 yen and
moving in a narrow range of 123.63-123.88 yen. The U.S. currency had
closed in Tokyo Thursday at 124.10 yen.
   Securities dealers attributed the sharp gain on the stock market
to generally bullish market sentiments. The market is viewing lower
oil prices and the strong yen favorably, they said.
   ``Institutional investors and trust fund managers seem to start
participating in the market again,'' said Keiichi Nishida, a dealer
at Kidder Peabody's Tokyo office. ``Also the fact the we have not
heard bad news on the emperor's condition in the past three days is
helping share prices rise.''
   The condition of Japan's Emperor Hirohito, who has been bedridden
since Sept. 19, took a sudden turn for the worse Tuesday and share
prices tumbled on the Tokyo market the following day. But he has
been reported stable since then.
   On the foreign exchange market, dealers said the dollar's decline
reflects the market's general sentiment toward the currency.
   It was the lowest value for the U.S. currency against the yen
since it hit 121.65 yen Jan. 4.
   ``The dollar could have gone lower if the Bank of Japan did not
prop it up,'' said an exchange dealer at a major U.S. commercial
bank in Tokyo.
   He said the central bank intervened moderately in the market
today when the dollar was trading at around 123.70 yen. Other
dealers said the Bank of Japan's intervention was considerable, to
the tune of 400 million dollars.
   ``It is unlikely that we'll see the dollar go below 123.50 yen at
this point,'' he said.
</TEXT>
