<HEAD>DLJ Sweetens Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donaldson Lufkin & Jenrette Securities Corp.
has sweetened its bid for Allegheny International Inc. in the battle
with a New York merchant bank to buy the appliance and consumer
products maker.
   Meanwhile, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Joseph Cosetti on Thursday gave
Allegheny International's board of directors a week to choose
between the two offers. After next Thursday, creditors and
shareholders will be free to propose other rescue plans or present
other prospective buyers.
   The banker Gilliam Joseph Littlejohn & Levy of New York on Monday
proposed a leveraged buyout that includes selling the Sunbeam-Oster
appliance division, reducing Allegheny International by half to a
maker of lawn furniture, barbecue grills, electric blankets, weather
instruments and bathroom scales.
   Both proposals would raise about $700 million to pay creditors.
   The new offer by Donaldson Lufkin & Jenrette would substitute
$111 million for bonds it pledged previously to settle debts.
   Allegheny International has been reorganizing under Chapter 11 of
the bankruptcy laws since early this year.
</TEXT>
