<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Minstar-Jacobs     11-11 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Minstar-Jacobs,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stockholders OK Transaction To Take Minstar Private</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minstar Inc. stockholders have approved a plan
under which an investor group led by company chairman Irwin Jacobs
will take the firm private for $420 million.
   Under terms of the deal approved Thursday, Jacobs and his
partners will buy all of the firm's outstanding common stock for
$31.50 a share.
   A cash tender offer for about 85.7 percent of the stock was
completed in July.
   The deal represents a healthy premium for Minstar stockholders,
who saw the price of their shares decline from a high of $35 in 1986
to the mid-$20s in the past year.
   Minstar stock closed at $23 a share in over-the-counter trading
Thursday.
   Jacobs, Minstar's largest investor, will get about $77 million
from the transaction _ about $64 million in cash, $10.6 million in
debentures and $2.7 million from cashing in stock options.
   He has said it would be difficult to calculate his exact profits
on the transaction because he acquired his stock during the past
several years at varying prices.
   Jacobs will continue to be the largest shareholder in the new
private company, with about 23 percent of the stock.
   Minneapolis banker Carl Pohlad, a longtime business associate of
Jacobs, will hold an 18 percent stake, according to proxy materials
filed in connection with the deal. Pohlad also will serve on the
board of the private company, which will do business as Genmar
Industries Inc. Genmar was Minstar's boat manufacturing subsidiary.
   Minstar was formed out of the remnants of Arctic Enterprises
Inc., a snowmobile and boat company in Thief River Falls that Jacobs
acquired with Pohlad in 1977.
   Jacobs sometimes used Minstar as a vehicle for corporate
takeovers, which expanded the boat business but also put the company
into the sporting goods, energy and moving and storage businesses.
All those businesses, except for a foreign sporting goods unit
expected to be sold next year, have since been sold.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881111-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 1050EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-BeerFight     11-11 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Beer Fight,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Blocks U.S. Brewer From Selling Draught Beer in Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British brewery on Friday won a high court order
temporarily preventing U.S.-based Anchor Brewing Co. from selling a
rival brand of draught real ale in Britain.
   Cornish Brewery Co. had complained to Justice John Knox that
customers wanting their Newquay Steam Beer could be confused by the
Anchor Steam Beer produced by San Francisco-based Anchor Brewing.
   The judge granted the Cornish brewery an order preventing the
American company from selling or marketing draught Anchor Steam in
this country pending full hearing of the action being brought by
Cornish Brewery.
   Anchor Brewing has been selling bottled version in Britain since
May and was planning to introduce the keg variety.
   The judge said Cornish Brewery had, on the evidence before him,
an arguable case that drinkers wanting draught ``steam'' might be
confused by the two brands.
   But he said bottled versions of the two ales looked very
different and customers were not likely to be confused over them.
   The Cornish company's range of Newquay Steam beers were first
marketed in Britain in 1987, lawyers said. The name ``steam'' comes
from a Cornish slang word for strong lager.
   Anchor Steam was first produced in America in the last century.
The name came from the ``frothy nature'' of the drink, lawyers said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
