<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell sharply in early trading today,
pressured by weakness in the dollar and continued uncertainty about
interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials had tumbled 27.56 points
to 2,087.13 at 11 a.m. EST. The blue-chip indicator was off 14.57
points an hour earlier.
   Declining issues lead advancers about 4 to 1 on the New York
Stock Exchange, with 975 issues down, 241 up and 431 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 44.76 million shares. Traders
said activity was relatively light with many players away for
Veterans Day.
   Analysts said the stock market began selling in reaction to a
steep slide in the U.S. currency on foreign exchange markets.
   ``It just seems that there is some worry about the weakness of
the dollar and also it's still undecided this question of interest
rates,'' Eldon A. Grimm, senior vice president for Birr, Wilson & Co.
   The dollar continued to weaken in overseas trading despite
reported intervention by the central bank of Japan.
   Grimm said the weakness in stock prices also stemmed from
lingering disappointment about the market's failure to respond
positively to a George Bush presidential victory.
   ``People were waiting for a rally to sell and now they're selling
the market today,'' he said.
   The NYSE composite index was off 1.50 to 152.59. At the American
Stock Exchange, the composite index fell 1.61 to 293.02.
   Among the most actively traded issues on the NYSE, IBM was down
1| at 118[, Sears Roebuck was off ] at 41] and RJR Nabisco was
unchanged at 89].
