<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed In Cautious Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed today on
the Chicago Board of Trade in light, cautious trading in the wake of
a sharp selloff in the soybean market in the previous session.
   ``I think everybody's sitting around licking their wounds after
yesterday,'' said Jerry Gidel, a grain market analyst with the G.H.
Miller Division of LIT America Inc. in Chicago.
   Analysts said Thursday's late sell-off was not sparked by any new
supply-demand developments but was led by speculators reacting to
technical developments reflected in price charts.
   Wheat futures prices were pressured in today's session by reports
of beneficial rain in U.S. winter wheat planting areas.
   But expectations of new export business were positive factors in
both the wheat and corn markets. Especially encouraging were reports
that U.S. and Soviet trade officials had met in Washington to
discuss dates for more talks on a long-term grain sale agreement to
replace the one that expired on Sept. 30.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to 2 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.23{ a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 1 cent higher with December at $2.74{ a bushel; oats
were unchanged to 1 cent higher with December at $2.16{ a bushel;
and soybeans were 2{ cents lower to 4 cents higher with November at
$7.70{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent lower to .25 cent higher with December
at 72.97 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent to .18 cent
higher with November at 81.17 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent
lower to .23 cent higher with December at 40.70 cents a pound; and
frozen pork bellies were .35 cent to .58 cent higher with February
at 44.55 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Thursday.
</TEXT>
