<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv12-13   11-11 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 12-13,0641</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 12</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Nov. 12-13</NOTE>
<HEAD>Treasury Auction is Pleasant Surprise, But Falling Dollar Hits
Bonds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was the proverbial good news and bad news for
the edgy bond market this past week.
   The government's quarterly refunding auctions went better than
expected, with yields on 3-year and 10-year Treasury notes falling
to the lowest levels in many months. Yields move in the opposite
direction of bond prices.
   But the dollar's slide to five-month lows took a big bite out of
that benefit, by sparking fears that the Federal Reserve could nudge
interest rates higher to bolster the U.S. currency.
   ``We're seeing definitely a fear of the dollar's deterioration,''
said Jay Goldinger, a principal of Capital Insight Inc., an
investment firm in Beverly Hills, Calif.
   There was even speculation about an imminent increase in the
Fed's key discount rate, the interest it charges on loans to
financial institutions. The talk hasn't yet escalated into ``disco
fever,'' analysts say, but it makes a shaky bond market even more
jumpy.
   The market already had the jitters on account of Tuesday's
presidential election: both before and after. It was nervous before
the election because of uncertainty about the outcome, then Bush's
victory stirred up worries about how he would deal with critical
problems like the budget and trade deficits and with the
Democratic-controlled Congress.
   ``The election results are not conducive to a kinder and gentler
bond market,'' said David Hale, chief economist for Kemper Financial
Services in Chicago, paraphrasing one of Bush's campaign slogans.
Bond prices were driven lower by the prospect of political
``gridlock'' between the new Republican president and the
Democrat-majority Congress, he noted.
   The Treasury auctions were a bright spot on the otherwise bleak
landscape for the bond market.
   The three auctions, on Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday, formed
the government's latest quarterly bond sale to help finance the $2.6
trillion national debt. The issues are sold to Wall Street's biggest
brokers, who later sell them to the public in the secondary market.
   On Election Day Tuesday, the average yield on 3-year notes fell
to 8.59 percent. That was down from 8.77 percent at the last
comparable auction on Aug. 9 and was the lowest rate since 3-year
notes averaged 8.23 percent on May 10.
   The momentum was sustained on Wednesday, when 10-year notes were
sold at an average yield of 8.94 percent, down from 9.27 percent at
the last such auction on Aug. 10. Rates on 10-year notes haven't
been that low since they hit 8.21 percent on Feb. 3.
   The auction results were ``pretty decent,'' said Kevin Flanagan,
a money- market economist at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``That gave
us a little help.''
   Helping the auctions, in turn, was the absence of the Treasury's
closely watched 30-year bond.
   As was the case in last quarter's auction, the government lacked
the authority to issue any more long bonds. However, the Treasury
hopes to sell $9 billion of them later this month or in early
December after President Reagan signs an authorizing tax bill.
   Analysts point out that the absence of the long-term bond
improved the auction results because it's a high-risk issue and
difficult to adjust in front of changing economic circumstances.
   In addition, Goldinger noted, it meant there simply was ``less
paper to auction.''
   In place of the 30-year bonds, the Treasury auctioned on Thursday
37-day cash management bills. They were sold at an average discount
rate of 8.07 percent.
   The bills are intended to help smooth the flow of government
revenue until the Treasury can issue the 30-year bonds.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Nov. 12-13</NOTE>
</DOC>
