<1ST_LINE>r f AM-KodakBonus     11-11 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kodak Bonus,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plans $263 Million Bonus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. will give its 77,300
U.S. employees a share of a record $263 million company bonus next
year, company officials announced Friday.
   The company's board approved the bonus, which Kodak calls the
``wage dividend,'' on Friday. It will be paid to employees on March
10, 1989, said Kodak spokesman Ron Roberts.
   The average worker will receive several thousand dollars,
although the exact amount depends on a person's salary.
   The previous record for a Kodak bonus was $254 million, approved
in 1983 and paid in March 1984.
   The wage dividend is related to cash dividends declared on Kodak
stock. When dividends are up, so is the company bonus.
   The board declared a cash dividend Friday of 50 cents a share,
bringing the total for the year to $1.90 compared with $1.71 for the
same period last year.
   The wage dividend is a Kodak benefit established in 1912 by
company founder George Eastman, who called it ``extra pay for extra
good work.''
   It has been paid annually ever since except for 1934, a
depression year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
