<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 1708EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyCommodities Adv12-13   11-11 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Commodities, Adv 12-13,0667</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 12</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Nov. 12-13</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bush Victory Cheers Futures Industry</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: will be followed later in cycle with an ADD containing weekly
commodity price trends</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A George Bush presidency should have little impact on most
commodities markets but the futures industry as a whole is relieved
by the election results, which appear to have weakened the forces
favoring more regulation.
   Particularly cheering, according to Futures Industry Association
President John Damgard, is the likelihood that Rep. Edward Markey,
D-Mass., will get little support from the Bush administration in his
quest to place regulatory authority for stock-index futures in the
hands of the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   All futures trading currently is overseen by the Commodities
Futures Trading Commission, which is a part of the Agriculture
Department. Markey, who did not return calls seeking an interview
for this article, has called the CFTC ``lax'' in its regulatory
approach and described it as ``bystander'' during the October 1987
stock market crash.
   An ally of defeated Democratic presidential contender Michael
Dukakis, Markey ``may be forced to be less ambitious or voracious in
his attempts to transfer jurisdiction to the SEC by knowing that
George Bush won't be so anxious to go along with that,'' Damgard
said in a telephone interview from his Washington office.
   Stock-index futures, which are heavily traded on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange and offered on a number of other U.S. futures
exchanges, are hedging instruments that investors can use as
insurance against losses in the stock market. But some contend they
encourage reckless speculation and that they contributed to the
collapse of the stock market last year.
   Stock-index futures traders buy and sell baskets of stocks for
delivery on a future date at a specified price. Because they are
derived from the stock market, Markey and others say they should be
regulated by the SEC, which oversees stock trading.
   But futures industry leaders say the SEC does not understand the
futures business. And they say giving the agency jurisdiction over
stock-index futures would needlessly expand the federal bureaucracy.
   The futures industry says its relentless lobbying on the issue
has won them an invaluable ally in Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady, who headed the post-crash panel that recommended better
coordination of the stock and stock-index futures markets.
   ``I basically see a friend in the Treasury Department for the
futures industry,'' Damgard said.
   Futures industry leaders also say they expect Bush to retain
Wendy Gramm _ an opponent of additional regulation _ as chairwoman
of the CFTC. And there are murmurings that SEC Chairman David Ruder,
who has sought SEC jurisdiction over stock-index futures, will be
replaced.
   The issue is expected to come to a head next year when the CFTC
comes up for recertification.
   Here is how Bush's election likely will affect various
commodities markets:
   _PRECIOUS METALS: ``I think the gold market will be watching what
Bush does and how the currency markets react to it,'' said John
Norris, chief precious metals trader with Citibank in New York.
Analysts said continued weakness in the dollar could lead to higher
inflation and higher metals prices but the Federal Reserve could
counterbalance those effects by raising interest rates.
   _GRAINS AND SOYBEANS: ``Nothing,'' said Cathy Leow, vice
president of grain and soybean trading with Thomson McKinnon
Securities Inc. in New York. ``There'll be no change in policies in
the short term and so there should be no change in the market.''
   _LIVESTOCK AND MEAT: ``It doesn't really change anything,'' said
Charles Levitt, senior livestock market analyst with Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. in Chicago.
   _ENERGY: ``Very little,'' said James Ritterbusch, vice president
of trading and research with the Carson Petroleum Co., a
Chicago-area oil distributor. ``Any domestic U.S. energy policy
shifts will be easily outweighed by international factors, namely
OPEC overproduction. That's the key factor in this market at the
present time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
