<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures closed substantially
lower Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid disappointment over
the slow pace of export sales of those commodities.
   But wheat futures finished mixed amid indications of growing
foreign demand for U.S. wheat.
   Technical factors keyed to Thursday's late collapse in the
soybean and corn markets also contributed to the sell-off Friday in
those markets.
   ``We were down so much yesterday and we just saw some
follow-through from that,'' said Jon Horton, a market analyst with
Research Department Inc. in Chicago.
   Thursday's declines were said to have stemmed mainly from
bearishly interpreted price-chart formations. But some observers
said the drop in prices may have indicated that a rumored sale of 2
million metric tons of U.S. corn to the Soviet Union had not been
completed.
   That view reflected the market's disappointment that last week's
sale to the Soviets of a large amount of U.S. soybeans had not been
followed by more large Soviet purchases.
   The grain markets rallied last week in anticipation of more sales
and ``we're just coming down from that,'' Horton said.
   At the close, wheat was 3\ cents lower to 1 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.22 a bushel; corn was 5
cents lower to \ cent higher with December at $2.69{ a bushel; oats
were 2{ cents to 3} cents lower with December at $2.12 a bushel; and
soybeans were 1\ cents to 12 cents lower with November at $7.62 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
