<1ST_LINE>r f AM-USX-Coke     11-11 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USX-Coke,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Groups Fight USX Coke Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLAIRTON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increased coke production at USX Corp.'s
Clairton Works should be allowed only if the company reduces air
pollution to safe levels, two environmental groups say.
   The Residents Against Chemical Environment and the Group Against
Smog and Pollution said Thursday that USX shouldn't be allowed to
fire up two rebuilt coke batteries without first cutting emissions
from the 10 batteries now in operation.
   The two new batteries would create 175 new full-time jobs. The
batteries contain ovens to bake coal to produce coke, an ingredient
used in making steel. The Clairton Works in the nation's largest
coke plant.
   ``Certainly, a corporation with the resources of USX is capable
of making coke in a safe manner and they should be required to do
so,'' said GASP President Walter Goldburg.
   The Allegheny County Health Department said air monitoring showed
levels of fine, inhalable particles downwind from the plant exceeded
government standards on 12 occasions in the past year. Also, levels
of benzene, a toxic pollutant, have averaged nearly 10 times a
proposed state guideline for the chemical.
   Paul Masciantonio, vice president of environmental affairs for
USX's USS division, said company consultants reveal no evidence the
factory is causing health problems.
   He said the company is installing additional air pollution
controls at a cost of about $30 million under a federal court
consent decree.
   USX spokesman Thomas Ferrall said the company has spent more than
$150 million on air and water pollution controls at the plant during
the last 15 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881111-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 1611EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     11-11 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0331</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices closed sharply lower in fairly quiet
holiday trading today, pressured by a declining dollar and investor
concerns about the economy.
   Analysts said the stock market began selling early in the day in
reaction to a steep slide in the U.S. currency in foreign exchange
markets in Europe and Tokyo, despite reported intervention by the
central bank of Japan.
   The currency continued its slide in U.S. trading, pulling down
bonds and stocks.
   ``We have the dollar down big, bonds down and the (stock) market
broke 2,100,'' said Emmanuel Geronimous, a senior vice president at
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ``A general malaise continues to pervade
the market.''
   Except for the dollar, analysts said there were no pressing
factors to explain the market's sharp drop.
   ``There's no special reason for it except a number of technical
support numbers were broken. The bond market was virtually closed
because of Veterans Day,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, vice president of
A.G. Edwards & Sons Inc. ``The market is showing no respect...which
has increased the fear factor.''
   Analysts said in the post-election environment, investors had
little conviction to commit their funds in the face of mounting
questions about the future under a new president.
   Concerns about the economy, particularly the federal budget
deficit, and how the president-elect will work to solve those
problems also continued to erode investor confidence, observers said.
   But some analysts said they were surprised by the market's
weakness.
   ``There was an unusual amount of decline despite the Japanese
stock market reaching a record high,'' said Eldon A Grimm, senior
vice president, Birr, Wilson & Co.
   Grimm said that many investors were still disappointed that the
market did not rally following the victory of George Bush, the
market's choice for president.
   ``People were waiting for a rally to sell and since it didn't
come they were selling today,'' Grimm said.
</TEXT>
