<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-11 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Continues to Plunge; Gold Rises</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar continued its downward spiral Friday
after what dealers termed half-hearted central bank intervention
failed to support the currency.
   Gold prices rose. Republic National Bank of New York said gold
bullion was bid at $421.25 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up from
$418.20 late Thursday.
   In domestic dealings, the dollar finished substantially beneath
its highs for the week, reached on Tuesday. The currency stood at a
10-month low against the Japanese yen and at five-month lows against
the West German mark and British pound.
   Trading around the world was extremely thin. In the United
States, banks and government offices were closed for Veterans Day.
The financial markets were closed in France and Belgium for
Armistice Day, and in Canada, government offices and banks were shut
for Remembrance Day.
   Dealers noted that central bank intervention failed to halt the
dollar's slide downward. ``It was not enough,'' said Gary Taratunio,
a trader at Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.
   ``The whole market is waiting to test the resolve of the central
banks, and given that, unless there is strong intervention or policy
statements by the new Bush cabinet, the dollar will continue to
slide,'' Taratunio added.
   Statements made in Europe by George Gould, a U.S. Treasury
official, and U.S. Commerce Secretary William Verity indicated there
is support for the dollar at its current, depressed levels.
   Gould said in London that while the market has to seek its own
level, ``we, as a matter of policy, have no interest in seeing the
dollar lower.'' And in a West German television interview, Verity
said the currency's present level was good for the Group of Seven
industrialized nations. The G-7 nations are the United States,
Japan, West Germany, France, Britain, Italy and Canada.
   The statements gave traders further reason to sell their dollar
holdings.
   Dealers continue to focus on the nation's trade and budget
deficits. Taratunio predicted dollar-selling would subside next week
as dealers square their positions ahead of Wednesday's release of
trade deficit figures for September.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.40 yen to a closing 123.70 yen. Later in London,
it was quoted at 122.65 yen. In New York, the dollar fell to 122.70
yen, from 124.05 yen on Thursday. The dollar had finished at 125.70
on Tuesday.
   In London, the dollar fell sharply against the British pound. It
cost $1.8137 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.7970 late
Thursday. In New York it cost $1.8110 to buy one pound, more
expensive than Thursday's $1.7975.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.7355 West German marks, down from 1.7540; 1.4590 Swiss
francs, down from 1.4745; 5.9400 French francs, down from 5.9970;
1,307.00 Italian lire, unchanged, and 1.2218 Canadian dollars,
unchanged.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.7345 West German marks, down from 1.7565; 1.4553 Swiss
francs, down from 1.4765; 5.9285 French francs, down from 6.0065;
1.9551 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9825; 1,296.50 Italian lire, down
from 1,311.00, and 1.2225 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2246.
   Gold prices rose. On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold
finished at $421.60 a troy ounce, up from $419.00 on Thursday.
   In London the metal rose to a late bid price of $419.95 a troy
ounce, compared with late Thursday's $419.75. In Zurich, gold also
moved up to a late bid price of $420.20, compared with $419.70 late
Thursday. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell $3.18 to a late bid of
$421.05.
   Silver bullion fell. On the New York Comex, silver closed at
$6.389 a troy ounce, down from $6.411 on Thursday. In London the
metal was trading at a late bid price of $6.45 a troy ounce,
compared with Thursday's $6.48.
</TEXT>
