<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Southland     11-11 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Southland,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Southland Posts $46.8 Million Loss in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southland Corp. reported Friday that it lost $46.8
million in the third quarter ended Sept. 30 because of interest and
other expenses related to the leveraged buyout of the company last
December.
   Southland, the nation's largest convenience store chain, had a
net loss of $3.7 million in the same period in 1987.
   But the company stressed that different accounting systems were
used during the two periods and the figures are not directly
comparable. Southland said it earned $17.5 million in July 1987,
then lost $21.2 million in the following two months.
   Revenue in the third quarter was $2.18 billion. In the same three
months of last year, Southland's revenue was $2.14 billion.
   The company has completed a divestiture program designed to raise
capital to repay money borrowed for the buyout by its founding
family and management. Southland has sold 910 convenience stores and
has signed agreements to sell 168 more.
   ``Through early November, we have already repaid approximately
$880 million of our leveraged buyout bank debt, meeting our
principal repayment obligations on that debt up to December 1989,''
said Southland President Jere Thompson.
   In the first nine months of the year, Southland had a net loss of
$179.2 million. In 1987, the company earned $90.1 million in the
seven months before the buyout, then lost $21.2 million in the two
months afterward.
   Southland still has 7,000 7-Eleven and other convenience store
units in the United States and Canada that are supported by five
distribution centers and six food division plants. There also are
more than 5,000 7-Eleven stores operated by licensees and affiliates.
</TEXT>
