<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WPPSSTrial     11-11 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-WPPSS Trial,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snohomish Agress to WPPSS Case Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Washington utility has agreed to a
settlement for its part in the Washington Public Power Supply System
securities fraud case, leaving only three private companies as
defendants in the two-month-old trial.
   In agreeing late Thursday to settle, the Snohomish County Public
Utility District joined 14 other Washington state utilities who
reached a $226 million settlement with WPPSS bondholders last week.
   The agreement also takes Chemical Bank of New York out of the
case. Chemical, a trustee for bondholders, sued only the utilities.
A class of more than 24,000 past and present bondholders sued all
the defendants.
   U.S. District Court Judge Browning, who is presiding over the
case, is expected to sign an order Monday that will formally cut
Snohomish and Chemical Bank from the case.
   He still must hold fairness hearings on the settlements involving
Snohomish and others that were reached before the trial started. If
he rules against the settlements, the parties could end up back in
court retrying the case.
   Snohomish's action leaves three defendants _ a financial advisory
firm and two engineering companies _ in the case brought on by
WPPSS' default on $2.25 billion in municipal bonds in 1983 after the
system scrapped two unfinished nuclear power plants.
   The Snohomish settlement calls for the utility to pay $48.6
million. In turn, the plaintiffs will pay it $2.6 million to retain
the rights to about $20 million in disputed insurance claims.
   Snohomish will pay about $3.5 million for each percentage point
of its 13-percent share of the plants.
   A group of 14 other Washington state utilities settled out of
court Oct. 31 for $181 million, or about $3.7 million for each
percentage point.
   As part of that agreement, the federal Bonneville Power
Administration agreed to add $35 million and Washington state will
add $10 million subject to legislative approval.
   Settlements of about $650 million have been pledged to
bondholders by more than 100 original defendants in the case.
   WPPSS reached a settlement that requires no monetary awards.
   Paul Bernstein, another attorney for the class plaintiffs, said
the latest settlement does not affect its case against the remaining
defendants.
   The plaintiffs maintain that the defendants conspired to lie and
hide information that might have discouraged bond investors.
   Financial adviser Blyth Eastman PaineWebber Inc. faces the same
allegations as did the utilities, Bernstein said. Separate
allegations were made against the two engineering firms, Ebasco
Services Inc. and United Engineers and Contractors Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
